1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:19,000
Good morning. I'm Emilye Crosby. It's December 10th, 2015. We're at the Library of Congress with Juadine Henderson.

3
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:26,000
And this is part of the Civil Rights History Project, co-sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Civil Rights History Project.

4
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:32,000
I'm sorry, the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

5
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:37,000
And with us is John Bishop.

6
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:42,000
Can you tell us first of all just thank you for joining us and doing your view?

7
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:46,000
Can you tell us when and where you're born and about your family?

8
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:51,000
Yes, I was born in Batesville, Mississippi, Panola County.

9
00:00:51,000 --> 00:01:00,000
My parents were Lyora Morris and Hugo Henderson. We were farmers.

10
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:11,000
We had a small farm where we grew cotton, corn, okra, soybeans, so I'd be major.

11
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:21,000
And that was about it. My dad died when I was about four or five. We're not sure of all the circumstances.

12
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:29,000
So I grew up basically with my mother who was married again when I was ten. And that's when we moved to the farm.

13
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:31,000
So that's when you began farming?

14
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:34,000
Yeah. Before that did you live in town?

15
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:41,000
I lived in town but we could hire ourselves out to local farmers.

16
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:46,000
So I bought my first coat when I was five from picking cotton.

17
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:49,000
Yeah. You appreciate that coat?

18
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Oh, yes, of course. Oh, I have to count my money every day. 25 cents now.

19
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:01,000
How did you feel about picking cotton?

20
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:08,000
It was natural, normal, it was fine. We also picked pecans.

21
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:09,000
So it was good.

22
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:14,000
When your mother remarried and you moved to the farm did you family own that land?

23
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Yes.

24
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:23,000
Yes. It was 80 acres and one group of brothers owned one side of the road.

25
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:27,000
They have first cousins that another group of brothers owned the other side.

26
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:30,000
And it was called Section 7.

27
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:33,000
And we are everybody referred to it as 7.

28
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:36,000
You're going to 7?

29
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:40,000
At the time were you aware of the difference that made the only own land?

30
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:41,000
No.

31
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:42,000
Anything to do?

32
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:43,000
No, it did not.

33
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:49,000
Before we moved to the farm my mom worked in a restaurant in town.

34
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:52,000
It was called Brown's Cafe.

35
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,000
And I would go in on Saturdays to be with her.

36
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:01,000
So she allowed me to wash dishes when I went in and I had on an apron and it was all the way to the floor.

37
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:06,000
And I was curious about why we had to stay in the kitchen.

38
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:08,000
What happens outside here?

39
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:15,000
And she said, well, the next tray of glasses that you wash do not stop walking until you get out front with them.

40
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:19,000
That was my first little experience. I think I was about eight years old.

41
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:25,000
So I walked my glasses out front and looked around and went, they're just eating.

42
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:28,000
Did you think there was something really exciting?

43
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:32,000
No, I was like, oh, that's different.

44
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:35,000
Did you have any brothers and sisters?

45
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:43,000
Yes, I have two older sisters and one younger sister and a brother who is no longer here.

46
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:46,000
He died about five years ago.

47
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:51,000
What were your school's like?

48
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:56,000
Well, I started school at age three because my grandmother was the teacher.

49
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:00,000
And she was also my babysitter. So I had to go to school with her every day.

50
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:06,000
And it was a church owned. I guess it was a public school but it was run by the church somehow.

51
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:12,000
And it was one through eight grades in that one little building.

52
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,000
I think.

53
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:17,000
Yeah, it was just for community kids.

54
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:23,000
It was Olive Ray School next to Olive Ray Church.

55
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:30,000
And I went into any class I wanted to because when it was your time to go into for your class,

56
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:35,000
they would go to the front seat and I would join them.

57
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:40,000
And I had to do homework at night. So it was kind of fun.

58
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:45,000
I learned to read and write fairly early, like 3 or 4.

59
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,000
Was it hard when you were actually with your own class?

60
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:49,000
Yes, it was because I was bored.

61
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:53,000
My mother wouldn't allow me to move ahead. She wanted me with my age group.

62
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:57,000
So they were learning alphabet and I wanted to play.

63
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:00,000
So yeah, yeah, I had done that.

64
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
So that was hard. I got in trouble a lot.

65
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:08,000
I was ordered to the corner a lot. Stand in the corner, Maria.

66
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:13,000
No, this was the real public school with other people.

67
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:16,000
So when did you start going to a different public school?

68
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:18,000
Oh, and I was six.

69
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:22,000
Okay, so you went with your grandmother to her school, but you went to a different school?

70
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:25,000
A public school and I turned six, yes.

71
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:26,000
What was that school like?

72
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:32,000
Different kids from all over people to play with. It was good.

73
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:35,000
You mentioned being at the restaurant and being curious.

74
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:39,000
What are some of your memories of breaks and how you learn about it?

75
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:46,000
Well, when I started school at age six, we went to school on a farm work as truck.

76
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:52,000
A truck came by in the mornings and the man got out and put a ladder down and we climbed up.

77
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:58,000
The white kids went past us on the school bus and we yelled at each other and waved.

78
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:06,000
But also in my little neighborhood, the family across the road from us was white.

79
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:09,000
Apparently poor because they wouldn't have been there otherwise.

80
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:14,000
And we played with the kids, but one person had to look out for their father.

81
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:20,000
When we saw their father's car coming, they had to go around through the back and come go home.

82
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:23,000
And he couldn't know that they were overplaying with us.

83
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:25,000
Did you think about that at the time?

84
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:29,000
We just knew that somebody had to watch out for their father's car.

85
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:33,000
No, didn't really meet anything to me.

86
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:36,000
And then it started to meet something.

87
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:44,000
When I was working with my mother in that restaurant at age eight and seeing all the black people who came to the restaurant,

88
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:46,000
ate in the kitchen with her.

89
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:53,000
And then there were these other people and we could not see what they were doing out front and that was different.

90
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:01,000
And then of course when I was also eight, I think it was when the Emmett Till murder happened.

91
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:04,000
And my mom bought me a copy.

92
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:06,000
I think it was Look Our Life magazine.

93
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:07,000
I'm not sure.

94
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:10,000
And Jet Magazine.

95
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:13,000
And of course I knew then there was something seriously wrong out there.

96
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:14,000
I read the stories.

97
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:17,000
I cried for his parents more than him.

98
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:20,000
Thinking what would mother do if somebody did that to me.

99
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:21,000
You know?

100
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:22,000
Yeah.

101
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:29,000
So that was about eight when I really knew something was seriously wrong in the neighborhood.

102
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:32,000
When your mother gave those to you, did she talk to you about it?

103
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:34,000
No, not really.

104
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:35,000
Yeah.

105
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:36,000
No, I just read it.

106
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:37,000
Yeah.

107
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:39,000
Because I tried to read everything I could find.

108
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:40,000
And she gave me that.

109
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:41,000
I read it.

110
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:47,000
And was sad for his mom more than anything.

111
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:49,000
And we didn't discuss it.

112
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:51,000
And you didn't talk about it with other kids?

113
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:52,000
No.

114
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:53,000
Yeah.

115
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:54,000
No.

116
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:57,000
There were a lot of things that we never talked about.

117
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:58,000
You know?

118
00:07:58,000 --> 00:07:59,000
And that was one of them.

119
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:00,000
We never talked them.

120
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:01,000
And there was a meeting.

121
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:03,000
I think probably in double-acp meeting in our house.

122
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:05,000
We had two rooms.

123
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:07,000
It was a little storehouse.

124
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:08,000
It had been a store.

125
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:13,000
And we, the kitchen and the living room was where we slept.

126
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:14,000
You know?

127
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:16,000
And there was a meeting there.

128
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:17,000
And I was not allowed.

129
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:20,000
You know, I could stay in the back and do whatever I was doing.

130
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:24,000
And I found my mother's in double-acp card and said,

131
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:26,000
what is this?

132
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:27,000
What is in double-acp?

133
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,000
I didn't say in double-acp.

134
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:34,000
And she said, you must never, ever say that again.

135
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:35,000
Ever.

136
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:37,000
I was like, okay.

137
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:40,000
Whatever it is.

138
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:43,000
It must be very serious.

139
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:46,000
And we never discussed what they were talking about in the next

140
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:47,000
room.

141
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:53,000
But at church on Sundays, the minister talked about everything.

142
00:08:53,000 --> 00:09:00,000
We talked about the kids in Little Rock who had just integrated the schools there.

143
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:05,000
Voter registration things that had not really started.

144
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:10,000
I think there were two people in the county, two black people registered to vote.

145
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:15,000
And we just sort of heard that on Sundays.

146
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:22,000
There was an older minister, Reverend Middleton, God-free, that's his name.

147
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:27,000
And I hated to see him coming on Sundays because it meant we had to stay at church,

148
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:31,000
another half an hour to listen to black history.

149
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:37,000
He traveled around in a little bit up Jeep and he talked history.

150
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:39,000
And you could almost work your mouth.

151
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:44,000
He said the same thing every time we knew who Crispus Attucks was.

152
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:48,000
So you were like the black history of our culture?

153
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:50,000
Yeah, but he did it every Sunday.

154
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:53,000
Oh, no, every other Sunday because we didn't have church every Sunday.

155
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:56,000
We had Sunday school and other stuff.

156
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:59,000
So what was your church?

157
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:04,000
West Camp Missionary Baptist Church.

158
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:08,000
Initially, until my mom got married.

159
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:12,000
Was it West camp missionary where you had these Sunday schools?

160
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:15,000
I mean, it talks about black history.

161
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:20,000
Yeah, and it was one of the most active churches in the county

162
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:24,000
throughout the Civil Rights Movement.

163
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:30,000
When they would talk about voting or NAACP or any decent in church,

164
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:34,000
and black history was this part of the service or before?

165
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:36,000
It was after the service.

166
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:39,000
After you finished, you can't say that.

167
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:44,000
After they were finished with the traditional service,

168
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:47,000
and the guests will stand up and introduce themselves.

169
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:52,000
And then they talked about what was going on in other southern places,

170
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:57,000
like Clarksdale, Mississippi, Arkansas.

171
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:02,000
And we didn't talk that much about what was going on in our own town.

172
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:05,000
So what's in the news?

173
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:10,000
What was going on in the NAACP mainly was involved with.

174
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:14,000
There were a couple of brothers, CJ Williams,

175
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:17,000
and his brother were active, and Mr. Robert Miles,

176
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:22,000
of course, who stayed active, and Mr. Willie Kirkendall.

177
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:28,000
It came sort of to a head because Mr. Kirkendall's daughter,

178
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:33,000
who was younger than I am, went to town and was accused of stealing.

179
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:38,000
The sheriff brought her to a dad and said, you have to beat her.

180
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:44,000
And the child said, she didn't steal, and the dad said, I'm not beating my child.

181
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:47,000
And you didn't say no to the sheriff.

182
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:50,000
And the energy and the neighborhood changed.

183
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:55,000
I don't know how to explain that other than you knew it was really serious.

184
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:58,000
And near nightfall, you saw all of the men,

185
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:02,000
or most of the men walking down the road with their guns on their shoulders

186
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:04,000
to the Kirkendall house.

187
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:07,000
They sent the women and children away,

188
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:10,000
but then they climbed into the trees and the trucks to protect the house,

189
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:12,000
the family, so to speak.

190
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:15,000
And the Kirkendall family moved away.

191
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:17,000
I never actually saw them again.

192
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:20,000
They went to Indiana, found out later.

193
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:24,000
So you knew something was seriously wrong then.

194
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:29,000
But it wasn't the nonviolent movement stuff had not happened.

195
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:32,000
Like we will protect ourselves.

196
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:35,000
What, do you remember how old you were when this happened?

197
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:37,000
I had to be eight or nine.

198
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:41,000
It seems to me everything happened when I was eight.

199
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:42,000
I don't know.

200
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:46,000
Eight or nine, because we still lived in our little two-room house in town.

201
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:51,000
And so this would have been, so probably around 55?

202
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:53,000
Oh, way after that.

203
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:58,000
Probably later 50s, maybe early 60s.

204
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:02,000
And Mr. Kirkendall was superintendent of the Sunday school,

205
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:04,000
so everybody knew him.

206
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:07,000
Did your family talk about that one?

207
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:09,000
Oh, no. It was just my mom and me.

208
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:12,000
So no, we didn't discuss it.

209
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:16,000
Did you remember what age you were,

210
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:19,000
or how you came to understand what the NAACP was,

211
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:22,000
other than this card that you can't talk about?

212
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:26,000
I think I was probably 13.

213
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:29,000
It was after we had moved to the farm.

214
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:35,000
And Frank Smith, the SNCC person, came to town in 1962.

215
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:36,000
The Thanksgiving.

216
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:39,000
He didn't come to do movement work.

217
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:40,000
Mm-hmm.

218
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:44,000
And my cousin, he met my cousin at Rust College, Holly Springs.

219
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:49,000
And I ran up to their house across the road to hear about college.

220
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:51,000
And what you do at college in.

221
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:53,000
And there was a stranger there.

222
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:54,000
So I said, hello.

223
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:57,000
And he told me about the Civil Rights Movement.

224
00:13:57,000 --> 00:13:59,000
Now, we knew about the Freedom Rights

225
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:01,000
because it was in the newspaper.

226
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:05,000
We got the commercial appeal from Memphis.

227
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:08,000
And he actually knew people who were involved.

228
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:09,000
He was involved.

229
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:11,000
I found it fascinating.

230
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:15,000
And I talked, and we talked, then I told him that

231
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:20,000
the uncle to one of the men who killed him at Till lived in the neighborhood.

232
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:25,000
And got in the car with him and showed him the house.

233
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:26,000
You know?

234
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:27,000
And we came back home.

235
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:29,000
And then I was so excited.

236
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:33,000
I went home and mother said, you got into a stranger's car.

237
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:34,000
He's not a stranger.

238
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:37,000
He's his friend.

239
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:42,000
And I told her what he told me about black people voting.

240
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:44,000
And she had had the right to vote.

241
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:49,000
And that there are no black people in Batesville who voted.

242
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:53,000
And if they did, we could change the whole system.

243
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:56,000
And mother was looking at me like, yeah, right.

244
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:57,000
Okay.

245
00:14:57,000 --> 00:14:59,000
Go play.

246
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:02,000
Go do something else.

247
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:05,000
So that was really the beginning.

248
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:07,000
We stayed in touch with Frank.

249
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:09,000
I told all of my friends about him.

250
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:10,000
And the movement.

251
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:13,000
I think we had a meeting at my house.

252
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:16,000
But I didn't tell my mom because she would have said no.

253
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:20,000
And then I told her, you know, I was like, what are you doing?

254
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:24,000
And I told her, you know, I was like, what are you doing?

255
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:28,000
And I told her, you know, I was like, what are you doing?

256
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:30,000
And we had a meeting.

257
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:34,000
And we had, I was the pianist at church.

258
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:37,000
I played piano every Sunday at our new church.

259
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:40,000
That was Concord Missionary Baptist Church.

260
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:43,000
And I knew that the church wasn't locked.

261
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:48,000
So after the initial meeting at our house, we went to church and had a meeting.

262
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:50,000
We didn't ask anybody.

263
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:51,000
We just went.

264
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:52,000
Uh-huh.

265
00:15:52,000 --> 00:15:53,000
We took a record player.

266
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:58,000
And Frank brought with him a copy of the Freedom in the Air.

267
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:03,000
So we got to hear what Freedom Songs sound like.

268
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:05,000
Is that freedom in the air?

269
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:07,000
It was called the Albany Movement, I think.

270
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:08,000
Uh-huh.

271
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:12,000
But Bernice Johnson Reagon was definitely a singer on there.

272
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:14,000
So we could do that now.

273
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:16,000
Um, it was wonderful.

274
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:22,000
It was like, mainly you put freedom in places where Jesus had been.

275
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:24,000
That was very good.

276
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:26,000
So we knew how to do that.

277
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:31,000
Because my girlfriends and me, we are now like 13, 14.

278
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:33,000
And we could sing Freedom Songs.

279
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:34,000
And we did.

280
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:37,000
You didn't worry about messing with the church songs?

281
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:38,000
No.

282
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:39,000
I didn't.

283
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:40,000
They did.

284
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:42,000
I didn't need that.

285
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:43,000
The elders.

286
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:44,000
What was the reason?

287
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:48,000
Well, it didn't come to a head right then.

288
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:51,000
Later when the preacher finished preaching,

289
00:16:51,000 --> 00:16:55,000
and I was supposed to play Amazing Grace, I played O Freedom.

290
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:00,000
And survived.

291
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:04,000
Some people got very upset and said the child has lost her mind.

292
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:05,000
And yeah, I had.

293
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:07,000
Yeah.

294
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:13,000
So you said who you were telling us about how you played O Freedom instead of Amazing Grace?

295
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:14,000
Yes.

296
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:18,000
And then you started to say that you heard something about your mother?

297
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:19,000
Yeah.

298
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:26,000
Before that, the summer of 63, we met Frank at Thanksgiving 1962.

299
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:27,000
Okay.

300
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:33,000
And Frank, I thought as an adult, he was 19 years old, I think.

301
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:41,000
And he told us about a voter registration workshop that was going to be held in Greenwood, Mississippi.

302
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:43,000
And he wanted us to come.

303
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:45,000
Mother didn't let me have dates.

304
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:50,000
So it was like, okay, how am I going to get to this workshop?

305
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:55,000
I packed my bag and it eased it under the bed, the storage place.

306
00:17:55,000 --> 00:17:57,000
Because I was going.

307
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:00,000
I was hearing words that I'd never heard before.

308
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:02,000
But that happened in Greenwood.

309
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:05,000
After my dad's death, she didn't do anything.

310
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:08,000
She didn't make decisions for me alone.

311
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:11,000
She had a brother who she consulted.

312
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:14,000
And I wanted to go to Greenwood.

313
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:17,000
So he was a dry cleaner truck driver.

314
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:19,000
He came to our house as he did on Mondays.

315
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:21,000
And she said,

316
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:27,000
Juadine wants to go with those freedom people to Greenwood.

317
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:31,000
And he said, Jimmy's going, Jimmy was my older cousin.

318
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:33,000
She was three years older.

319
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:34,000
Free, it was freedom.

320
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:37,000
Like, oh yeah, we're going.

321
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:41,000
And he said, if anything happens and you need to come home, call somebody.

322
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:43,000
We didn't have telephones.

323
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:46,000
There was one telephone in the neighborhood.

324
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:49,000
And everybody had the number.

325
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:56,000
So if something happened and your family needed to contact you, they called that number and they would let you know.

326
00:18:56,000 --> 00:18:59,000
So we headed to Greenwood, Mississippi.

327
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:02,000
June, 1963.

328
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:05,000
It was my cousin, Jimmy.

329
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:07,000
My friend, Fay.

330
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:10,000
John Hardy.

331
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:11,000
And I think that was it.

332
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:12,000
Three of us.

333
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:16,000
And T, my cousin, John Morris, who was a college student.

334
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:19,000
Jimmy was also a college student.

335
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:21,000
And we went to Greenwood.

336
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:25,000
Very excited about being able to get away from home without your mother and all of that.

337
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:28,000
With these freedom people.

338
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:32,000
And we got to the Greenwood Snick Office.

339
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:36,000
And looked around and people were talking on the phone.

340
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:38,000
Very hushed and very serious.

341
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:43,000
And we sort of took it in and sat there and watched.

342
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:49,000
Then we were taken across the street to stay with a woman named Mama Hackman.

343
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:51,000
That was all we knew.

344
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:53,000
And everybody was very friendly.

345
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:58,000
They were kids our age, talking to us and pulling our legs a little bit too.

346
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:01,000
Because we were going to go to a mass meeting that evening.

347
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:04,000
And I didn't know mass, M-A-S-S, from mask.

348
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:05,000
M-A-S-K.

349
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:08,000
It was like, what are we supposed to do at this meeting?

350
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:13,000
And one of the girls said, you have to hold a hand with the person you're with and walk in.

351
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:14,000
Do we wear anything?

352
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:15,000
Nope.

353
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:16,000
You just go ahead.

354
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:24,000
And we went to the meeting and people could, we heard freedom sing songs.

355
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:28,000
How they were really supposed to sound in person.

356
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:30,000
At that meeting that night, it was very nice.

357
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:36,000
And younger people, you know, just a little bit older than we were singing and leading songs.

358
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:38,000
And it was very nice.

359
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:41,000
We went back to Mama Hackman's house.

360
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:43,000
I don't know where we ate.

361
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:47,000
And then the next morning we went in to the SNCC office.

362
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:50,000
And it was a very different energy.

363
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:53,000
People weren't as friendly as they had been the day before.

364
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:55,000
It was very strange.

365
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:57,000
It was like, what is going on?

366
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:00,000
We sat there and was quiet for a second or two.

367
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:02,000
And then a kid who called himself freedom.

368
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:04,000
I don't know what freedom's name was.

369
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:07,000
Came in and we said, what's going on freedom?

370
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:09,000
Why is everybody so sad?

371
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:13,000
And he said, Medgar Evans was killed last night in Jackson.

372
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:15,000
It was like, oh, oh.

373
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:16,000
We got to go home.

374
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:18,000
Jimmy said, you think we need to call daddy?

375
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:21,000
He said, no, we're here. We're staying.

376
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:25,000
And so we stayed and they told us they were going to canvas the neighborhood.

377
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:27,000
And we heard a canvassing.

378
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:29,000
No. Okay, what is that?

379
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:36,000
We're going to walk around from house to house, passing out leaflets, inviting people to a meeting.

380
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:37,000
A mass meeting.

381
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:38,000
Okay.

382
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:49,000
So we went with the local kids, walked around the neighborhood, passing out leaflets, saying there was a meeting at 11 o'clock at some church or the other.

383
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:50,000
We went.

384
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:55,000
There were more people at that church than I had ever seen gathered in one place in Batesville.

385
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:57,000
You know, it was amazing.

386
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:05,000
And people that we met had met the day before in the SNCC office were up leading songs and talking.

387
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:06,000
I don't remember what they said.

388
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:07,000
It was just the energy.

389
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:10,000
And my cousin and me tried to sing as loud as we could.

390
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:11,000
We wanted to.

391
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:14,000
Like, we know how to sing freedom songs now.

392
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:18,000
But it was talking about what was going on in Jackson.

393
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:23,000
I don't remember specifics, but being very energized by the whole thing.

394
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:28,000
We went back to the SNCC office and had workshops.

395
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:31,000
A workshop, put it over there, that is.

396
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:35,000
On filling out voter registration forms.

397
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:41,000
And at that gathering, I think I met John O'Neal, who was with the Free Southern Theater later.

398
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:48,000
Willie Peacock, who was major freedom fighter in Mississippi from Charleston.

399
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:52,000
James Peacock, his brother.

400
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:55,000
And they were talking about voter registration.

401
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:57,000
How to fill out the forms.

402
00:22:57,000 --> 00:23:02,000
And it was necessary for black people to be able to register to vote in their neighborhoods.

403
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:05,000
And how they get to elect people to office.

404
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:07,000
That was amazing to me.

405
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:10,000
And then we were saying every day.

406
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:14,000
Did you connect voting for things in your life for your community?

407
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:20,000
No, because we, I told you there were two people as far as I knew in the county who were registered voters.

408
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:25,000
I think Robert Miles, Robert Miles, and maybe Reverend Middleton.

409
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:28,000
I'm not sure of that.

410
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:31,000
When they're telling you about it and you're thinking about it and everything.

411
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:32,000
Yeah, of course.

412
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:34,000
Because are you seeing what you have?

413
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:38,000
In that context, do you think about how it might affect the New Year world?

414
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:41,000
A little bit. Well, what they were saying.

415
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:43,000
But you started thinking about it.

416
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:48,000
You haven't paid a lot of attention to elections.

417
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:51,000
You need, we need to be a part of that.

418
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:54,000
It was something you read about in school, not something you did.

419
00:23:54,000 --> 00:23:56,000
You know, not voting.

420
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:01,000
So yeah, we connected, we connected the dots a little bit.

421
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:06,000
And then interpreting a section of the Constitution.

422
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:08,000
The state constitution. Okay.

423
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:10,000
It was schoolwork.

424
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:12,000
And filling out the forms.

425
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:13,000
They were very long.

426
00:24:13,000 --> 00:24:15,000
We practiced filling them out.

427
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:17,000
People how to do it.

428
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:19,000
When we went back home.

429
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:21,000
We were only in Greenwood for a week.

430
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:26,000
I think while we were gone, and I'm not sure if this.

431
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:32,000
June Johnson, who is from Greenwood, (Fannie Lou) Hamer who is from Ruleville,

432
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:39,000
Euvester Simpson, who was from Itta Bena, I think, came up missing.

433
00:24:39,000 --> 00:24:43,000
And they sent Lawrence Guyot. off to look for them.

434
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:52,000
Eavesdropping, okay? We weren't a part of the major discussions with our kids, but it was all interesting information.

435
00:24:52,000 --> 00:25:04,000
And we had to go home after a week. And a couple of SNCC people took us back to Batesville, and we were trying to tell them about our town and what happens there.

436
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:25,000
Batesville at the time, I think, was 54% black, no black voters. And we weren't all the 3,000 people who lived in the neighborhood didn't all live next to each other. We were scattered. We were farmers. And a few people had other kinds of jobs, but very few.

437
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:30,000
Did a lot of African Americans only land in that area? Yeah, actually, yes.

438
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:42,000
Did there wasn't nearly as much sharecropping? No, there was one plantation that I knew about in our part of the county, because there was Northern Phenola County in Southern, South Phenola County.

439
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:53,000
South Phenola County people owned their land pretty well. There was a plantation, the Macmillan plantation where sharecroppers lived.

440
00:25:53,000 --> 00:26:06,000
And their little houses sat next to each other. We knew their kids, because we all went to school together. And we didn't think about them in a differently accept they lived on the plantation, on the Macmillan plantation.

441
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:15,000
It wasn't that big, you know? Now, in retrospect, it wasn't that big, it's just they didn't own their own land.

442
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:22,000
I wanted to... Is Phenola part of the Delta?

443
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:27,000
Part of it. Half of Phenola County is in the Delta, and the other half is Hill Country.

444
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:35,000
So which half is the where African Americans only land? So where is it? Split. Split.

445
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:41,000
We lived in the Delta. Yeah. Yeah.

446
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:54,000
You mentioned that while you were in Greenwood, (Fannie Lou) Hamer and doing jobs and who was a native of Greenwood, against you, that's their Simpson, and they come up and they're seen in Lawrence, he got good food.

447
00:26:54,000 --> 00:26:57,000
To look for them.

448
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:00,000
How do you find out what happened to them?

449
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:03,000
Later. We didn't find out while we were there.

450
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:05,000
How did you come to find out?

451
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:07,000
Somebody told us. I don't know.

452
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:20,000
I stayed in touch with SNCC people after that one week experience, another group of kids from my town went to Greenwood to do the voter registration workshop.

453
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:26,000
And I looked at the newspaper differently, looked for stories about people I had met, you know?

454
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:34,000
We didn't find out about Miss Hamer and June Johnson. I knew June's sister Dorothy. She was, I think, my age.

455
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:41,000
We found out later, but not from the newspaper. And I don't really remember how.

456
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:44,000
Oh, I know from the group of kids who went after we did.

457
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:46,000
Okay. You came back from the group.

458
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:50,000
How did you feel when you found that out?

459
00:27:50,000 --> 00:28:01,000
It didn't really do anything. It didn't register. It wasn't fear. It was, you know, I think that Larsky, we knew was beaten after that during that time.

460
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:09,000
I didn't really know Miss Hamer. I didn't know June. I had met her mother and her sister when I was in Greenwood.

461
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:14,000
You vest, I didn't know either. So these were strangers to me.

462
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:18,000
And there wasn't a real connection until later.

463
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:20,000
Until later, you know only men in the middle.

464
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:23,000
Yeah, yeah. Yeah, yeah. Of course.

465
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:28,000
What, what did you do when you got back from the workshop? Did you start doing movement work?

466
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:32,000
Trying. We would run around and, well, harass, I harassed my mother.

467
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:39,000
And my stepfather about registering to vote and how important it was that black people elected officials in our town.

468
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:46,000
And they sort of listened, but, you know, okay, mother said, I think those people hypnotized you.

469
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:51,000
Well, you and Greenwood, you didn't come back the same person that you were when you went.

470
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:54,000
Just like, no.

471
00:28:54,000 --> 00:29:05,000
So it was, it was trying to show people how to fill out the forms, trying to get my mother and stepfather to register to vote at least to try.

472
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:14,000
And people had meetings in the neighborhood to talk about it, not mass meetings, but a few people got together to talk about it.

473
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:22,000
And that went on. This was 63. The very next summer was the summer of 64. The summer project of all of these people came to town.

474
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:31,000
Now, I will admit on tape that I was sort of little resentful that all of these people came out to stare at these new people.

475
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:35,000
And we've been begging you to do this for a year.

476
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:42,000
So, okay, that was that. And the whole movement in Batesville changed, I think.

477
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:52,000
You had a lot more people coming together. We got to meet kids from other parts of the county who were active.

478
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:55,000
It was on, you know.

479
00:29:55,000 --> 00:30:01,000
I was in the summer project when you were working in 63 and you're trying to get people to register.

480
00:30:01,000 --> 00:30:04,000
Are there any SNCC people staying in town for hours?

481
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:09,000
No, no. Frank came back some time.

482
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:15,000
Willie Blue, who was also a SNCC organizer, came to town for a while.

483
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:22,000
The Keller came to town for a while. There was no office.

484
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:30,000
They came and lived with a family someplace, you know. Mainly Robert Miles.

485
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:34,000
Yeah, but there wasn't a SNCC office until the summer of 64.

486
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:38,000
So, were they organizing you all or were you organizing yourself?

487
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:44,000
We were both. They were organizing us and talking to us and we were organizing ourselves.

488
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:47,000
You know, we live here. We know what's going on.

489
00:30:47,000 --> 00:30:52,000
And that's basically what my mom said in 64. You can continue to do what you've been doing.

490
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:57,000
But don't hang out with these white children. They are going to leave and you're going to be here.

491
00:30:57,000 --> 00:30:59,000
Say, how? Okay.

492
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:00,000
Did that make sense to you?

493
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:02,000
No.

494
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:03,000
Did you listen to it?

495
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:10,000
No. I got in trouble because there was an office in town. I think it was co-full office by then.

496
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:13,000
Council of Federated Organizations.

497
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:17,000
And we lived 10 miles away in the country.

498
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:23,000
And we had gone out to do whatever we were doing. And by the time we got back to the office, it was late.

499
00:31:23,000 --> 00:31:25,000
And there was no ride home.

500
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:34,000
So, we had to get a ride home with a young white man from Harvard, Jeffrey "Jeff" Cowan.

501
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:38,000
And I thought, you know, mother's not going to see, she saw everything.

502
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:44,000
And Jeff dropped us off. He had a sunbeet up car. He dropped me off.

503
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:47,000
And mother had a fly swatter.

504
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:49,000
I'm 16, I think.

505
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:56,000
I'm 17, I don't know. But she hit me with the fly swatter. I told you not to ride around here with these white children.

506
00:31:56,000 --> 00:32:00,000
Like, how was I supposed to get home? 10 miles away, mother.

507
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:04,000
And she let it go. She let it go.

508
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:07,000
Worry is the word.

509
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:11,000
That was mainly it. She was worried that something would happen.

510
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:15,000
You know, nothing did. Not yet.

511
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:20,000
Did you ever have any luck getting your mother and your stepfather to register?

512
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:24,000
Yes, they registered in 1964.

513
00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:30,000
My stepfather had to interpret Section 30 of the Mississippi Constitution.

514
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:35,000
He memorized the thing. Well, he's filling out his voter registration form.

515
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:38,000
And he talked it all night long.

516
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:43,000
And they said, interpret Section 30 of the Mississippi Constitution. It said.

517
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:46,000
No, it's like...

518
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:49,000
Of course, he had had a little drink too. That helped.

519
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:54,000
But he said the whole section all night long.

520
00:32:54,000 --> 00:32:58,000
They were very proud of themselves. They both passed.

521
00:32:58,000 --> 00:33:00,000
Was it their first time out?

522
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:01,000
Yes, they did.

523
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:02,000
Did you get it?

524
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:05,000
No. If they did, they didn't tell me.

525
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:09,000
Yeah.

526
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:14,000
Tell me about some of the older people in Phenola who were involved in the movement?

527
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:20,000
That was Robert Miles. I told you he was from West Camp. Mr. C.J. Williams,

528
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:26,000
who had gone to an all black boarding school, Piney Woods,

529
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:30,000
you had gone to school there.

530
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:36,000
And his brother, Jasper, that was his name, Jasper Williams.

531
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:41,000
And there was a Robinson family. They were also West Camp people.

532
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:45,000
Pearl Robinson and her daughter Claire.

533
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:52,000
Miss Virgil Robinson, who was also from West Camp. Everybody was from West Camp.

534
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:56,000
Is that the area where people were in their own land?

535
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:58,000
People owned their own land.

536
00:33:58,000 --> 00:33:59,000
Everywhere.

537
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:01,000
All over the place. Yeah.

538
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:04,000
The minister probably helped a lot.

539
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:07,000
But you had to tuck our brothers.

540
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:12,000
And the Pinolian, the local newspaper did a feature on them a couple of years ago.

541
00:34:12,000 --> 00:34:13,000
Really?

542
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:14,000
Uh-huh.

543
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:21,000
And they were very active, but they had traced their ancestry back to Guinea.

544
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:24,000
He said he was from the Guinea tribe in Africa.

545
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:27,000
And I thought, that's not a tribe, but that's okay.

546
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:28,000
They were very active.

547
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:33,000
So they had a whole sense of self-worth, I think, the folks in Pinola County,

548
00:34:33,000 --> 00:34:35,000
the land owners.

549
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:39,000
People tried to send it because there were no high schools for black kids

550
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:41,000
until the 50s, I think.

551
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:45,000
Because my older step-sister went to Rust College High School.

552
00:34:45,000 --> 00:34:47,000
My grandmother went away to school.

553
00:34:47,000 --> 00:34:50,000
My mother stayed in eighth grade for three years because she couldn't go to high school.

554
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:51,000
You know?

555
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:55,000
So she just kept going to school and going to school in eighth grade.

556
00:34:55,000 --> 00:34:56,000
You know?

557
00:34:56,000 --> 00:34:57,000
She...

558
00:34:57,000 --> 00:34:58,000
I know people do that.

559
00:34:58,000 --> 00:34:59,000
I know kidding.

560
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:01,000
Oh, I'm glad to hear that.

561
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:05,000
Yeah, because they would have them repeat seven or eight grade a couple of times

562
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:06,000
since they're in high school.

563
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:07,000
Yeah.

564
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:10,000
And also because sometimes they wouldn't get to go the whole year.

565
00:35:10,000 --> 00:35:11,000
Yeah.

566
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:17,000
Well, we had split sessions until I graduated from high school.

567
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:19,000
So we could get out and work on the farm.

568
00:35:19,000 --> 00:35:21,000
We got out to chop cotton.

569
00:35:21,000 --> 00:35:23,000
And then we got out to pick cotton.

570
00:35:23,000 --> 00:35:26,000
All the white kids were going to school and we were out working.

571
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:27,000
You know?

572
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:29,000
Did you think about that at the time?

573
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:30,000
No.

574
00:35:30,000 --> 00:35:32,000
No, it was just normal.

575
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:33,000
It was something.

576
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:34,000
Yeah.

577
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:36,000
And we weren't our own farm, so it was different.

578
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:40,000
So did the young people in Pinola County, did you all want to get involved in direct action?

579
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:44,000
I know, in some counties, the young people got tired of all the registration.

580
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:45,000
Yeah, we did.

581
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:46,000
We got involved.

582
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:47,000
We went to them.

583
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:53,000
In 1964, I think it was, we went to the same restaurant where my mom had worked.

584
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:56,000
Mother quit her job at the restaurant saying,

585
00:35:56,000 --> 00:36:02,000
if they come out, anybody put their hands on you, I'm coming out of the kitchen with a knife.

586
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:03,000
So I'm going to quit.

587
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:08,000
And she quit and got a job in the neighborhood at the local restaurant.

588
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:09,000
So blackresser.

589
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:11,000
So you didn't get ready to go.

590
00:36:11,000 --> 00:36:14,000
If you didn't know what to expect, she had to listen to the radio for a while

591
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:17,000
to find out whether I was at school or in jail.

592
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:21,000
But we went to the restaurant where she had worked.

593
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:25,000
And I knew the waitress and the owners because my mom had worked there.

594
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:26,000
You know?

595
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:33,000
And we walked in, we had practice falling out into chairs and, you know, nonviolent workshops and covering ourselves.

596
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:36,000
And we were told not to talk.

597
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:39,000
Didn't mean that we couldn't talk through our teeth like this.

598
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:48,000
So we went to the restaurant in town.

599
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:52,000
I don't remember how many of us, maybe 14?

600
00:36:52,000 --> 00:36:53,000
Quite a few.

601
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:55,000
Was it even boys and girls?

602
00:36:55,000 --> 00:36:58,000
Mostly girls, I think they were couple of boys.

603
00:36:58,000 --> 00:37:03,000
John Hardy, junior Robinson, who was the youngest, I think he was 13-14.

604
00:37:03,000 --> 00:37:06,000
His mom was Mrs. Virgil Robinson.

605
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:08,000
Excuse me.

606
00:37:08,000 --> 00:37:18,000
We went into the restaurant and Miss Lill, the waitress who had been there when my mother worked there, walked over by us and said,

607
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:22,000
we are not drinking any cake and eating any milk in here today.

608
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:24,000
She was nervous.

609
00:37:24,000 --> 00:37:26,000
And it was like, okay.

610
00:37:26,000 --> 00:37:30,000
We sat there like we were supposed to do waiting patiently.

611
00:37:30,000 --> 00:37:33,000
And then we saw the sheriff come in.

612
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:37,000
So a girl, we're going to get it now.

613
00:37:37,000 --> 00:37:40,000
To my girlfriend, Fay, Fay, go over.

614
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:47,000
And after the sheriff came in, some farmers came in putting on their brown cotton gloves.

615
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:49,000
Oh, oh.

616
00:37:49,000 --> 00:37:50,000
Is there white farmers?

617
00:37:50,000 --> 00:37:51,000
Oh, yeah.

618
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:53,000
They're walking in and they're going behind the counter.

619
00:37:53,000 --> 00:37:59,000
We have the waitress normally is, and we are sitting there in our little booths thinking,

620
00:37:59,000 --> 00:38:02,000
I want to know what they're going to do now.

621
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:12,000
And they came in and they started grabbing the seats we were on and slinging them across the floor and we were holding on.

622
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:15,000
Like we're not falling yet.

623
00:38:15,000 --> 00:38:22,000
And then they started picking us up bodily and throwing us out into the street in front of cars or whatever.

624
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:26,000
And they took a couple of people and banged their heads together.

625
00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:29,000
And they got us all out.

626
00:38:29,000 --> 00:38:32,000
Nobody was arrested yet.

627
00:38:32,000 --> 00:38:35,000
How did you feel when you had a new co-oper this violent?

628
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:39,000
It was a little scary because I didn't know what to expect.

629
00:38:39,000 --> 00:38:41,000
You know, a little scary.

630
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:44,000
Not being super scared, but a little scared.

631
00:38:44,000 --> 00:38:48,000
And so we said there's another restaurant in town in a slunch time.

632
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:49,000
Let's go down there.

633
00:38:49,000 --> 00:38:52,000
And so off we went to the next restaurant.

634
00:38:52,000 --> 00:38:54,000
Batesville is a tiny little town.

635
00:38:54,000 --> 00:38:57,000
They aren't like big, they weren't big restaurants.

636
00:38:57,000 --> 00:39:00,000
And so we went and they locked the door.

637
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:02,000
They saw us coming.

638
00:39:02,000 --> 00:39:07,000
And the guys in the pool hall across the way came out with their pool cues.

639
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:09,000
They were like, oh they're going to be an astronaut.

640
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:10,000
They didn't.

641
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:11,000
We stood there.

642
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:14,000
And so if you go through the front door, we're going in.

643
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:17,000
And if you go to the back, we're not coming.

644
00:39:17,000 --> 00:39:18,000
So you want to go in.

645
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:20,000
You got to go through the back door.

646
00:39:20,000 --> 00:39:23,000
It turns the table so we're not feeding out of the back.

647
00:39:23,000 --> 00:39:25,000
We're in that movie.

648
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:29,000
We stood there until lunch hour was over.

649
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:31,000
And then we decided to go back to our neighborhood.

650
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:36,000
And we were walking down the road when the sheriff.

651
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:39,000
I think there were maybe three people in the sheriff's department.

652
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:44,000
Deputy said, you're under arrest.

653
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:48,000
You broke a city audience.

654
00:39:48,000 --> 00:39:50,000
And we started laughing.

655
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:52,000
Of course, we were bad kids.

656
00:39:52,000 --> 00:39:54,000
And we started singing.

657
00:39:54,000 --> 00:39:56,000
He marched us through town to the jail.

658
00:39:56,000 --> 00:39:59,000
And nobody turned me around.

659
00:39:59,000 --> 00:40:02,000
We got to keep on talking.

660
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:03,000
Walking.

661
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:06,000
No, we didn't call their names because we didn't know their names at that point.

662
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:08,000
We knew Sheriff Uppert.

663
00:40:08,000 --> 00:40:11,000
We didn't know the other people.

664
00:40:11,000 --> 00:40:14,000
We went to jail.

665
00:40:14,000 --> 00:40:19,000
And they booked us and didn't lock the door.

666
00:40:19,000 --> 00:40:22,000
He said, I'm not going to lock you up in here.

667
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:25,000
But you have to stay in the cell.

668
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:27,000
There were other prisoners in there.

669
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:30,000
So it was a good opportunity to say, you don't need to do crime.

670
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:32,000
We have other work to do out here.

671
00:40:32,000 --> 00:40:34,000
So of course, we were all over the place.

672
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:36,000
And he made us go back to the cell.

673
00:40:36,000 --> 00:40:38,000
It was kind of okay.

674
00:40:38,000 --> 00:40:40,000
Go back in there until you leave.

675
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:43,000
And then we're going back out and talk to prisoners.

676
00:40:43,000 --> 00:40:47,000
And at five o'clock, those of us who were under 18

677
00:40:47,000 --> 00:40:49,000
were told to go home.

678
00:40:49,000 --> 00:40:52,000
Anybody 18 and overhead to stay.

679
00:40:52,000 --> 00:40:54,000
So I went home.

680
00:40:54,000 --> 00:40:55,000
Walked home.

681
00:40:55,000 --> 00:40:57,000
Were you worried when you kept putting your...

682
00:40:57,000 --> 00:40:58,000
No.

683
00:40:58,000 --> 00:41:00,000
I expected it.

684
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:02,000
Yeah, that's what happens.

685
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:05,000
You know kids all over the state were going to jail.

686
00:41:05,000 --> 00:41:09,000
And so I went home.

687
00:41:09,000 --> 00:41:11,000
We went...

688
00:41:11,000 --> 00:41:12,000
I went back up.

689
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:16,000
I was headed back up to the jail the next day to take some ice water

690
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:17,000
for the kids.

691
00:41:17,000 --> 00:41:18,000
A big jar.

692
00:41:18,000 --> 00:41:21,000
And the sheriff pulled up and said, get in.

693
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:23,000
I know you're going to do something.

694
00:41:23,000 --> 00:41:26,000
And took me back to jail.

695
00:41:26,000 --> 00:41:28,000
Didn't lock up the cell.

696
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:30,000
Again, I'm roaming.

697
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:33,000
You know, having a good time, actually.

698
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:37,000
And that happened a few times.

699
00:41:37,000 --> 00:41:40,000
And then when the kids who were over 18 had to go to trial,

700
00:41:40,000 --> 00:41:44,000
the whole community turned out in Batesville.

701
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:47,000
Lots of people.

702
00:41:47,000 --> 00:41:53,000
And some local people thought they could walk through the crowd

703
00:41:53,000 --> 00:41:56,000
and hit the white kids who were there.

704
00:41:56,000 --> 00:41:59,000
I think Chris Williams was in the group.

705
00:41:59,000 --> 00:42:02,000
So when you say the white kid, you get the white volunteers.

706
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:05,000
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, I do.

707
00:42:05,000 --> 00:42:10,000
And Robert Miles, our local hero, decked him.

708
00:42:10,000 --> 00:42:13,000
The guy who was going to go through the crowd to get Chris got hit

709
00:42:13,000 --> 00:42:14,000
by Robert Miles.

710
00:42:14,000 --> 00:42:17,000
The older people didn't buy the nonviolence, okay?

711
00:42:17,000 --> 00:42:18,000
No, you hit me.

712
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:20,000
We're hitting you back.

713
00:42:20,000 --> 00:42:23,000
Anyway, so Robert Miles was arrested

714
00:42:23,000 --> 00:42:26,000
and people had to put up land to get to him.

715
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:28,000
We had a mass meeting that night.

716
00:42:28,000 --> 00:42:33,000
I think at Mount Zion Church, which is closer to town.

717
00:42:33,000 --> 00:42:39,000
And I don't remember what happened with the older kids

718
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:40,000
and when they went to court,

719
00:42:40,000 --> 00:42:44,000
but the younger ones, we had to go to juvenile court.

720
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:47,000
And the lawyers were all busy all over the state

721
00:42:47,000 --> 00:42:51,000
with other kids who had in jail for everything.

722
00:42:51,000 --> 00:42:54,000
And they told us to ask for a continuance.

723
00:42:54,000 --> 00:42:55,000
What is a continuance?

724
00:42:55,000 --> 00:42:58,000
Okay, we'll ask.

725
00:42:58,000 --> 00:43:00,000
And we did that.

726
00:43:00,000 --> 00:43:07,000
And the judge said that if we kept doing stuff like we were doing,

727
00:43:07,000 --> 00:43:09,000
we were going to have a record.

728
00:43:09,000 --> 00:43:12,000
And when freedom comes, you're going to have a criminal record.

729
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:13,000
And I'm sitting there grinning.

730
00:43:13,000 --> 00:43:15,000
As I always do, you said,

731
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:17,000
like that smile off your face.

732
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:20,000
So I wiped it off and threw it on the floor.

733
00:43:20,000 --> 00:43:22,000
And my mother looked at me like,

734
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:24,000
you better behave yourself.

735
00:43:24,000 --> 00:43:26,000
She's still worried.

736
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:27,000
Oh, yeah, she's worried.

737
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:28,000
They were both.

738
00:43:28,000 --> 00:43:30,000
My stepfather also was worried.

739
00:43:30,000 --> 00:43:31,000
That was over.

740
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:34,000
We didn't have to go back to jail for anything.

741
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:36,000
But one Saturday morning,

742
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:40,000
because we moved from the farm into town,

743
00:43:40,000 --> 00:43:44,000
got a little house, a little bigger house.

744
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:46,000
Were they still farming?

745
00:43:46,000 --> 00:43:48,000
Yeah, the farm was still there.

746
00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:51,000
The mother was working at the local of the sundry.

747
00:43:51,000 --> 00:43:54,000
Thomas Sundry in town.

748
00:43:54,000 --> 00:43:58,000
My stepfather was going back to the farm to do farming.

749
00:43:58,000 --> 00:44:02,000
I was a senior in high school by now.

750
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:05,000
But a knock came on our door one Saturday morning.

751
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:08,000
And my stepfather opened the door.

752
00:44:08,000 --> 00:44:12,000
The deputy stepped in just as I was walking out of my room.

753
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:15,000
And he said, oh, wrong house.

754
00:44:15,000 --> 00:44:17,000
And stepped back down.

755
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:18,000
And left.

756
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:19,000
And my stepfather said,

757
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:22,000
you're moving out of that room today.

758
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:25,000
And the shotguns came out.

759
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:29,000
Like he loaded the gun and put it in the corner like, oh no.

760
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:31,000
I did not get it you.

761
00:44:31,000 --> 00:44:32,000
I didn't hear.

762
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:33,000
So.

763
00:44:33,000 --> 00:44:36,000
So he assumed that the deputy was there to figure out

764
00:44:36,000 --> 00:44:37,000
where I didn't shoot?

765
00:44:37,000 --> 00:44:38,000
Yeah.

766
00:44:38,000 --> 00:44:40,000
And they would be coming to you.

767
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:41,000
Yeah.

768
00:44:41,000 --> 00:44:42,000
Yeah.

769
00:44:42,000 --> 00:44:43,000
Did you think he was, did he?

770
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:44,000
Were you worried?

771
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:45,000
No.

772
00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:47,000
I was too young and too silly to worry.

773
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:49,000
Did you think they might come?

774
00:44:49,000 --> 00:44:50,000
I didn't think about it.

775
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:51,000
I didn't think about it.

776
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:52,000
I really didn't.

777
00:44:52,000 --> 00:44:58,000
My high school principal,

778
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:01,000
who was also a family.

779
00:45:01,000 --> 00:45:05,000
After I had gone to the jail one day for something to visit

780
00:45:05,000 --> 00:45:08,000
my old friends who were 18.

781
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:12,000
And somebody shocked, fired a gun.

782
00:45:12,000 --> 00:45:14,000
And I ran back inside and said,

783
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:16,000
share a fuck with somebody just sat.

784
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:19,000
And he said, you had no business up here.

785
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:21,000
So okay.

786
00:45:21,000 --> 00:45:23,000
The guy just ran and walked down the road

787
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:26,000
and the red pick up truck and there's a guy on the back

788
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:27,000
with a gun.

789
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:29,000
And he said, you had no business up here.

790
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:30,000
Okay.

791
00:45:30,000 --> 00:45:31,000
I went home.

792
00:45:31,000 --> 00:45:33,000
And the principal of my high school said,

793
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:36,000
if we can do anything to help let you know.

794
00:45:36,000 --> 00:45:37,000
Really?

795
00:45:37,000 --> 00:45:38,000
Yeah.

796
00:45:38,000 --> 00:45:39,000
So I'm good.

797
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:40,000
I was.

798
00:45:40,000 --> 00:45:41,000
You know?

799
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:44,000
But you feel you really have support in your community?

800
00:45:44,000 --> 00:45:45,000
Yeah.

801
00:45:45,000 --> 00:45:46,000
Yeah.

802
00:45:46,000 --> 00:45:47,000
There was support in the community.

803
00:45:47,000 --> 00:45:52,000
And one of the earlier stories before the 64 summer project,

804
00:45:52,000 --> 00:45:55,000
I told you, the older people were not non-violent people.

805
00:45:55,000 --> 00:45:59,000
We were having a voter registration meeting again at West Camp.

806
00:45:59,000 --> 00:46:04,000
And they always left two people outside to guard.

807
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:07,000
And one of the men came in and said,

808
00:46:07,000 --> 00:46:11,000
two men just came down here inquiring about what we're doing.

809
00:46:11,000 --> 00:46:15,000
So I think we need to go home and get some protection.

810
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:18,000
Almost every woman in the church petted her purse.

811
00:46:18,000 --> 00:46:20,000
Got mine right here.

812
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:24,000
And the response was, carry on.

813
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:27,000
No need to leave.

814
00:46:27,000 --> 00:46:30,000
And it was just the way it was.

815
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:35,000
The women walked with pistols in their purses, even to church.

816
00:46:35,000 --> 00:46:37,000
Did you get before the movement?

817
00:46:37,000 --> 00:46:38,000
Yeah.

818
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:39,000
It's all the time.

819
00:46:39,000 --> 00:46:40,000
Yeah.

820
00:46:40,000 --> 00:46:41,000
It's in there.

821
00:46:41,000 --> 00:46:43,000
And the men didn't know it?

822
00:46:43,000 --> 00:46:45,000
They didn't tell them.

823
00:46:45,000 --> 00:46:49,000
They didn't tell them how would they know.

824
00:46:49,000 --> 00:46:51,000
They got to protect our families.

825
00:46:51,000 --> 00:46:53,000
We don't know what's going to happen.

826
00:46:53,000 --> 00:46:54,000
You know?

827
00:46:54,000 --> 00:46:56,000
Did your mom do that?

828
00:46:56,000 --> 00:46:57,000
Yeah.

829
00:46:57,000 --> 00:46:59,000
My mom was a good shot.

830
00:46:59,000 --> 00:47:00,000
Yeah.

831
00:47:00,000 --> 00:47:03,000
They didn't teach me because they didn't think I had.

832
00:47:03,000 --> 00:47:05,000
They were afraid to teach me.

833
00:47:05,000 --> 00:47:08,000
My grandfather, yeah.

834
00:47:08,000 --> 00:47:14,000
My grandfather, after I turned 18 and I had gone to the Delta to work with the farmer,

835
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:16,000
the farm workers down there said,

836
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:19,000
it's about time that you learned how to shoot.

837
00:47:19,000 --> 00:47:22,000
And he took me out and put some bottles on the fence.

838
00:47:22,000 --> 00:47:23,000
I was supposed to shoot them down.

839
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:24,000
Of course, I didn't love them.

840
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:25,000
I didn't learn.

841
00:47:25,000 --> 00:47:26,000
You never learned?

842
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:27,000
No.

843
00:47:27,000 --> 00:47:28,000
You weren't worried?

844
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:29,000
No.

845
00:47:29,000 --> 00:47:34,000
You didn't feel like you had to have your own pistol in your mouth?

846
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:35,000
I did.

847
00:47:35,000 --> 00:47:39,000
I put a pistol in my purse in the late, in 1965.

848
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:40,000
Yeah.

849
00:47:40,000 --> 00:47:42,000
But I didn't know how to shoot it.

850
00:47:42,000 --> 00:47:43,000
It was just in there.

851
00:47:43,000 --> 00:47:46,000
You were just open it by.

852
00:47:46,000 --> 00:47:48,000
Did nobody would bother me?

853
00:47:48,000 --> 00:47:49,000
Yeah.

854
00:47:49,000 --> 00:47:50,000
That's right.

855
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:51,000
I remember.

856
00:47:51,000 --> 00:47:58,000
You remember, were there any differences between the works that mandated and women did in

857
00:47:58,000 --> 00:48:04,000
the movement or the way they participated?

858
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:07,000
I don't think so.

859
00:48:07,000 --> 00:48:11,000
Not locally anyway.

860
00:48:11,000 --> 00:48:19,000
Once you got to a different, after high school, let's go back to that a little bit.

861
00:48:19,000 --> 00:48:26,000
I decided I got a scholarship and academic scholarship to Mississippi Industrial College.

862
00:48:26,000 --> 00:48:28,000
Is it a private school?

863
00:48:28,000 --> 00:48:29,000
No.

864
00:48:29,000 --> 00:48:32,000
It was a private school run by some church group or the other.

865
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:37,000
It was in Holly Springs across the road from Rust.

866
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:45,000
I just took the test because I wanted to get away from school that day, so I took the test.

867
00:48:45,000 --> 00:48:51,000
After high school and I applied, I wanted to go to Memphis State and then I heard that all

868
00:48:51,000 --> 00:48:55,000
these people had walked off plantations in the Delta.

869
00:48:55,000 --> 00:48:56,000
Farm workers.

870
00:48:56,000 --> 00:48:58,000
And that's a state of life, right?

871
00:48:58,000 --> 00:48:59,000
It probably was.

872
00:48:59,000 --> 00:49:01,000
I don't remember, but probably.

873
00:49:01,000 --> 00:49:02,000
Okay.

874
00:49:02,000 --> 00:49:06,000
All of these people had walked off plantations in the Delta.

875
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:09,000
They said 1,000 people.

876
00:49:09,000 --> 00:49:12,000
And I thought, oh, that's where I have to be.

877
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:14,000
I had no clue about anything.

878
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:15,000
I just turned 18.

879
00:49:15,000 --> 00:49:17,000
The month before I graduated.

880
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:25,000
I went to a meeting at Mary Holmes College, reconnected to some of the people I met in 63,

881
00:49:25,000 --> 00:49:29,000
and decided that I'm going to work in the movement full time.

882
00:49:29,000 --> 00:49:32,000
Didn't occur to me that you have to have money or a place to live.

883
00:49:32,000 --> 00:49:33,000
None of that.

884
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:35,000
I'm going.

885
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:42,000
So I went home from my week's meeting in Mary Holmes College and told my mother,

886
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:45,000
I'm not going to college yet.

887
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:47,000
I'm going to work in the movement.

888
00:49:47,000 --> 00:49:49,000
And she couldn't believe it.

889
00:49:49,000 --> 00:49:51,000
It's like, what do you mean?

890
00:49:51,000 --> 00:49:54,000
I'm going to work in the movement.

891
00:49:54,000 --> 00:50:00,000
There are 1,000 people walked off plantations in the Delta and I'm going to work with them.

892
00:50:00,000 --> 00:50:03,000
And so, what could she do?

893
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:10,000
My older sister came to see me and she slipped me $10.

894
00:50:10,000 --> 00:50:12,000
My bankroll.

895
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:17,000
You couldn't go to the putt, you couldn't go to the Delta with $10.

896
00:50:17,000 --> 00:50:20,000
Yeah, that was what I had, $10.

897
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:22,000
That's the only one.

898
00:50:22,000 --> 00:50:26,000
And I went to the Freedom Office.

899
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:29,000
It wasn't a sneak office, I don't think.

900
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:39,000
And I asked if anybody was driving down to Jackson and Lou Grant, who was head of the project at that time.

901
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:43,000
Yes, his name was Lewis Grant, we call them Lou.

902
00:50:43,000 --> 00:50:48,000
He was driving down, so I said, can I get a ride? I'm going to Jackson.

903
00:50:48,000 --> 00:50:50,000
I had made no connections.

904
00:50:50,000 --> 00:50:53,000
Look, I had just turned 18.

905
00:50:53,000 --> 00:50:58,000
I meant you don't get out of jail at 5 o'clock anymore.

906
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:00,000
You're now 18.

907
00:51:00,000 --> 00:51:02,000
It's a little more serious.

908
00:51:02,000 --> 00:51:09,000
So we went to Jackson to Mount Beulah, which was a conference center.

909
00:51:09,000 --> 00:51:17,000
And we were getting ready for some major demonstration that I don't think I even knew about.

910
00:51:17,000 --> 00:51:27,000
And I got a room for free, of course, and got my little blankets and sheets and went to get in my bed.

911
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:29,000
And some guy walked into the room.

912
00:51:29,000 --> 00:51:32,000
There were no locks and got into the bed over there.

913
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:34,000
And I thought, ooh, you better get out of here.

914
00:51:34,000 --> 00:51:36,000
Left my bag.

915
00:51:36,000 --> 00:51:38,000
And saw somebody walking down the hallway.

916
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:42,000
And I went into the first room I saw on my left.

917
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:47,000
And there were three old women in there from Beatsville, my hometown.

918
00:51:47,000 --> 00:51:51,000
I thought, oh my goodness, they said, girl, what are you doing here?

919
00:51:51,000 --> 00:51:53,000
Are you here for the demonstration?

920
00:51:53,000 --> 00:51:54,000
Uh-huh, yeah.

921
00:51:54,000 --> 00:51:56,000
I'm here for the demonstration.

922
00:51:56,000 --> 00:51:58,000
And they said, well, where are you staying?

923
00:51:58,000 --> 00:52:00,000
I said, I have a room up the hall.

924
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:01,000
And they said, stay with us.

925
00:52:01,000 --> 00:52:03,000
I said, okay.

926
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:04,000
Sounds good.

927
00:52:04,000 --> 00:52:05,000
Sounds good.

928
00:52:05,000 --> 00:52:09,000
So I stayed with them overnight.

929
00:52:10,000 --> 00:52:13,000
Got a ride into Jackson the next day with my little bag.

930
00:52:13,000 --> 00:52:15,000
And I didn't have my $10 anymore.

931
00:52:15,000 --> 00:52:19,000
I saw a dress that I wanted for seven, I bought it.

932
00:52:19,000 --> 00:52:25,000
Just completely a child.

933
00:52:25,000 --> 00:52:31,000
Went into Jackson to the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party office

934
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:33,000
and had my little bag with me.

935
00:52:33,000 --> 00:52:37,000
And they were canvassing about the demonstration the next day.

936
00:52:37,000 --> 00:52:38,000
And I pretended I knew the area.

937
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:40,000
I knew nothing about Jackson.

938
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:43,000
It was a city I came from a country.

939
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:48,000
So I helped somebody pass out leaflets in town

940
00:52:48,000 --> 00:52:50,000
about the demonstration the next day.

941
00:52:50,000 --> 00:52:52,000
Went back into the office.

942
00:52:52,000 --> 00:52:56,000
Everybody was gone except one other woman who was from California.

943
00:52:56,000 --> 00:52:59,000
And we were both sitting in the office on our bags.

944
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:03,000
And the last person to leave the office said, do you have someplace to stay?

945
00:53:03,000 --> 00:53:05,000
And we both went, no.

946
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:10,000
And he said, well come and stay with me.

947
00:53:10,000 --> 00:53:14,000
And so we picked up our bags and went with him.

948
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:17,000
He was living with a family in Jackson.

949
00:53:17,000 --> 00:53:19,000
And we slept there.

950
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:20,000
And left our bags.

951
00:53:20,000 --> 00:53:23,000
The next day went to the demonstration.

952
00:53:23,000 --> 00:53:27,000
Was arrested about an hour in.

953
00:53:27,000 --> 00:53:30,000
You know, maybe within the hour we were arrested.

954
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:33,000
And taken to the Jackson Fairgrounds.

955
00:53:33,000 --> 00:53:37,000
And that's where all the old women I had seen from Batesville were.

956
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:40,000
Everybody, there were about a thousand women in there.

957
00:53:40,000 --> 00:53:45,000
You know, I was in there for two weeks.

958
00:53:45,000 --> 00:53:48,000
Met new people.

959
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:53,000
We didn't have clothes.

960
00:53:53,000 --> 00:53:56,000
So somebody had a trench coat and we passed a trench coat around.

961
00:53:56,000 --> 00:53:58,000
You can go take a shower.

962
00:53:58,000 --> 00:54:02,000
You can wear a trench coat while you're taking your shower and washing your clothes.

963
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:04,000
You know, with ivory soap.

964
00:54:04,000 --> 00:54:08,000
For years I couldn't stand the smell of ivory soap because of that.

965
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:12,000
You washed your clothes, you hung them up to dry with your somebody's trench coat on.

966
00:54:12,000 --> 00:54:17,000
When they were dry, I almost dry you, put your clothes on and gave your trench coat to somebody else.

967
00:54:17,000 --> 00:54:19,000
Uh-huh, two weeks.

968
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:21,000
You never heard that story?

969
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:22,000
Two weeks.

970
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:25,000
I mean I do about people being in the fairgrounds.

971
00:54:25,000 --> 00:54:27,000
Oh, it was horrible.

972
00:54:27,000 --> 00:54:32,000
Well, they gave us mattresses to sleep on the floor.

973
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:37,000
And at five o'clock in the morning you got up and stacked your mattress against the wall.

974
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:40,000
And went outside to eat your breakfast.

975
00:54:40,000 --> 00:54:47,000
And there were fifty gallon tanks with fire under them.

976
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:53,000
And you had to wash your tray, dip it in the next one and the next one and put it down.

977
00:54:53,000 --> 00:54:59,000
And hope it didn't get so hot you couldn't hold on to it because you knew they would make you stick your hands in this boiling water.

978
00:54:59,000 --> 00:55:01,000
It was a little bit scary.

979
00:55:01,000 --> 00:55:05,000
I don't remember what we ate.

980
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:07,000
It was something terrible.

981
00:55:07,000 --> 00:55:10,000
Maybe syrup and grits.

982
00:55:10,000 --> 00:55:11,000
A biscuit and grits.

983
00:55:11,000 --> 00:55:15,000
They took all of the white women out and put them in the jail.

984
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:18,000
We stayed in the fairground.

985
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:22,000
And I remember there was one woman they didn't, they weren't sure.

986
00:55:22,000 --> 00:55:25,000
And they said, ask her if she was colored or white.

987
00:55:25,000 --> 00:55:28,000
And she said she didn't know.

988
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:33,000
And so they ended up taking her out and putting her in the jail with the white women.

989
00:55:33,000 --> 00:55:35,000
But she was local?

990
00:55:35,000 --> 00:55:40,000
No, no, she was not local.

991
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:45,000
Every day, you know your hands got kind of sore from sitting on concrete.

992
00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:50,000
You walked around and talked to people about what they were doing in their communities.

993
00:55:50,000 --> 00:55:54,000
I met a lot of folks my age.

994
00:55:54,000 --> 00:55:56,000
I think I met June in there.

995
00:55:56,000 --> 00:56:00,000
June Johnson after a couple of years, yeah, met her in the fairground.

996
00:56:00,000 --> 00:56:02,000
What did you talk about what happened with her?

997
00:56:02,000 --> 00:56:05,000
Not then, I don't think so.

998
00:56:05,000 --> 00:56:07,000
I don't remember.

999
00:56:07,000 --> 00:56:10,000
Mainly talking about what you're going to do when you get out.

1000
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:14,000
And people that you do and what your experiences were.

1001
00:56:14,000 --> 00:56:17,000
And your towns where you grew up.

1002
00:56:17,000 --> 00:56:21,000
It was, it was very good in that sense.

1003
00:56:21,000 --> 00:56:26,000
And one morning, one of the women decided she wasn't giving up a mattress.

1004
00:56:26,000 --> 00:56:29,000
She stayed on the mattress.

1005
00:56:29,000 --> 00:56:33,000
And there was a police officer that we called red.

1006
00:56:33,000 --> 00:56:35,000
I don't know what his name was.

1007
00:56:35,000 --> 00:56:39,000
And he yelled for her to get up and she refused.

1008
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:43,000
And he was going to hit her with his belly club.

1009
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:45,000
And she took the belly club.

1010
00:56:45,000 --> 00:56:48,000
And she said, I think it was a sick woman.

1011
00:56:48,000 --> 00:56:51,000
I think poor red guy, his leg broken.

1012
00:56:51,000 --> 00:56:56,000
But it was a standoff between all of these women and the police.

1013
00:56:56,000 --> 00:56:59,000
They had guns and their hands on their belly clubs.

1014
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:01,000
And we're just standing there.

1015
00:57:01,000 --> 00:57:05,000
You know, cursing, I let some of my best words in there.

1016
00:57:05,000 --> 00:57:09,000
And there was a little, I don't know what you call it,

1017
00:57:09,000 --> 00:57:12,000
a little line between us.

1018
00:57:12,000 --> 00:57:15,000
And a lady from Batesville, Mrs. Thelma Glover,

1019
00:57:15,000 --> 00:57:18,000
walked in the middle of the little line

1020
00:57:18,000 --> 00:57:21,000
and started praying and swinging her arms.

1021
00:57:21,000 --> 00:57:24,000
And by the time she finished praying, they had all backed out.

1022
00:57:24,000 --> 00:57:26,000
We were saved again.

1023
00:57:26,000 --> 00:57:27,000
Yeah.

1024
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:28,000
Were you worried?

1025
00:57:28,000 --> 00:57:31,000
I thought it was the funniest thing I'd ever seen in my life.

1026
00:57:31,000 --> 00:57:32,000
I couldn't wait to tell it.

1027
00:57:32,000 --> 00:57:37,000
Hadoota was one of my best friends about how your mom stood out in the middle of everybody.

1028
00:57:37,000 --> 00:57:40,000
We were cursing at the cops and calling them names.

1029
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:43,000
And she steps out and start praying and swinging her arm.

1030
00:57:43,000 --> 00:57:45,000
And they backed out of the room.

1031
00:57:45,000 --> 00:57:47,000
It was funny.

1032
00:57:47,000 --> 00:57:49,000
No, I wasn't worried.

1033
00:57:49,000 --> 00:57:51,000
I guess I was a little crazy.

1034
00:57:51,000 --> 00:57:54,000
I didn't think about worrying.

1035
00:57:54,000 --> 00:57:58,000
Then two weeks later, they called my name.

1036
00:57:58,000 --> 00:58:02,000
They were calling names and somebody had bells me out.

1037
00:58:02,000 --> 00:58:07,000
And I went back to the house where I had stayed before we were arrested.

1038
00:58:07,000 --> 00:58:13,000
Oh, and by the way, the woman had sent some underwear or something from the suitcase to us

1039
00:58:13,000 --> 00:58:17,000
because she found ID in the woman from California's bag.

1040
00:58:17,000 --> 00:58:20,000
I didn't have any.

1041
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:24,000
She sent us a change of clothes because her sister was a cop,

1042
00:58:24,000 --> 00:58:26,000
which was interesting.

1043
00:58:26,000 --> 00:58:27,000
Yeah.

1044
00:58:27,000 --> 00:58:28,000
Were there black officers?

1045
00:58:28,000 --> 00:58:31,000
Well, they were a black woman officer, her sister.

1046
00:58:31,000 --> 00:58:33,000
I don't know if there were others.

1047
00:58:33,000 --> 00:58:34,000
I didn't know that.

1048
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:37,000
For that time in that, I guess.

1049
00:58:37,000 --> 00:58:39,000
It was 65.

1050
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:42,000
You know they had all the protests in 1962 over high.

1051
00:58:42,000 --> 00:58:44,000
The man who was hiring.

1052
00:58:44,000 --> 00:58:46,000
Yeah, I think there was a black...

1053
00:58:46,000 --> 00:58:52,000
I don't know how many black women were on the police force, but that one came.

1054
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:55,000
And we were sitting in the woman's house.

1055
00:58:55,000 --> 00:58:56,000
She was a beautician.

1056
00:58:56,000 --> 00:59:00,000
She saw us and closed the shop.

1057
00:59:00,000 --> 00:59:01,000
She was a beautician.

1058
00:59:01,000 --> 00:59:09,000
She took us to a house and we could take a real bath and warm water and eat real food.

1059
00:59:09,000 --> 00:59:12,000
And she was just very sweet.

1060
00:59:12,000 --> 00:59:20,000
And the next day we slept in a bed, not on the concrete floor with a little thin mattress.

1061
00:59:20,000 --> 00:59:25,000
Next day, we were sitting there and the California woman said,

1062
00:59:25,000 --> 00:59:27,000
that looks like a SNCC person.

1063
00:59:27,000 --> 00:59:29,000
And it was my friend, Hollis Watkins.

1064
00:59:29,000 --> 00:59:35,000
And one of the lawyers had remembered my name because it was a little different.

1065
00:59:35,000 --> 00:59:37,000
And he found us somehow.

1066
00:59:37,000 --> 00:59:38,000
But how was this?

1067
00:59:38,000 --> 00:59:39,000
Yeah.

1068
00:59:39,000 --> 00:59:41,000
How did you know Hollis?

1069
00:59:41,000 --> 00:59:42,000
From 1963.

1070
00:59:42,000 --> 00:59:43,000
From the beginning of January?

1071
00:59:43,000 --> 00:59:45,000
Yeah, 1963.

1072
00:59:45,000 --> 00:59:49,000
And we stayed in touch loosely.

1073
00:59:49,000 --> 00:59:56,000
And so I went with Hollis to McComb, Mississippi.

1074
00:59:56,000 --> 00:59:59,000
And McComb was one of those hot places, scary.

1075
00:59:59,000 --> 01:00:02,000
And I was a little nervous about McComb.

1076
01:00:02,000 --> 01:00:03,000
Other places I knew.

1077
01:00:03,000 --> 01:00:07,000
You know, Batesville was mild compared to there.

1078
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:09,000
And I met Curtis Hayes.

1079
01:00:09,000 --> 01:00:13,000
Curtis is now Curtis, my homie.

1080
01:00:13,000 --> 01:00:21,000
Curtis was putting together a group of Mississippi kids to work in the Delta, just what I needed.

1081
01:00:21,000 --> 01:00:26,000
So I went up after a couple of days in McComb.

1082
01:00:26,000 --> 01:00:32,000
I went with Curtis up to Cleveland, Mississippi.

1083
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:39,000
And Cleveland was one of the places where the Mississippi Freedom Labor Union was organized.

1084
01:00:39,000 --> 01:00:42,000
Shaw was near Cleveland.

1085
01:00:42,000 --> 01:00:48,000
And had no idea what you do to organize anything or anybody except my experiences in Batesville.

1086
01:00:48,000 --> 01:00:57,000
And I stayed with Owen Brooks initially, because the National Council of Churches was paying the stipend for Freedom Corps.

1087
01:00:57,000 --> 01:00:59,000
And I was going to be a part of that group.

1088
01:00:59,000 --> 01:01:07,000
And when you talked about the difference in men and women, Freedom Corps was mainly guys and me.

1089
01:01:07,000 --> 01:01:09,000
Guys and me.

1090
01:01:09,000 --> 01:01:10,000
You know why?

1091
01:01:10,000 --> 01:01:13,000
No, I have no idea.

1092
01:01:13,000 --> 01:01:20,000
So you could throw a fan of course in the Delta Ministry from the National Council of Churches.

1093
01:01:20,000 --> 01:01:25,000
So they were recruiting young people in Mississippi to be the Freedom Corps?

1094
01:01:25,000 --> 01:01:27,000
Curtis did.

1095
01:01:27,000 --> 01:01:28,000
Curtis did.

1096
01:01:28,000 --> 01:01:29,000
Uh huh.

1097
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:30,000
And we paid for by a Delta Ministry.

1098
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:31,000
Yeah.

1099
01:01:31,000 --> 01:01:33,000
And we got $10 a week.

1100
01:01:33,000 --> 01:01:37,000
And of course, I was filling my 18.

1101
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:40,000
I'm not an adult person because I'm 18.

1102
01:01:40,000 --> 01:01:46,000
And I'm staying with Owen Brooks, who is working for the Delta Ministry.

1103
01:01:46,000 --> 01:01:47,000
And Owen was funny.

1104
01:01:47,000 --> 01:01:49,000
I thought he was an old man.

1105
01:01:49,000 --> 01:01:53,000
He was about 30, I guess.

1106
01:01:53,000 --> 01:02:03,000
And I went out one night with a group of movement people to a Duke joint, a Rexburg,

1107
01:02:03,000 --> 01:02:10,000
where they were playing live blues, loved blues, and stayed out all night.

1108
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:13,000
Got back the next day, I'm 18, remember.

1109
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:14,000
I'm an adult person.

1110
01:02:14,000 --> 01:02:16,000
I can stay out all night if I want to.

1111
01:02:16,000 --> 01:02:21,000
I said to myself, Owen was like a mother in.

1112
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:27,000
He said, you stay out all night again.

1113
01:02:27,000 --> 01:02:31,000
And I will call your mother.

1114
01:02:31,000 --> 01:02:33,000
Where have you been?

1115
01:02:33,000 --> 01:02:35,000
I told them the story didn't work.

1116
01:02:35,000 --> 01:02:37,000
Owen found a family for me to stay with.

1117
01:02:37,000 --> 01:02:46,000
He wasn't going to be responsible for young Juadine leaving Batesville for the first time, trying to hang out, have no clue about anything.

1118
01:02:46,000 --> 01:02:51,000
So I stayed with the Washington family.

1119
01:02:51,000 --> 01:02:54,000
And not anymore.

1120
01:02:54,000 --> 01:02:56,000
Not anymore.

1121
01:02:56,000 --> 01:03:01,000
So I went to live with the Washington family for a minute or two.

1122
01:03:01,000 --> 01:03:09,000
And then they sent me off to Rosedale, you know, one of the places where the Freedom Labor Union was really big.

1123
01:03:09,000 --> 01:03:12,000
And a lot of the farm workers had lived in the little town.

1124
01:03:12,000 --> 01:03:16,000
And I was to organize and work with them.

1125
01:03:16,000 --> 01:03:21,000
I lived with a family there, Frank Davis, who was the local leader.

1126
01:03:21,000 --> 01:03:30,000
And it was interesting because he lived right across the road, or the street from the courthouse and the jail.

1127
01:03:30,000 --> 01:03:36,000
And I stayed in the room with their daughter, who was, I think, a 14-year-old.

1128
01:03:36,000 --> 01:03:40,000
And they had three other people living in their house.

1129
01:03:40,000 --> 01:03:42,000
Now, house was tiny.

1130
01:03:42,000 --> 01:03:47,000
Morton Thomas from Boston, I think, and a student at Harvard.

1131
01:03:47,000 --> 01:03:54,000
Billy Kochiyama, who was Japanese grew up in Harlem.

1132
01:03:54,000 --> 01:03:57,000
And we'll stay another person.

1133
01:03:57,000 --> 01:03:59,000
Maybe that was it.

1134
01:03:59,000 --> 01:04:02,000
So these guys are people who came in and this is it?

1135
01:04:02,000 --> 01:04:03,000
Yes.

1136
01:04:03,000 --> 01:04:07,000
What about the rest of the Freedom Court when they came outside or local?

1137
01:04:07,000 --> 01:04:08,000
They were local.

1138
01:04:08,000 --> 01:04:12,000
Everybody was in the movement at home.

1139
01:04:12,000 --> 01:04:15,000
And I think that's our Reese Webb from my county.

1140
01:04:15,000 --> 01:04:18,000
He's still there.

1141
01:04:18,000 --> 01:04:24,000
Homer Crawford, Willie had been a farm worker.

1142
01:04:24,000 --> 01:04:27,000
He was a tractor driver, I think.

1143
01:04:27,000 --> 01:04:35,000
Isaac Foster, who had been a tractor driver on somebody's plantation.

1144
01:04:35,000 --> 01:04:40,000
And Joe Harrison from Holmes County.

1145
01:04:40,000 --> 01:04:43,000
Did you think about the fact that the other Freedom Court

1146
01:04:43,000 --> 01:04:46,000
and the outside folks are mostly men?

1147
01:04:46,000 --> 01:04:47,000
No.

1148
01:04:47,000 --> 01:04:48,000
Did you notice?

1149
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:50,000
Yeah, I noticed.

1150
01:04:50,000 --> 01:04:52,000
I had to fight them sometime, you know?

1151
01:04:52,000 --> 01:04:56,000
But I could curse as good as they could, so.

1152
01:04:56,000 --> 01:04:58,000
No, they would.

1153
01:04:58,000 --> 01:05:00,000
They said nothing to do with the movement.

1154
01:05:00,000 --> 01:05:02,000
There was a softball game.

1155
01:05:02,000 --> 01:05:03,000
I played softball.

1156
01:05:03,000 --> 01:05:05,000
I played softball.

1157
01:05:05,000 --> 01:05:09,000
And Benjamin Brown.

1158
01:05:09,000 --> 01:05:11,000
You said you don't want to get killed in the city?

1159
01:05:11,000 --> 01:05:14,000
Yes, yes he did.

1160
01:05:14,000 --> 01:05:19,000
Ben said, why don't you act like other girls?

1161
01:05:19,000 --> 01:05:23,000
And I said just because you can't play softball is not my problem.

1162
01:05:23,000 --> 01:05:25,000
I'm playing first base.

1163
01:05:25,000 --> 01:05:29,000
And I played first base.

1164
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:30,000
I'm studying about that.

1165
01:05:30,000 --> 01:05:31,000
Not at all.

1166
01:05:31,000 --> 01:05:38,000
And then I recruited another young woman, Helen Williams,

1167
01:05:38,000 --> 01:05:42,000
from Rosedale, to come and work with us.

1168
01:05:42,000 --> 01:05:46,000
And then another woman I met in Washington at one of those demonstrations,

1169
01:05:46,000 --> 01:05:50,000
Tete Tete came and joined the group.

1170
01:05:50,000 --> 01:05:52,000
Helen could hang.

1171
01:05:52,000 --> 01:05:55,000
Tete, not so much.

1172
01:05:55,000 --> 01:06:00,000
And Faye, my home girl, my best friend, came and worked with us for a minute.

1173
01:06:00,000 --> 01:06:02,000
She also couldn't hang.

1174
01:06:02,000 --> 01:06:04,000
Mr. Boy's, well boys, you know?

1175
01:06:04,000 --> 01:06:06,000
He can only.

1176
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:09,000
Did they just find out that it really is?

1177
01:06:09,000 --> 01:06:10,000
No, no.

1178
01:06:10,000 --> 01:06:15,000
And we had, when we went out to the plantations to talk to farm workers,

1179
01:06:15,000 --> 01:06:17,000
we left one person in the van.

1180
01:06:17,000 --> 01:06:19,000
We had a van.

1181
01:06:19,000 --> 01:06:24,000
And when you saw the dust coming, you knew the owner was coming.

1182
01:06:24,000 --> 01:06:27,000
So you had to beep the horn.

1183
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:31,000
And everybody ran out from wherever they were and jumped in the car and we took off.

1184
01:06:31,000 --> 01:06:33,000
And the fight was on.

1185
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:35,000
Like, they were chasing us and we were chased.

1186
01:06:35,000 --> 01:06:36,000
We just ran.

1187
01:06:36,000 --> 01:06:37,000
That's all.

1188
01:06:37,000 --> 01:06:39,000
And then we would go back.

1189
01:06:39,000 --> 01:06:43,000
And sometimes when we went back, there were the people who were gone.

1190
01:06:43,000 --> 01:06:45,000
They had left overnight.

1191
01:06:45,000 --> 01:06:48,000
It was like slavery.

1192
01:06:48,000 --> 01:06:50,000
They lived there.

1193
01:06:50,000 --> 01:06:51,000
They shopped there.

1194
01:06:51,000 --> 01:06:52,000
They went to church there.

1195
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:56,000
There was one plantation, Delta Pines.

1196
01:06:56,000 --> 01:06:58,000
It had seven churches.

1197
01:06:58,000 --> 01:07:00,000
I counted them.

1198
01:07:00,000 --> 01:07:01,000
Yeah.

1199
01:07:01,000 --> 01:07:03,000
And people had no reason to leave.

1200
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:06,000
So there's a few people who have cloned off on the stage.

1201
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:07,000
Yeah.

1202
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:11,000
And so when you went back and knocked on the door that you had knocked on last week

1203
01:07:11,000 --> 01:07:15,000
other day before and nobody was there, you knew they had run away.

1204
01:07:15,000 --> 01:07:18,000
Right away, sort of, when you saw a safe lift in the room?

1205
01:07:18,000 --> 01:07:19,000
No.

1206
01:07:19,000 --> 01:07:20,000
Together away.

1207
01:07:20,000 --> 01:07:21,000
The different life.

1208
01:07:21,000 --> 01:07:29,000
When you say you're working and organizing, it's a farm labor party.

1209
01:07:29,000 --> 01:07:31,000
What was freedom labor union?

1210
01:07:31,000 --> 01:07:38,000
You know, I'm trying to take a weird, I've got the freedom labor union.

1211
01:07:38,000 --> 01:07:41,000
I think the former labor party was a big deal.

1212
01:07:41,000 --> 01:07:43,000
At the time, okay.

1213
01:07:43,000 --> 01:07:51,000
At the time people were making 30 cents an hour, ten hour days, three dollars a day.

1214
01:07:51,000 --> 01:07:57,000
And what we were saying is they needed to make more money and organizing.

1215
01:07:57,000 --> 01:08:02,000
And that they should walk off if they couldn't get more money.

1216
01:08:02,000 --> 01:08:04,000
Because they couldn't live on three dollars a day.

1217
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:12,000
They were on the plantations mainly because they had accumulated bills with the company store, you know, to eat.

1218
01:08:12,000 --> 01:08:15,000
And they couldn't leave because they had a debt.

1219
01:08:15,000 --> 01:08:16,000
They had to pay.

1220
01:08:16,000 --> 01:08:18,000
Could pay the debt.

1221
01:08:18,000 --> 01:08:26,000
So that was in Bolivar County, Sunflower County, and Washington counties.

1222
01:08:26,000 --> 01:08:35,000
And I also tried to organize a little bit of a little tiny freedom school.

1223
01:08:35,000 --> 01:08:41,000
Because a lot of the kids had dropped out at third grade to teach people how to write their names.

1224
01:08:41,000 --> 01:08:45,000
You know, simple stuff.

1225
01:08:45,000 --> 01:08:50,000
Billy, Kotiama, his family had lived in Harlem.

1226
01:08:50,000 --> 01:08:55,000
His parents had been in internment camps during World War II.

1227
01:08:55,000 --> 01:09:02,000
And when they were released, they moved to Harlem.

1228
01:09:02,000 --> 01:09:06,000
And his mom was a big follower of Malcolm X.

1229
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:12,000
And Billy was the first person who told me I was African-American.

1230
01:09:12,000 --> 01:09:15,000
I think he called us Afro-American at the time.

1231
01:09:15,000 --> 01:09:19,000
He was like, okay, we can be that.

1232
01:09:19,000 --> 01:09:25,000
Billy also was not your typical non-violent movement person.

1233
01:09:25,000 --> 01:09:29,000
I went out of town for some meeting of the other.

1234
01:09:29,000 --> 01:09:35,000
I got back to town and they said, got to go to court at two o'clock.

1235
01:09:35,000 --> 01:09:38,000
Billy was arrested over the weekend.

1236
01:09:38,000 --> 01:09:43,000
I was like, okay, I got my $10, right?

1237
01:09:43,000 --> 01:09:50,000
Billy had been standing with one of the kids when the clan marched through town.

1238
01:09:50,000 --> 01:09:56,000
And one of the clansmen, we're talking about the KKK now, called him Tojo.

1239
01:09:56,000 --> 01:10:03,000
That was his behind. Billy kicked his behind right there and was arrested.

1240
01:10:03,000 --> 01:10:07,000
I used my $10 to get Billy out of jail or to keep him out of jail.

1241
01:10:07,000 --> 01:10:12,000
I think that was the fine 10 bucks good thing because we didn't have one in that.

1242
01:10:12,000 --> 01:10:16,000
Billy went back to New York at the end of the summer.

1243
01:10:16,000 --> 01:10:21,000
And I didn't ever see Billy again.

1244
01:10:21,000 --> 01:10:27,000
It was over. I met his mom a few years later.

1245
01:10:27,000 --> 01:10:31,000
It was kind of a nice, raggedag crew in Rose Del.

1246
01:10:31,000 --> 01:10:35,000
So did you bring up or get farmers to organize and walk off?

1247
01:10:35,000 --> 01:10:41,000
There were a lot of people who walked off, but they had walked off with no means of support.

1248
01:10:41,000 --> 01:10:47,000
Labor unions, freedom labor union had no money.

1249
01:10:47,000 --> 01:10:50,000
I think Isaac Foster, one of the guys who worked with Freedom Corps,

1250
01:10:50,000 --> 01:10:54,000
was one of the organizers of the Freedom Labor Union.

1251
01:10:54,000 --> 01:10:58,000
It didn't really know how unions worked.

1252
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:00,000
I wish I could remember details.

1253
01:11:00,000 --> 01:11:07,000
I know there was a group of them living in tents in the year Greenville.

1254
01:11:07,000 --> 01:11:10,000
Oh, that was later.

1255
01:11:10,000 --> 01:11:21,000
Greenville Air Force Base sent me to raise money for people.

1256
01:11:21,000 --> 01:11:24,000
Two Minnesota and to Pennsylvania.

1257
01:11:24,000 --> 01:11:26,000
It was my first plane ride.

1258
01:11:26,000 --> 01:11:31,000
I was scared to death, but I had to put on a brave front.

1259
01:11:31,000 --> 01:11:32,000
And...

1260
01:11:32,000 --> 01:11:35,000
Were you not worried about anything in the specific, but you're afraid of an airplane?

1261
01:11:35,000 --> 01:11:39,000
Yes. Absolutely.

1262
01:11:39,000 --> 01:11:46,000
And I got to speak at little church groups and stuff in Minnesota and in Pennsylvania.

1263
01:11:46,000 --> 01:11:48,000
And Illinois.

1264
01:11:48,000 --> 01:11:53,000
And this was also, I guess, it was late 65 or early 66.

1265
01:11:53,000 --> 01:11:57,000
I went with Bob Reverend Robert Beach.

1266
01:11:57,000 --> 01:12:02,000
We called him Bob Beach.

1267
01:12:02,000 --> 01:12:04,000
And I was kind of fun.

1268
01:12:04,000 --> 01:12:07,000
I was excited when you watched you.

1269
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:10,000
It was different.

1270
01:12:10,000 --> 01:12:12,000
Yeah, yeah.

1271
01:12:12,000 --> 01:12:19,000
In Minnesota, there were a couple of women who had been in Greenville working for Delta Ministry.

1272
01:12:19,000 --> 01:12:21,000
And so I stayed with them.

1273
01:12:21,000 --> 01:12:24,000
So I knew them.

1274
01:12:24,000 --> 01:12:31,000
The church groups, you know, I guess they had never seen somebody like me before.

1275
01:12:31,000 --> 01:12:35,000
And that was kind of interesting.

1276
01:12:36,000 --> 01:12:38,000
They were just sort of staring.

1277
01:12:38,000 --> 01:12:42,000
At one church, they had me put on a robe.

1278
01:12:42,000 --> 01:12:46,000
And you know, with the preachers, and I stood there.

1279
01:12:46,000 --> 01:12:49,000
And did my little talk.

1280
01:12:49,000 --> 01:12:50,000
Yeah.

1281
01:12:50,000 --> 01:12:52,000
I thought so too.

1282
01:12:52,000 --> 01:12:55,000
Okay, I'll put it on our own care.

1283
01:12:55,000 --> 01:12:58,000
And most of the groups were white.

1284
01:12:58,000 --> 01:13:03,000
When I went to Pennsylvania, and I'm just outside of Pittsburgh,

1285
01:13:03,000 --> 01:13:07,000
I asked the minister that I was living with.

1286
01:13:07,000 --> 01:13:10,000
I didn't know whether we were black or colored then.

1287
01:13:10,000 --> 01:13:14,000
Other people who like me nearby, because I hadn't seen any.

1288
01:13:14,000 --> 01:13:19,000
And so he arranged with the NAACP for me to come and speak in the Hill District.

1289
01:13:19,000 --> 01:13:20,000
So really?

1290
01:13:20,000 --> 01:13:21,000
Yeah, yeah.

1291
01:13:21,000 --> 01:13:22,000
That's cool.

1292
01:13:22,000 --> 01:13:27,000
And one of the women said, where are you staying while you're here?

1293
01:13:27,000 --> 01:13:29,000
And I said Mount Lebanon.

1294
01:13:30,000 --> 01:13:32,000
She said, oh my goodness girl.

1295
01:13:32,000 --> 01:13:35,000
It's a wonder we don't have seen you hung up on a tree out there.

1296
01:13:35,000 --> 01:13:37,000
Like, are you serious?

1297
01:13:37,000 --> 01:13:38,000
She said, yep.

1298
01:13:38,000 --> 01:13:40,000
It's about the North.

1299
01:13:40,000 --> 01:13:41,000
Yeah.

1300
01:13:41,000 --> 01:13:43,000
It was revelation.

1301
01:13:43,000 --> 01:13:46,000
It was like black people don't go out there after dark.

1302
01:13:46,000 --> 01:13:48,000
And I don't know that we were black yet.

1303
01:13:48,000 --> 01:13:51,000
But you know, you don't go out there after dark.

1304
01:13:51,000 --> 01:13:56,000
Oh, that's why I leave before sign up and go back after dark care.

1305
01:13:56,000 --> 01:13:57,000
Okay.

1306
01:13:58,000 --> 01:13:59,000
And then...

1307
01:13:59,000 --> 01:14:01,000
They were worried, but they're like, you shouldn't...

1308
01:14:01,000 --> 01:14:02,000
Yeah.

1309
01:14:02,000 --> 01:14:03,000
It was like, okay.

1310
01:14:03,000 --> 01:14:04,000
I didn't know that.

1311
01:14:04,000 --> 01:14:08,000
And then I think the next stop was Illinois.

1312
01:14:08,000 --> 01:14:12,000
And I spoke at the seminary in Chicago.

1313
01:14:12,000 --> 01:14:15,000
I don't remember the name, McCormick maybe.

1314
01:14:15,000 --> 01:14:16,000
I don't know.

1315
01:14:16,000 --> 01:14:19,000
But I think that's where I was speaking.

1316
01:14:19,000 --> 01:14:20,000
Uh-huh.

1317
01:14:20,000 --> 01:14:24,000
And they told me I had a family for me.

1318
01:14:24,000 --> 01:14:26,000
And I said, I have family here.

1319
01:14:26,000 --> 01:14:28,000
I began...

1320
01:14:28,000 --> 01:14:31,000
Up the river.

1321
01:14:31,000 --> 01:14:41,000
So they had to take me to the south side and I had to yell up in the tentimate for my older sister to come and get me downstairs to let me in.

1322
01:14:41,000 --> 01:14:44,000
And I was speaking at a church there on Sunday.

1323
01:14:44,000 --> 01:14:46,000
Did you been in Chicago before?

1324
01:14:46,000 --> 01:14:47,000
No.

1325
01:14:47,000 --> 01:14:49,000
No.

1326
01:14:50,000 --> 01:14:54,000
And my sister did not like the way I looked.

1327
01:14:54,000 --> 01:14:57,000
You cannot go out of this house looking like that.

1328
01:14:57,000 --> 01:15:05,000
So she straightened my hair and put me on a suit with hills.

1329
01:15:05,000 --> 01:15:07,000
I thought they will not recognize me.

1330
01:15:07,000 --> 01:15:09,000
This is not me.

1331
01:15:09,000 --> 01:15:12,000
And I allowed it because you didn't...

1332
01:15:12,000 --> 01:15:14,000
You had to respect your elders.

1333
01:15:14,000 --> 01:15:16,000
That was how I grew up, you know?

1334
01:15:16,000 --> 01:15:17,000
Okay.

1335
01:15:17,000 --> 01:15:22,000
I haven't noticed you speaking of respect in your elders the last time.

1336
01:15:22,000 --> 01:15:24,000
Well, I had trouble with that.

1337
01:15:24,000 --> 01:15:25,000
Yeah.

1338
01:15:25,000 --> 01:15:27,000
That's a lot of thinking.

1339
01:15:27,000 --> 01:15:29,000
I had trouble with it.

1340
01:15:29,000 --> 01:15:32,000
So you said your sister will understand your hair.

1341
01:15:32,000 --> 01:15:34,000
She did. She didn't want to. She did it.

1342
01:15:34,000 --> 01:15:37,000
So were you wearing your hair natural on purpose because of the cement?

1343
01:15:37,000 --> 01:15:38,000
Yeah.

1344
01:15:38,000 --> 01:15:39,000
Yeah.

1345
01:15:39,000 --> 01:15:41,000
Did all the women in the movement?

1346
01:15:41,000 --> 01:15:43,000
No, I don't think so.

1347
01:15:43,000 --> 01:15:48,000
I met some young woman named Gwen Gillian, I think.

1348
01:15:48,000 --> 01:15:50,000
And she had her hair natural.

1349
01:15:50,000 --> 01:15:52,000
And I thought that's not so bad.

1350
01:15:52,000 --> 01:15:56,000
And then I saw an album cover with Odetta on it with natural hair.

1351
01:15:56,000 --> 01:16:00,000
I hadn't cut my hair yet, but I said,

1352
01:16:00,000 --> 01:16:03,000
I don't need to straighten my hair. Why would I do that?

1353
01:16:03,000 --> 01:16:04,000
Mm-hmm.

1354
01:16:04,000 --> 01:16:08,000
But my sister wasn't having it.

1355
01:16:08,000 --> 01:16:14,000
So I went back to Mississippi and something was happening,

1356
01:16:14,000 --> 01:16:19,000
the politics of the movement I think was changing early 1966.

1357
01:16:19,000 --> 01:16:21,000
You just cut that or talked about it.

1358
01:16:21,000 --> 01:16:23,000
I don't really remember. I wish.

1359
01:16:23,000 --> 01:16:26,000
The Freedom Corps was kind of breaking up.

1360
01:16:26,000 --> 01:16:29,000
I don't remember why.

1361
01:16:29,000 --> 01:16:31,000
But...

1362
01:16:31,000 --> 01:16:34,000
What are the racial conflicts?

1363
01:16:34,000 --> 01:16:37,000
Freedom Corps was all black.

1364
01:16:37,000 --> 01:16:40,000
It was Curtis and us.

1365
01:16:40,000 --> 01:16:43,000
If you were working with some of the white kids...

1366
01:16:43,000 --> 01:16:45,000
Yeah, of course.

1367
01:16:45,000 --> 01:16:46,000
Yeah.

1368
01:16:46,000 --> 01:16:49,000
I don't remember that.

1369
01:16:49,000 --> 01:16:55,000
I have to try and remember what happened because I blocked on it.

1370
01:16:55,000 --> 01:17:00,000
But I left my place in Bolivar County.

1371
01:17:00,000 --> 01:17:03,000
I was living with the family there who had absolutely nothing.

1372
01:17:03,000 --> 01:17:06,000
I slept with some of the kids.

1373
01:17:06,000 --> 01:17:12,000
You could be sitting in the bed and see a mouse running across the pillow.

1374
01:17:12,000 --> 01:17:15,000
I can't handle this.

1375
01:17:15,000 --> 01:17:18,000
The floor is one thing.

1376
01:17:18,000 --> 01:17:19,000
The pillow?

1377
01:17:19,000 --> 01:17:21,000
Yeah. It's time to move.

1378
01:17:21,000 --> 01:17:24,000
I went to Jackson.

1379
01:17:24,000 --> 01:17:27,000
And I don't remember what went into that decision.

1380
01:17:27,000 --> 01:17:30,000
Helen decided to go back home to Rosedale.

1381
01:17:30,000 --> 01:17:33,000
I went to Jackson.

1382
01:17:33,000 --> 01:17:36,000
The guys also split up.

1383
01:17:36,000 --> 01:17:39,000
I don't remember what caused the split.

1384
01:17:39,000 --> 01:17:44,000
And I'll send a note to Curtis and ask him if he remembers.

1385
01:17:44,000 --> 01:17:52,000
In Jackson, I stayed with another group of movement women in the patio apartments where other

1386
01:17:52,000 --> 01:17:55,000
snick people lived.

1387
01:17:55,000 --> 01:17:57,000
For some of the people you were staying with said...

1388
01:17:57,000 --> 01:18:09,000
The women in that apartment was Gracie Hartthorn from Hattiesburg, Joyce Brown from McComb, Marjorie Hyatt.

1389
01:18:09,000 --> 01:18:15,000
Marjorie was from Hattiesburg and she also claimed Pittsburgh somehow.

1390
01:18:15,000 --> 01:18:20,000
And most of them worked for the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party in the office.

1391
01:18:20,000 --> 01:18:23,000
And I wasn't sure what I was doing yet.

1392
01:18:23,000 --> 01:18:26,000
And Smith always pulled me out.

1393
01:18:26,000 --> 01:18:28,000
And I did.

1394
01:18:28,000 --> 01:18:31,000
So I went to work for Frank.

1395
01:18:31,000 --> 01:18:34,000
He had neighborhood development group or something.

1396
01:18:34,000 --> 01:18:42,000
And they were supposed to make bricks to build homes for people in strike city.

1397
01:18:42,000 --> 01:18:46,000
That's what the tent city was called, strike city.

1398
01:18:46,000 --> 01:18:52,000
And I was working in his office and getting a feel for the city.

1399
01:18:52,000 --> 01:18:55,000
It was...

1400
01:18:55,000 --> 01:18:57,000
Where was strike city?

1401
01:18:57,000 --> 01:19:01,000
It was Strike City, Mississippi.

1402
01:19:01,000 --> 01:19:04,000
And it's where people went when they went on strike with the...

1403
01:19:04,000 --> 01:19:07,000
When they got kicked off plantations.

1404
01:19:07,000 --> 01:19:13,000
Yeah, it was a tent city and they had a big sign in [/at] Strike City.

1405
01:19:13,000 --> 01:19:20,000
Isaac Foster, the person I mentioned earlier, was one of the people from strike city.

1406
01:19:20,000 --> 01:19:23,000
Did you meet Jean Wheeler at that time?

1407
01:19:23,000 --> 01:19:25,000
She and Frank were married.

1408
01:19:25,000 --> 01:19:26,000
I met her with Frank.

1409
01:19:26,000 --> 01:19:29,000
I think they were already married.

1410
01:19:29,000 --> 01:19:32,000
And she was like a big sister to me.

1411
01:19:32,000 --> 01:19:33,000
Yeah.

1412
01:19:33,000 --> 01:19:34,000
Yeah.

1413
01:19:34,000 --> 01:19:36,000
We still live in the same neighborhood.

1414
01:19:36,000 --> 01:19:37,000
What can I tell you?

1415
01:19:37,000 --> 01:19:38,000
Yeah.

1416
01:19:38,000 --> 01:19:41,000
Was she still organizing, working with the movement at that time?

1417
01:19:41,000 --> 01:19:42,000
Yes.

1418
01:19:42,000 --> 01:19:47,000
But she was working, I think, mainly with Frank.

1419
01:19:47,000 --> 01:19:59,000
And his brick factory idea, trying to figure out how you make bricks to build houses.

1420
01:19:59,000 --> 01:20:01,000
I'm trying to remember.

1421
01:20:01,000 --> 01:20:06,000
Jean, I think, was also writing, which I thought was interesting.

1422
01:20:06,000 --> 01:20:07,000
Yeah.

1423
01:20:07,000 --> 01:20:11,000
And I had to think about, now it's almost time to go to college.

1424
01:20:11,000 --> 01:20:16,000
You've almost finished your year of movement work.

1425
01:20:16,000 --> 01:20:18,000
And how are you going to do that?

1426
01:20:18,000 --> 01:20:19,000
I don't know.

1427
01:20:19,000 --> 01:20:28,000
And some guy came into the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party office and was looking for people recruiting for Bishop College in Texas.

1428
01:20:28,000 --> 01:20:31,000
It was a Baptist college.

1429
01:20:31,000 --> 01:20:33,000
And most of us went.

1430
01:20:33,000 --> 01:20:39,000
All of us who had finished high school, yeah, we'll go, what do we need to do?

1431
01:20:39,000 --> 01:20:41,000
And we went to Bishop.

1432
01:20:41,000 --> 01:20:43,000
So Bishop was actively recruiting movement kids?

1433
01:20:43,000 --> 01:20:44,000
No.

1434
01:20:45,000 --> 01:20:46,000
Bishop was not.

1435
01:20:46,000 --> 01:20:47,000
No.

1436
01:20:47,000 --> 01:20:48,000
Bishop was not.

1437
01:20:48,000 --> 01:20:53,000
Tom Brown, who had been a SNCC person, was working in the admissions office.

1438
01:20:53,000 --> 01:20:57,000
He was recruiting movement folks without telling them that.

1439
01:20:57,000 --> 01:20:58,000
No.

1440
01:20:58,000 --> 01:20:59,000
Not Bishop.

1441
01:20:59,000 --> 01:21:00,000
No.

1442
01:21:00,000 --> 01:21:01,000
Absolutely not.

1443
01:21:01,000 --> 01:21:02,000
No.

1444
01:21:02,000 --> 01:21:03,000
No.

1445
01:21:03,000 --> 01:21:12,000
So Marjorie Hyatt, Linda Wilson, who was active in Hattiesburg,

1446
01:21:12,000 --> 01:21:14,000
and I, who else?

1447
01:21:14,000 --> 01:21:18,000
Maybe it was just three of us went to Bishop.

1448
01:21:18,000 --> 01:21:19,000
Mm-hmm.

1449
01:21:19,000 --> 01:21:21,000
You all organized a Bishop for Bishop?

1450
01:21:21,000 --> 01:21:23,000
Oh, it was a nightmare.

1451
01:21:23,000 --> 01:21:28,000
Bishop was an experience.

1452
01:21:28,000 --> 01:21:33,000
When we got to Dallas, I think we took a bus there.

1453
01:21:33,000 --> 01:21:37,000
The person from the school who came to pick us up had a big sign on the side of the car.

1454
01:21:38,000 --> 01:21:40,000
The said repent and be saved.

1455
01:21:40,000 --> 01:21:45,000
Did you turn the leaf in?

1456
01:21:45,000 --> 01:21:49,000
If I could have, I think I would have, I was, oh my.

1457
01:21:49,000 --> 01:21:50,000
Okay.

1458
01:21:50,000 --> 01:21:58,000
And so I went to, we got to the campus and I had an afro body and had cut my hair.

1459
01:21:58,000 --> 01:22:05,000
Low and all the little women girls were staring like, look, she washed her hair.

1460
01:22:06,000 --> 01:22:12,000
Like, oh, now I know what black kids feel like when they go to white schools.

1461
01:22:12,000 --> 01:22:18,000
Had a roommate who was very religious, I guess, young.

1462
01:22:18,000 --> 01:22:22,000
And thought this is a mistake, but they didn't try to pair us with each other.

1463
01:22:22,000 --> 01:22:25,000
They wanted us to, I guess, stretch out.

1464
01:22:25,000 --> 01:22:28,000
Went to breakfast the next morning, same thing happened.

1465
01:22:28,000 --> 01:22:34,000
Everybody stopped eating to stare like she washed her hair.

1466
01:22:34,000 --> 01:22:37,000
So that was interesting.

1467
01:22:37,000 --> 01:22:38,000
I had to get a job.

1468
01:22:38,000 --> 01:22:40,000
I was in the work study program and I got a job.

1469
01:22:40,000 --> 01:22:43,000
They put me in the laundry room.

1470
01:22:43,000 --> 01:22:47,000
We had nobody with CME.

1471
01:22:47,000 --> 01:22:50,000
And so I wouldn't mess with nobody's hair.

1472
01:22:50,000 --> 01:22:53,000
I'm sorry, it's straightened.

1473
01:22:53,000 --> 01:22:57,000
Did any of the house mothers of the dean of students, did they say anything to you about your hair?

1474
01:22:57,000 --> 01:23:00,000
The librarian said something to me about my hair.

1475
01:23:00,000 --> 01:23:05,000
She said, you look as bad as that African woman who came here with her hair like that.

1476
01:23:05,000 --> 01:23:12,000
Jamella Stokes from Hadisburg said to her, I've never seen anybody born with blue hair before.

1477
01:23:12,000 --> 01:23:19,000
And that was when black women who had white hair would dye it blue.

1478
01:23:23,000 --> 01:23:27,000
And she sort of lifted me because I got fired from my first job.

1479
01:23:27,000 --> 01:23:32,000
First thing I did, and it wasn't an act of protest or anything.

1480
01:23:32,000 --> 01:23:36,000
I put it in this roller thing that was supposed to dry it.

1481
01:23:36,000 --> 01:23:37,000
It never came out.

1482
01:23:37,000 --> 01:23:39,000
And the room got all smoky.

1483
01:23:39,000 --> 01:23:40,000
It burned.

1484
01:23:40,000 --> 01:23:45,000
So they sent me out of there and sent me to the library to work in periodical.

1485
01:23:45,000 --> 01:23:47,000
So nobody would see me.

1486
01:23:47,000 --> 01:23:51,000
I could be behind the books and behind the magazines and all of that.

1487
01:23:51,000 --> 01:23:53,000
That was kind of interesting.

1488
01:23:53,000 --> 01:24:00,000
The other interesting part I think was the first night, not the first night, the second night.

1489
01:24:00,000 --> 01:24:05,000
A couple of kids came up to stairs and said, can you do my hair like that?

1490
01:24:05,000 --> 01:24:06,000
Interesting.

1491
01:24:06,000 --> 01:24:09,000
I said, yeah, I got to do this wash it now.

1492
01:24:09,000 --> 01:24:10,000
I cut it for you.

1493
01:24:10,000 --> 01:24:11,000
I cut hair.

1494
01:24:11,000 --> 01:24:12,000
Did I pull up out cutting hair?

1495
01:24:12,000 --> 01:24:14,000
No, but I could do it.

1496
01:24:14,000 --> 01:24:17,000
So you started a movement.

1497
01:24:17,000 --> 01:24:20,000
I think everybody was ready pretty much.

1498
01:24:20,000 --> 01:24:28,000
And Ebony magazine did a cover in 1966 that said, all natural.

1499
01:24:28,000 --> 01:24:31,000
And they had women on the cover with afros.

1500
01:24:31,000 --> 01:24:33,000
Oh, was my mother pleased.

1501
01:24:33,000 --> 01:24:36,000
See, why Dean's not the only one, look.

1502
01:24:36,000 --> 01:24:37,000
That's cool.

1503
01:24:37,000 --> 01:24:43,000
So once Ebony did it, it was all right, though.

1504
01:24:43,000 --> 01:24:44,000
People...

1505
01:24:44,000 --> 01:24:45,000
It took a little bit more time.

1506
01:24:45,000 --> 01:24:46,000
Mm-hmm.

1507
01:24:46,000 --> 01:24:49,000
And how would university, maybe that was later,

1508
01:24:49,000 --> 01:24:58,000
the queen of how it had an afro, but people were getting used to the idea of, okay, you can have that be hair.

1509
01:24:58,000 --> 01:25:01,000
So did you, you stay at Bishop?

1510
01:25:01,000 --> 01:25:02,000
I stayed at No.

1511
01:25:02,000 --> 01:25:05,000
I stayed at Bishop for two years.

1512
01:25:05,000 --> 01:25:07,000
And I had a good time at Bishop.

1513
01:25:07,000 --> 01:25:09,000
I made friends.

1514
01:25:09,000 --> 01:25:16,000
It was like being in elementary school again in some ways, because it was a very strict campus.

1515
01:25:16,000 --> 01:25:18,000
You couldn't wear slacks.

1516
01:25:18,000 --> 01:25:20,000
It was a religious school.

1517
01:25:20,000 --> 01:25:22,000
It was a Baptist college.

1518
01:25:22,000 --> 01:25:23,000
I got caught.

1519
01:25:23,000 --> 01:25:27,000
You were supposed to go to chapel every, I think, three days a week.

1520
01:25:27,000 --> 01:25:33,000
And I would send my punch card by one of the girls on the dorm.

1521
01:25:33,000 --> 01:25:37,000
And I would sit in my room and tinker on the guitar.

1522
01:25:37,000 --> 01:25:40,000
And one day I got a knock on the door.

1523
01:25:40,000 --> 01:25:45,000
And I thought it was somebody else who had cut chapel.

1524
01:25:45,000 --> 01:25:48,000
And it was the dean of women.

1525
01:25:48,000 --> 01:25:50,000
And she went back in the house.

1526
01:25:50,000 --> 01:25:55,000
There was a young lady in her room playing the ukulele.

1527
01:25:55,000 --> 01:25:57,000
And everybody knew it was me.

1528
01:25:57,000 --> 01:25:58,000
So, okay.

1529
01:25:58,000 --> 01:26:03,000
And on Sundays, when you were supposed to go to church, I went to the federal prison.

1530
01:26:03,000 --> 01:26:07,000
There was a prison nearby called Seagoville.

1531
01:26:07,000 --> 01:26:13,000
And my English professor had given me something that a prisoner over there had written.

1532
01:26:13,000 --> 01:26:16,000
And I thought he was a good writer.

1533
01:26:16,000 --> 01:26:18,000
So, we connected.

1534
01:26:18,000 --> 01:26:21,000
They arranged for me to come and visit.

1535
01:26:21,000 --> 01:26:23,000
So, that's where I went on Sundays.

1536
01:26:23,000 --> 01:26:29,000
And I wrote, when you had to sign out the dorm, I said I was going to a Quaker meeting.

1537
01:26:29,000 --> 01:26:31,000
They didn't know.

1538
01:26:31,000 --> 01:26:35,000
So, they would let you do a Quaker meeting instead of chapel?

1539
01:26:35,000 --> 01:26:37,000
Yeah, that was chapel for me.

1540
01:26:37,000 --> 01:26:38,000
But I was gone.

1541
01:26:38,000 --> 01:26:39,000
And there was a woman.

1542
01:26:39,000 --> 01:26:49,000
I think she was from Louisiana, whose fiance was in prison there because he refused to go to the war.

1543
01:26:49,000 --> 01:26:52,000
She would pick me up on Sunday mornings and take me with her.

1544
01:26:52,000 --> 01:26:56,000
And I would go visit Lafayette, Locke, the prisoner.

1545
01:26:56,000 --> 01:27:02,000
And I also was able to get books and stuff for them that they wanted.

1546
01:27:02,000 --> 01:27:06,000
And he would tell me where to leave it, like in the pastor near the prison.

1547
01:27:06,000 --> 01:27:08,000
I don't know how they got them.

1548
01:27:08,000 --> 01:27:09,000
And I would, you know?

1549
01:27:09,000 --> 01:27:11,000
Interesting.

1550
01:27:11,000 --> 01:27:15,000
That's how I spent my Sundays instead of going to church.

1551
01:27:15,000 --> 01:27:18,000
What did you do when you left Bishop?

1552
01:27:18,000 --> 01:27:21,000
After Bishop.

1553
01:27:21,000 --> 01:27:23,000
Oh gosh.

1554
01:27:23,000 --> 01:27:27,000
I left Bishop in 68.

1555
01:27:27,000 --> 01:27:34,000
And Dr. King was coming to Batesville to speak before his death.

1556
01:27:34,000 --> 01:27:36,000
And of course it would be before his death.

1557
01:27:36,000 --> 01:27:39,000
But my mom said, Dr. King is coming to town.

1558
01:27:39,000 --> 01:27:40,000
You need to go see him.

1559
01:27:40,000 --> 01:27:41,000
And I said no.

1560
01:27:41,000 --> 01:27:44,000
I was depressed.

1561
01:27:44,000 --> 01:27:46,000
I'm not going to see him.

1562
01:27:46,000 --> 01:27:49,000
And so she did what she normally did.

1563
01:27:49,000 --> 01:27:54,000
She got my uncle and said, go get Juadine and take her to see Dr. King.

1564
01:27:54,000 --> 01:27:56,000
Is this for brother?

1565
01:27:56,000 --> 01:27:57,000
Yes, yes.

1566
01:27:57,000 --> 01:28:03,000
So I'm sitting in the house and I'm not going outside.

1567
01:28:03,000 --> 01:28:06,000
And my uncle shows up and he said, put your clothes on.

1568
01:28:06,000 --> 01:28:08,000
We're going to see Dr. King.

1569
01:28:08,000 --> 01:28:09,000
Okay.

1570
01:28:09,000 --> 01:28:12,000
You don't say no to your uncle.

1571
01:28:12,000 --> 01:28:15,000
And that might have been a male thing too.

1572
01:28:15,000 --> 01:28:16,000
You know?

1573
01:28:16,000 --> 01:28:17,000
He's the man in the house.

1574
01:28:17,000 --> 01:28:18,000
And he's an elder.

1575
01:28:18,000 --> 01:28:20,000
You have to listen kind of.

1576
01:28:20,000 --> 01:28:23,000
So I went with him to see Dr. King.

1577
01:28:23,000 --> 01:28:28,000
And Dr. King had young people with him and I was surprised.

1578
01:28:28,000 --> 01:28:31,000
It's like, I thought this was all old preachers.

1579
01:28:32,000 --> 01:28:33,000
What is this?

1580
01:28:33,000 --> 01:28:34,000
You know?

1581
01:28:34,000 --> 01:28:35,000
And I don't know.

1582
01:28:35,000 --> 01:28:36,000
The turning of the floor.

1583
01:28:36,000 --> 01:28:37,000
Yeah.

1584
01:28:37,000 --> 01:28:44,000
In 1966, the Meredith March, he had been one of the people who came at the end.

1585
01:28:44,000 --> 01:28:46,000
And he spoke at the rally.

1586
01:28:46,000 --> 01:28:49,000
I can't say that I listened.

1587
01:28:49,000 --> 01:28:50,000
But he spoke.

1588
01:28:50,000 --> 01:28:55,000
I heard his voice.

1589
01:28:55,000 --> 01:28:58,000
And people turned out in Batesville.

1590
01:28:58,000 --> 01:29:03,000
And there were just massive numbers of people there to hear Dr. King.

1591
01:29:03,000 --> 01:29:05,000
Which I thought was annoying again.

1592
01:29:05,000 --> 01:29:07,000
It was like, okay.

1593
01:29:07,000 --> 01:29:11,000
It's 1968.

1594
01:29:11,000 --> 01:29:18,000
But what it had done is exposed me that I was back in town.

1595
01:29:18,000 --> 01:29:27,000
And my friend, Tate, who had come from Washington and worked with Freedom Corps a little bit showed up at our house in like two weeks' time.

1596
01:29:27,000 --> 01:29:30,000
And I was going to say, I heard you were here.

1597
01:29:30,000 --> 01:29:33,000
And we were organizing the Poor People's Campaign.

1598
01:29:33,000 --> 01:29:35,000
That might have happened after King's assassination.

1599
01:29:35,000 --> 01:29:38,000
King was assassinated shortly after that.

1600
01:29:38,000 --> 01:29:41,000
Maybe the next couple of weeks.

1601
01:29:41,000 --> 01:29:46,000
And coming to help us organize for the Poor People's Campaign.

1602
01:29:46,000 --> 01:29:48,000
And I thought, that's silly.

1603
01:29:48,000 --> 01:29:51,000
Just going to Washington to March and Bade.

1604
01:29:51,000 --> 01:29:53,000
But okay.

1605
01:29:53,000 --> 01:29:56,000
And I went with her to Memphis.

1606
01:29:56,000 --> 01:30:00,000
Stayed at the Lorraine Motel where King had been assassinated.

1607
01:30:00,000 --> 01:30:05,000
And met these younger people who were working with SCLC.

1608
01:30:05,000 --> 01:30:12,000
And agreed that I would go and help them get folks on the buses to come to DC.

1609
01:30:12,000 --> 01:30:16,000
But I wasn't coming.

1610
01:30:16,000 --> 01:30:25,000
I went to Grenada and worked with this young guy named Leon Hall who was organizing for SCLC.

1611
01:30:25,000 --> 01:30:31,000
And once they got people all signed up to get on the buses to come to DC, I went to Mount Beulah.

1612
01:30:31,000 --> 01:30:33,000
And I was supposed to go back to Batesville.

1613
01:30:33,000 --> 01:30:35,000
I didn't really have any plans.

1614
01:30:35,000 --> 01:30:37,000
Like, what are you going to do now?

1615
01:30:37,000 --> 01:30:39,000
I don't know.

1616
01:30:39,000 --> 01:30:45,000
And Leon said, okay, go with us to Selma and then you can go home.

1617
01:30:45,000 --> 01:30:47,000
And I said, okay.

1618
01:30:47,000 --> 01:30:48,000
And went to Selma.

1619
01:30:48,000 --> 01:30:51,000
Some little kid in Selma said, can you stay with us?

1620
01:30:51,000 --> 01:30:52,000
And I said, sure.

1621
01:30:52,000 --> 01:30:54,000
He went and asked his mom.

1622
01:30:54,000 --> 01:30:56,000
And I spent the night at their house.

1623
01:30:56,000 --> 01:30:59,000
Next day, they said, come with us to Montgomery.

1624
01:30:59,000 --> 01:31:01,000
And then you can go home.

1625
01:31:01,000 --> 01:31:04,000
I stayed with Leon's family in Montgomery.

1626
01:31:04,000 --> 01:31:06,000
Come with us to Birmingham.

1627
01:31:06,000 --> 01:31:07,000
And then you can go home.

1628
01:31:07,000 --> 01:31:09,000
And I ended up in Washington.

1629
01:31:09,000 --> 01:31:11,000
And that's with the Poor People's Campaign.

1630
01:31:11,000 --> 01:31:13,000
With the Poor People's Campaign.

1631
01:31:13,000 --> 01:31:14,000
Yes.

1632
01:31:14,000 --> 01:31:15,000
So, was that the Mule Train?

1633
01:31:15,000 --> 01:31:16,000
Yeah.

1634
01:31:16,000 --> 01:31:17,000
Yeah.

1635
01:31:17,000 --> 01:31:18,000
Yeah.

1636
01:31:18,000 --> 01:31:19,000
That's the Mule Train.

1637
01:31:19,000 --> 01:31:20,000
Ended up in Washington, DC.

1638
01:31:20,000 --> 01:31:23,000
But was it like to travel with the Mule Train?

1639
01:31:23,000 --> 01:31:24,000
Hmm.

1640
01:31:24,000 --> 01:31:30,000
One of the interesting things, the Mule Train, I wasn't so much into.

1641
01:31:30,000 --> 01:31:37,000
But one of the things that happened, I think, in Birmingham, is I met these reporters

1642
01:31:37,000 --> 01:31:40,000
from the New York Times and the Washington Post.

1643
01:31:40,000 --> 01:31:45,000
That Earl called well, Gerald Fraser, he just died.

1644
01:31:45,000 --> 01:31:51,000
Thomas A. Johnson, with the [New York] Times of the New York Times, and Robert C. "Bob" Maynard from the Washington Post,

1645
01:31:51,000 --> 01:31:53,000
they were interesting.

1646
01:31:53,000 --> 01:31:56,000
So, I kind of hung out with them and listened to what they were doing.

1647
01:31:56,000 --> 01:31:59,000
And thought, hmm, interesting work.

1648
01:31:59,000 --> 01:32:00,000
Hmm.

1649
01:32:00,000 --> 01:32:02,000
Okay.

1650
01:32:02,000 --> 01:32:07,000
I think that was more interesting to me than trying to organize people to come to Washington

1651
01:32:07,000 --> 01:32:09,000
to sit in the tent city".

1652
01:32:09,000 --> 01:32:14,000
You said that you didn't really see the point of going to Washington to buy some bags?

1653
01:32:14,000 --> 01:32:15,000
Yeah.

1654
01:32:15,000 --> 01:32:16,000
What were you doing?

1655
01:32:16,000 --> 01:32:20,000
We have to figure a way to do it ourselves now.

1656
01:32:20,000 --> 01:32:22,000
Washington is not listening.

1657
01:32:22,000 --> 01:32:27,000
And I don't know when I came to that conclusion, but I had come to that conclusion.

1658
01:32:27,000 --> 01:32:34,000
I had come here, I think, in 1965, to help unseat the Mississippi delegation.

1659
01:32:34,000 --> 01:32:41,000
And we lobbied and set out in front of the Capitol all night and went home and nothing happened.

1660
01:32:41,000 --> 01:32:50,000
Same thing had happened in 1964, you know, with the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party going to Atlantic City.

1661
01:32:50,000 --> 01:32:58,000
And I didn't know for sure what we needed to do, but I thought we had to do something different than marching and begging.

1662
01:32:58,000 --> 01:33:01,000
I think that's where I was.

1663
01:33:01,000 --> 01:33:09,000
So in DC, Washington, I made it to Washington and they had put up tents on the National Mall.

1664
01:33:09,000 --> 01:33:18,000
And SCLC staff, oh, this is terrible, I didn't had rooms at the Pitts Motor Inn".

1665
01:33:18,000 --> 01:33:25,000
So the four people are staying in tents on the mall, and the staff, and then the hotel?

1666
01:33:25,000 --> 01:33:27,000
Yes.

1667
01:33:27,000 --> 01:33:29,000
I mean, the hotel too.

1668
01:33:29,000 --> 01:33:31,000
Did you think about that?

1669
01:33:31,000 --> 01:33:33,000
Of course I did.

1670
01:33:33,000 --> 01:33:37,000
I thought, you know, what a difference. What kind of thing are you doing here?

1671
01:33:37,000 --> 01:33:41,000
You have people living out here in mud because it was a muddy place.

1672
01:33:41,000 --> 01:33:50,000
And we are all sitting up in the pit smoder in, eating, and sleeping, warm, warm showers.

1673
01:33:50,000 --> 01:33:54,000
It's something unfair about this situation.

1674
01:33:55,000 --> 01:34:01,000
So I don't know how long I had been here, but one day we were driving down 14th Street.

1675
01:34:01,000 --> 01:34:04,000
I was with one of the preachers.

1676
01:34:04,000 --> 01:34:08,000
And this would have been after 14th Street, after the riots?

1677
01:34:08,000 --> 01:34:11,000
Yeah, this was 68th, after the riots.

1678
01:34:11,000 --> 01:34:14,000
And I see Charles E. Cobb Jr.

1679
01:34:14,000 --> 01:34:18,000
And I said to the preacher, pull over!

1680
01:34:19,000 --> 01:34:22,000
And he pulled over and I jumped out of the car and hugged Charlie.

1681
01:34:22,000 --> 01:34:25,000
And he told me that everybody is in Washington.

1682
01:34:25,000 --> 01:34:27,000
I said, you're kidding.

1683
01:34:27,000 --> 01:34:31,000
And he said, no, and I said, I'm out at what was it called?

1684
01:34:31,000 --> 01:34:35,000
Resurrection City with the preachers.

1685
01:34:35,000 --> 01:34:37,000
We need to do something.

1686
01:34:37,000 --> 01:34:41,000
We need to organize these people or do something.

1687
01:34:41,000 --> 01:34:43,000
And he said, where are you staying?

1688
01:34:43,000 --> 01:34:46,000
And I said to pits, motor in.

1689
01:34:46,000 --> 01:34:51,000
And he said, okay, and it was before a cell phone, so there was no way to call.

1690
01:34:51,000 --> 01:34:55,000
Went back to that place.

1691
01:34:55,000 --> 01:34:57,000
Resurrection City.

1692
01:34:57,000 --> 01:35:01,000
And did whatever we did.

1693
01:35:01,000 --> 01:35:04,000
I think I was supposed to be working with volunteers or something.

1694
01:35:04,000 --> 01:35:08,000
But I have vague recollection of what we did out there,

1695
01:35:08,000 --> 01:35:14,000
other than looking at people stumping around through mud and getting ready to go through demonstrations,

1696
01:35:14,000 --> 01:35:17,000
watching around the Department of Agriculture or something.

1697
01:35:17,000 --> 01:35:21,000
Do not have a very good image of that.

1698
01:35:21,000 --> 01:35:29,000
That evening I went back to the pits and Curtis, I think, came.

1699
01:35:29,000 --> 01:35:32,000
Curtis and his wife, Mimi, were here.

1700
01:35:32,000 --> 01:35:34,000
And he said, what are you doing?

1701
01:35:34,000 --> 01:35:38,000
And I said, I'm out in the mud with the people at Resurrection City.

1702
01:35:38,000 --> 01:35:40,000
He said, okay.

1703
01:35:40,000 --> 01:35:42,000
And the next day Frank showed up.

1704
01:35:42,000 --> 01:35:44,000
And he said, get your stuff.

1705
01:35:44,000 --> 01:35:45,000
Let's go.

1706
01:35:45,000 --> 01:35:47,000
You're getting out of here.

1707
01:35:47,000 --> 01:35:49,000
And I got my little bags.

1708
01:35:49,000 --> 01:35:55,000
And I left the pits, motor in in Resurrection City and the poor people's campaign.

1709
01:35:55,000 --> 01:35:59,000
And I had an apartment with a roommate.

1710
01:35:59,000 --> 01:36:03,000
And I became a student at the Institute for Policy Studies.

1711
01:36:03,000 --> 01:36:04,000
He was really?

1712
01:36:04,000 --> 01:36:06,000
Getting a little stifled.

1713
01:36:06,000 --> 01:36:08,000
Yes.

1714
01:36:08,000 --> 01:36:10,000
And going over there.

1715
01:36:11,000 --> 01:36:12,000
At the Institute?

1716
01:36:12,000 --> 01:36:13,000
Yes.

1717
01:36:13,000 --> 01:36:20,000
Frank Smith, Marvin Holloway, Ivanhoe Donaldson, were fellows at the Institute.

1718
01:36:20,000 --> 01:36:22,000
And I was a student.

1719
01:36:22,000 --> 01:36:23,000
I was Frank's student.

1720
01:36:23,000 --> 01:36:25,000
And I would go to seminars.

1721
01:36:25,000 --> 01:36:29,000
And I mainly went to the seminars, I think, to eat.

1722
01:36:29,000 --> 01:36:33,000
I don't know that that's true, but that's probably true.

1723
01:36:33,000 --> 01:36:39,000
And then shortly after that, somebody quit work at Drum and Spear Bookstore.

1724
01:36:39,000 --> 01:36:42,000
So I got a job at Drum and Spear Bookstore.

1725
01:36:42,000 --> 01:36:44,000
What was that like at the time?

1726
01:36:44,000 --> 01:36:45,000
Oh, it was wonderful.

1727
01:36:45,000 --> 01:36:52,000
I guess not everybody else would say what Drum and Spear Bookstore was started, I guess, by Charlie.

1728
01:36:52,000 --> 01:36:55,000
And a group called Afro-American Resources.

1729
01:36:55,000 --> 01:37:00,000
And it was every book in the world you could find about black people.

1730
01:37:00,000 --> 01:37:04,000
And I had never seen that many books about black people.

1731
01:37:04,000 --> 01:37:07,000
And I tried to read as many of them as I could.

1732
01:37:07,000 --> 01:37:12,000
So when people walked into the store and I'm looking for a book about such and such, I can say, look over here.

1733
01:37:12,000 --> 01:37:14,000
This book is wonderful.

1734
01:37:14,000 --> 01:37:23,000
It has, so that was my first real job, I guess, outside of the movement, but it was not really outside of the movement.

1735
01:37:23,000 --> 01:37:26,000
It was Drum and Spear Bookstore.

1736
01:37:26,000 --> 01:37:28,000
It was wonderful.

1737
01:37:28,000 --> 01:37:34,000
It was connected later with the Center for Black Education.

1738
01:37:35,000 --> 01:37:38,000
They were off-shoot of Federal City College.

1739
01:37:38,000 --> 01:37:43,000
A lot of the guys from the movement was teaching over there, black history, kind of stuff.

1740
01:37:43,000 --> 01:37:45,000
And I didn't go to the center a lot.

1741
01:37:45,000 --> 01:37:47,000
I mainly stayed at the bookstore.

1742
01:37:47,000 --> 01:37:56,000
And then there was a radio program on Sunday nights, Sauti ya Watoto.

1743
01:37:56,000 --> 01:37:57,000
Did you spell it?

1744
01:37:57,000 --> 01:37:59,000
Oh, please.

1745
01:37:59,000 --> 01:38:00,000
I wouldn't.

1746
01:38:00,000 --> 01:38:01,000
Okay.

1747
01:38:01,000 --> 01:38:03,000
Is that why he was?

1748
01:38:03,000 --> 01:38:04,000
Yeah.

1749
01:38:04,000 --> 01:38:05,000
Yeah.

1750
01:38:05,000 --> 01:38:06,000
Yeah.

1751
01:38:06,000 --> 01:38:17,000
And we did Mimi Curtis' former wife with do scripts from stories, regular stories.

1752
01:38:17,000 --> 01:38:23,000
And we would read them on the air on Sunday nights, Sunday nights, and take on the characters.

1753
01:38:23,000 --> 01:38:27,000
That was fun.

1754
01:38:27,000 --> 01:38:32,000
And you got authors coming to the bookstore to sign their books and to talk.

1755
01:38:32,000 --> 01:38:39,000
And I remember one Saturday I wasn't there, Lerone Bennett Jr, who wrote before the Mayflower,

1756
01:38:39,000 --> 01:38:43,000
was in the store signing books when the police tear gased the bookstore.

1757
01:38:43,000 --> 01:38:44,000
What?

1758
01:38:44,000 --> 01:38:45,000
Tear gased it.

1759
01:38:45,000 --> 01:38:47,000
Shot tear gas into the store.

1760
01:38:47,000 --> 01:38:48,000
What was there?

1761
01:38:48,000 --> 01:38:49,000
I don't know.

1762
01:38:49,000 --> 01:38:52,000
I have no idea.

1763
01:38:52,000 --> 01:38:54,000
I have no idea.

1764
01:38:54,000 --> 01:38:56,000
It was very strange.

1765
01:38:56,000 --> 01:39:01,000
It was Lerone Bennett Jr, the historian.

1766
01:39:02,000 --> 01:39:10,000
After that, I think we were always on the radar because it was old movement people in the bookstore.

1767
01:39:10,000 --> 01:39:16,000
We moved to a bigger place because people were ordering books from all over the country coming into the store,

1768
01:39:16,000 --> 01:39:19,000
doing their book signings and stuff.

1769
01:39:19,000 --> 01:39:22,000
So it expanded.

1770
01:39:22,000 --> 01:39:30,000
Ralph Featherstone, who had been an organizer in Mississippi, came to be the manager of the store.

1771
01:39:31,000 --> 01:39:33,000
Yeah, he was.

1772
01:39:33,000 --> 01:39:44,000
He was first Tony Gittens, then Featherstone.

1773
01:39:44,000 --> 01:39:47,000
So it became a little bit more political, I think.

1774
01:39:47,000 --> 01:39:54,000
People came into the store to talk and to get books and to tell us about books that they thought we should have.

1775
01:39:54,000 --> 01:39:58,000
It was one of the biggest, I guess, black bookstores in the country at the time.

1776
01:39:58,000 --> 01:40:01,000
Did you feel like this movement worked?

1777
01:40:01,000 --> 01:40:03,000
Yeah, actually.

1778
01:40:03,000 --> 01:40:04,000
Yeah, I did.

1779
01:40:04,000 --> 01:40:10,000
What was the thought of the answer to that question you had been asking about what to do instead of protesting?

1780
01:40:10,000 --> 01:40:17,000
No, not really, but it was something to do at the time.

1781
01:40:17,000 --> 01:40:24,000
We moved to a bigger place, meeting new people.

1782
01:40:24,000 --> 01:40:38,000
Then the day that two days after we moved to this bigger location, Featherstone was blown up in a car with [Che] Payne.

1783
01:40:38,000 --> 01:40:50,000
And we probably should have had some kind of psychological counseling, but we didn't, you know.

1784
01:40:50,000 --> 01:40:53,000
That was 1970, March 10th.

1785
01:40:53,000 --> 01:41:08,000
I didn't do very well with it, but Mimi, Curtis' former wife, had guessed money.

1786
01:41:08,000 --> 01:41:10,000
Did I get a job first?

1787
01:41:10,000 --> 01:41:12,000
Yes, I left the bookstore.

1788
01:41:12,000 --> 01:41:19,000
I went to work for the (likely) Black Child Development Institute, downtown DC, where you had to actually put on clothes.

1789
01:41:19,000 --> 01:41:22,000
You actually put on clothes to go to work.

1790
01:41:22,000 --> 01:41:25,000
You didn't wear your jeans and stuff.

1791
01:41:25,000 --> 01:41:31,000
And Met Florence Tate, who was like a big sister.

1792
01:41:31,000 --> 01:41:34,000
I got a job as a receptionist.

1793
01:41:34,000 --> 01:41:40,000
I had never had a job outside of the movement, a movement people before.

1794
01:41:40,000 --> 01:41:42,000
And I couldn't type really well.

1795
01:41:42,000 --> 01:41:48,000
I had taken typing in high school on a royal typewriter.

1796
01:41:48,000 --> 01:41:56,000
I had this new typewriter, and I'm over there making noise, pretending I'm typing while people are there and answering the phones.

1797
01:41:56,000 --> 01:42:00,000
And when they left to go home, I would do my work.

1798
01:42:00,000 --> 01:42:02,000
I would type the letters.

1799
01:42:02,000 --> 01:42:06,000
I should have been typing during the day.

1800
01:42:06,000 --> 01:42:10,000
So, is that because you didn't want people to know that I couldn't type?

1801
01:42:10,000 --> 01:42:12,000
Yeah, that was part of the job.

1802
01:42:12,000 --> 01:42:14,000
So I had to do my work.

1803
01:42:14,000 --> 01:42:15,000
So I would stay.

1804
01:42:15,000 --> 01:42:17,000
I'd get home at about 10 o'clock every night.

1805
01:42:17,000 --> 01:42:24,000
And then the head of the organization had some kind of black caucus meeting.

1806
01:42:24,000 --> 01:42:30,000
And she came in at lunchtime, and she needed me to type what she was saying.

1807
01:42:30,000 --> 01:42:35,000
And I was typing away, and she looked over and saw that I was on the paper.

1808
01:42:35,000 --> 01:42:40,000
And she sat down to the typewriter and typed her own work.

1809
01:42:40,000 --> 01:42:42,000
And went back to her meeting, and when she came back, she said,

1810
01:42:42,000 --> 01:42:44,000
how have you been getting out all of this work?

1811
01:42:44,000 --> 01:42:47,000
I said, when you go home in the evenings, I do my work.

1812
01:42:47,000 --> 01:42:50,000
And she said, I don't want you staying here late anymore.

1813
01:42:50,000 --> 01:42:53,000
I was also rewriting people.

1814
01:42:53,000 --> 01:42:55,000
I don't want you staying here late.

1815
01:42:55,000 --> 01:43:00,000
I'm going to get somebody to come in to do the work that you haven't finished and help you with your typing.

1816
01:43:00,000 --> 01:43:03,000
And I said, oh, okay, I wasn't fired.

1817
01:43:03,000 --> 01:43:08,000
I was now, I think I became a program analyst or something.

1818
01:43:08,000 --> 01:43:13,000
So I could do a little writing, rewriting, and typing at my own pace.

1819
01:43:13,000 --> 01:43:15,000
And that was a three month project.

1820
01:43:15,000 --> 01:43:20,000
When that was over, we went off to the West Indies.

1821
01:43:20,000 --> 01:43:26,000
First to Haiti, no Puerto Rico first, with Judy and Mimi.

1822
01:43:26,000 --> 01:43:33,000
Puerto Rico first, then to Haiti, and then to Trinidad.

1823
01:43:34,000 --> 01:43:35,000
That's Judy Richardson?

1824
01:43:35,000 --> 01:43:38,000
Yeah, Barbados.

1825
01:43:38,000 --> 01:43:40,000
We were gone for a minute.

1826
01:43:40,000 --> 01:43:44,000
So this is like, we're going to go and see these places explore?

1827
01:43:44,000 --> 01:43:50,000
I think so, but I think it was also a mental health issue that we didn't ever talk about.

1828
01:43:50,000 --> 01:43:54,000
It was really good.

1829
01:43:54,000 --> 01:43:56,000
It was a good trip.

1830
01:43:56,000 --> 01:43:58,000
Haiti I loved.

1831
01:43:58,000 --> 01:44:06,000
And one of the things that somebody said is when you get off the plane, say what you want to do while you're here, somebody will hear you.

1832
01:44:06,000 --> 01:44:10,000
And I said, I want to go to a voodoo ceremony.

1833
01:44:10,000 --> 01:44:17,000
And about three days in, and then another guy, old man came and said, I take care of you girls.

1834
01:44:17,000 --> 01:44:21,000
And he grabbed our stuff and took us off to the hotel where we were supposed to stay.

1835
01:44:21,000 --> 01:44:29,000
He argued with the manager, we left there and went to another hotel because he didn't like what the guy was charging us or something.

1836
01:44:29,000 --> 01:44:32,000
He actually did take care of us.

1837
01:44:32,000 --> 01:44:36,000
About three days in, some man came and said, I came to take you to the voodoo.

1838
01:44:36,000 --> 01:44:38,000
He said, you want to go to the voodoo?

1839
01:44:38,000 --> 01:44:39,000
Yeah.

1840
01:44:39,000 --> 01:44:41,000
He took us.

1841
01:44:41,000 --> 01:44:42,000
Yeah, it was amazing.

1842
01:44:42,000 --> 01:44:44,000
I was so scared I didn't know what to do with myself.

1843
01:44:44,000 --> 01:44:47,000
I didn't know what to expect.

1844
01:44:47,000 --> 01:44:54,000
And all of a sudden you're hearing these drums and these people are singing something you don't know what they're saying.

1845
01:44:54,000 --> 01:44:56,000
And I'm scared.

1846
01:44:56,000 --> 01:44:57,000
Okay.

1847
01:44:57,000 --> 01:45:01,000
We left there finally and I prayed.

1848
01:45:01,000 --> 01:45:03,000
This was the time.

1849
01:45:03,000 --> 01:45:05,000
Well, please don't go back with us.

1850
01:45:05,000 --> 01:45:07,000
I don't know what they were saying.

1851
01:45:07,000 --> 01:45:09,000
I promise you I won't come back.

1852
01:45:09,000 --> 01:45:11,000
You mentioned the drums.

1853
01:45:11,000 --> 01:45:15,000
And earlier, I think before we started the interview, you said that there was drumming in Canola County.

1854
01:45:15,000 --> 01:45:17,000
Northern Mississippi.

1855
01:45:17,000 --> 01:45:18,000
Yeah.

1856
01:45:18,000 --> 01:45:20,000
And Panolla County, yes.

1857
01:45:20,000 --> 01:45:21,000
Can you tell us about that?

1858
01:45:21,000 --> 01:45:22,000
A little bit.

1859
01:45:22,000 --> 01:45:24,000
I didn't know a lot at the time.

1860
01:45:24,000 --> 01:45:31,000
Two days, every July, third and fourth, there were these old men who played drums.

1861
01:45:31,000 --> 01:45:36,000
And the first thing you heard on the third was a big, big boom, a boom sound.

1862
01:45:36,000 --> 01:45:38,000
And it was like, you knew the drums were there.

1863
01:45:38,000 --> 01:45:41,000
You got new clothes to go to the event.

1864
01:45:41,000 --> 01:45:47,000
A baseball team came to play baseball with the neighborhood guys against the neighborhood guys.

1865
01:45:47,000 --> 01:45:51,000
We got our new clothes and we went to the picnic.

1866
01:45:51,000 --> 01:45:55,000
That's what it was called and everybody came.

1867
01:45:55,000 --> 01:46:00,000
These old men had a fire going to heat the drums, the skins on the drum.

1868
01:46:00,000 --> 01:46:04,000
And they played and only the men danced to it.

1869
01:46:04,000 --> 01:46:07,000
The women were making...

1870
01:46:07,000 --> 01:46:08,000
No.

1871
01:46:08,000 --> 01:46:10,000
The women were cooking.

1872
01:46:10,000 --> 01:46:15,000
The kids were dancing to the jukebox when the old men stopped playing.

1873
01:46:15,000 --> 01:46:17,000
And it was like, will they hurry up and finish?

1874
01:46:17,000 --> 01:46:21,000
I was embarrassed because my stepfather danced, so did his brother.

1875
01:46:21,000 --> 01:46:25,000
You know it was like, oh, they're so embarrassing.

1876
01:46:25,000 --> 01:46:31,000
And they came every July, third and fourth, two days.

1877
01:46:31,000 --> 01:46:33,000
And everybody came.

1878
01:46:33,000 --> 01:46:35,000
I mean, the whole neighborhood turned out.

1879
01:46:35,000 --> 01:46:38,000
For the baseball game first and then the drumming in the evening,

1880
01:46:38,000 --> 01:46:41,000
had no idea it was African.

1881
01:46:41,000 --> 01:46:43,000
No idea.

1882
01:46:43,000 --> 01:46:44,000
No idea.

1883
01:46:44,000 --> 01:46:52,000
And then, some years ago, one of my girlfriends who had come to work with us in Freedom Corps for a second,

1884
01:46:52,000 --> 01:46:54,000
so do you remember the drums?

1885
01:46:54,000 --> 01:47:02,000
Those old men playing drums and I said, yeah, they had five flute made from cane.

1886
01:47:03,000 --> 01:47:08,000
I said, yeah, and I went online and looked for them and found them.

1887
01:47:08,000 --> 01:47:13,000
The Smithsonian recorded them in the 1940s.

1888
01:47:13,000 --> 01:47:18,000
Trace the rhythms that they were playing back to West Africa, Mali.

1889
01:47:18,000 --> 01:47:23,000
And I said, oh, my goodness, we were doing that then and I had no clue.

1890
01:47:23,000 --> 01:47:25,000
That's the thing, isn't it?

1891
01:47:25,000 --> 01:47:30,000
Uh-huh, then I asked one of my cousins, did you ever go to the picnics and he said, yeah, I went.

1892
01:47:30,000 --> 01:47:32,000
Everybody went.

1893
01:47:32,000 --> 01:47:35,000
Uh-huh, so it was like a neighborhood gathering for two days.

1894
01:47:35,000 --> 01:47:37,000
Did they play in other places?

1895
01:47:37,000 --> 01:47:39,000
Yeah, all over northern Mississippi.

1896
01:47:39,000 --> 01:47:41,000
So you all got them for the Fourth of July?

1897
01:47:41,000 --> 01:47:43,000
And third, the third and fourth, uh-huh.

1898
01:47:43,000 --> 01:47:45,000
But they would play in other places.

1899
01:47:45,000 --> 01:47:46,000
Yeah.

1900
01:47:46,000 --> 01:47:47,000
Uh-huh.

1901
01:47:47,000 --> 01:47:55,000
Alan Lomax wrote that the women in other parts of the state saluted the drums.

1902
01:47:55,000 --> 01:47:56,000
We didn't do that.

1903
01:47:56,000 --> 01:47:57,000
We didn't know.

1904
01:47:57,000 --> 01:48:05,000
Well, you know, and that they killed slotted goats and served goat sandwiches.

1905
01:48:05,000 --> 01:48:06,000
We didn't do all of that.

1906
01:48:06,000 --> 01:48:10,000
We had the normal, you know, picnic food.

1907
01:48:10,000 --> 01:48:14,000
You can buy a fish sandwich and sow this.

1908
01:48:15,000 --> 01:48:18,000
And did they still do it?

1909
01:48:18,000 --> 01:48:20,000
The drummers.

1910
01:48:20,000 --> 01:48:27,000
the granddaughter of Othar Turner was supposed to hold the group together.

1911
01:48:27,000 --> 01:48:32,000
I haven't seen them since, and I promised one of my cousins that I was going to look for the recordings,

1912
01:48:32,000 --> 01:48:36,000
because the younger people do not know about it, you know?

1913
01:48:36,000 --> 01:48:42,000
Everybody moved away from the farms, and the older people didn't share.

1914
01:48:43,000 --> 01:48:45,000
It didn't tell us what was going on.

1915
01:48:45,000 --> 01:48:48,000
So, um, was the Turner?

1916
01:48:48,000 --> 01:48:51,000
Othar Turner came after Sid Hemphill.

1917
01:48:51,000 --> 01:48:57,000
They have a, um, a statue or a plaque or something to him in northern Penole County.

1918
01:48:57,000 --> 01:49:00,000
And so it is a someplace like that.

1919
01:49:00,000 --> 01:49:04,000
Because I believe his grandfather and a group played at this messoing in football.

1920
01:49:04,000 --> 01:49:06,000
I heard that.

1921
01:49:06,000 --> 01:49:07,000
I heard that.

1922
01:49:07,000 --> 01:49:09,000
I didn't know it, so I missed them.

1923
01:49:09,000 --> 01:49:10,000
I would have gone.

1924
01:49:10,000 --> 01:49:11,000
I would have danced.

1925
01:49:12,000 --> 01:49:14,000
That's what we're looking for.

1926
01:49:14,000 --> 01:49:16,000
We're looking for the 40s, though.

1927
01:49:16,000 --> 01:49:18,000
And so, yeah, but I think they have a recording.

1928
01:49:18,000 --> 01:49:19,000
I know they have a recording.

1929
01:49:19,000 --> 01:49:22,000
I don't know if it's online, from the more recent ones.

1930
01:49:22,000 --> 01:49:23,000
Mm-hmm.

1931
01:49:23,000 --> 01:49:26,000
I have a record called Penole even played County plays.

1932
01:49:26,000 --> 01:49:28,000
Are you serious?

1933
01:49:28,000 --> 01:49:30,000
That's what we're talking about.

1934
01:49:30,000 --> 01:49:31,000
Oh, please do.

1935
01:49:31,000 --> 01:49:32,000
I don't know.

1936
01:49:32,000 --> 01:49:33,000
Oh, please.

1937
01:49:33,000 --> 01:49:34,000
I'll do the basement.

1938
01:49:34,000 --> 01:49:35,000
Oh, please.

1939
01:49:35,000 --> 01:49:36,000
Oh, yeah.

1940
01:49:37,000 --> 01:49:38,000
Mm-hmm.

1941
01:49:38,000 --> 01:49:45,000
I wanted to ask, um, I want to go back if it's okay.

1942
01:49:45,000 --> 01:49:46,000
Yeah.

1943
01:49:46,000 --> 01:49:50,000
And I'm still stuck on the fact that you're in church and you're supposed to play amazing grace.

1944
01:49:50,000 --> 01:49:52,000
And you come out with, uh, old freedom.

1945
01:49:52,000 --> 01:49:53,000
Yeah.

1946
01:49:53,000 --> 01:49:54,000
It was wonderful.

1947
01:49:54,000 --> 01:49:55,000
I lived.

1948
01:49:55,000 --> 01:49:56,000
I lived.

1949
01:49:56,000 --> 01:49:57,000
I lived.

1950
01:49:57,000 --> 01:50:01,000
I only know of one person who protested very strongly.

1951
01:50:01,000 --> 01:50:05,000
And I've since seen her and sort of made peace with her.

1952
01:50:05,000 --> 01:50:08,000
And I was like, this girl has lost her mind.

1953
01:50:08,000 --> 01:50:16,000
But it was also after I was almost 18 and I stopped playing at the church after I graduated

1954
01:50:16,000 --> 01:50:18,000
high school because I left.

1955
01:50:18,000 --> 01:50:20,000
And didn't have to do it anymore.

1956
01:50:20,000 --> 01:50:26,000
So by the time you do this, the movement is really kind of big and put a family of a lot of people

1957
01:50:26,000 --> 01:50:27,000
into it.

1958
01:50:27,000 --> 01:50:31,000
They know it, but that's not what you do in church unless it's a mass meeting where you're singing

1959
01:50:31,000 --> 01:50:32,000
freedom songs.

1960
01:50:32,000 --> 01:50:33,000
You're mixing it.

1961
01:50:33,000 --> 01:50:35,000
And what your mom say.

1962
01:50:35,000 --> 01:50:36,000
Nothing.

1963
01:50:36,000 --> 01:50:40,000
She didn't tell me I better not do it again or any of that.

1964
01:50:40,000 --> 01:50:41,000
She didn't.

1965
01:50:41,000 --> 01:50:43,000
My friends did the choir.

1966
01:50:43,000 --> 01:50:45,000
We knew the songs.

1967
01:50:45,000 --> 01:50:46,000
We knew.

1968
01:50:46,000 --> 01:50:47,000
I don't think so.

1969
01:50:47,000 --> 01:50:49,000
I think I just did it.

1970
01:50:49,000 --> 01:50:57,000
And the choir was mostly my friends that I had been with since I was 10.

1971
01:50:57,000 --> 01:50:58,000
You know.

1972
01:50:58,000 --> 01:51:00,000
So we knew what to do with each other.

1973
01:51:00,000 --> 01:51:01,000
You know.

1974
01:51:01,000 --> 01:51:03,000
But did the minister want to do movement supporters?

1975
01:51:03,000 --> 01:51:04,000
No.

1976
01:51:04,000 --> 01:51:08,000
I don't remember him ever mentioning anything about the movement.

1977
01:51:08,000 --> 01:51:10,000
Can he didn't say nothing to you?

1978
01:51:10,000 --> 01:51:11,000
No.

1979
01:51:11,000 --> 01:51:12,000
Nobody did.

1980
01:51:12,000 --> 01:51:13,000
Yes.

1981
01:51:13,000 --> 01:51:19,000
The Deacon, after that meeting that we had at church with the record, they started locking the church.

1982
01:51:19,000 --> 01:51:30,000
And the Deacon went around to the different houses saying your children are getting involved with this stuff and you better talk to them because I'm not getting them out of jail

1983
01:51:30,000 --> 01:51:32,000
and they don't know if they get arrested.

1984
01:51:32,000 --> 01:51:34,000
He went from house to house.

1985
01:51:34,000 --> 01:51:44,000
But by the time 1964 rolled around, he actually kept in his house a couple of the volunteers.

1986
01:51:44,000 --> 01:51:47,000
So people were moving in the direction of the movement?

1987
01:51:47,000 --> 01:51:48,000
Yes.

1988
01:51:48,000 --> 01:51:49,000
Yeah.

1989
01:51:49,000 --> 01:51:54,000
So you weren't allowed to use the church for meetings after that?

1990
01:51:54,000 --> 01:51:55,000
Well, I got up.

1991
01:51:55,000 --> 01:51:57,000
We had something called, what was the thing called?

1992
01:51:57,000 --> 01:52:04,000
All the requires got together to sing one Sunday a month from different churches.

1993
01:52:04,000 --> 01:52:10,000
And I think I did get up and announce that they had locked out church and we could no longer meet there.

1994
01:52:10,000 --> 01:52:11,000
And I did it.

1995
01:52:11,000 --> 01:52:14,000
It wasn't completely innocent.

1996
01:52:14,000 --> 01:52:18,000
And somebody from West Camp got up and said, our church is always open to you.

1997
01:52:18,000 --> 01:52:20,000
If you need to meet, you can meet here.

1998
01:52:20,000 --> 01:52:22,000
Did you do that to him?

1999
01:52:22,000 --> 01:52:23,000
Yeah.

2000
01:52:23,000 --> 01:52:29,000
I think we went to West Camp once, but it was not in the neighborhood and you had to get a ride.

2001
01:52:29,000 --> 01:52:34,000
Although a group of a 16-year-old Mrs. Glover let us use her car.

2002
01:52:34,000 --> 01:52:38,000
Her daughter, who was my age, could drive us anyplace.

2003
01:52:38,000 --> 01:52:41,000
We would even drive off to Memphis to get a 5-cent adog.

2004
01:52:41,000 --> 01:52:43,000
How old were you all from Memphis?

2005
01:52:43,000 --> 01:52:44,000
59 miles.

2006
01:52:44,000 --> 01:52:48,000
So it's like the big city.

2007
01:52:48,000 --> 01:52:49,000
Oh, yeah.

2008
01:52:49,000 --> 01:52:50,000
It was the city.

2009
01:52:51,000 --> 01:52:56,000
What was greener like when you went in there in 63 for that week?

2010
01:52:56,000 --> 01:52:59,000
Can you describe the community at all?

2011
01:52:59,000 --> 01:53:02,000
It was mostly movement people that I saw.

2012
01:53:02,000 --> 01:53:06,000
We went to eat at somebody's house who invited us over for dinner.

2013
01:53:06,000 --> 01:53:08,000
That was good.

2014
01:53:08,000 --> 01:53:13,000
It seemed to be much more active than Batesville was at the time.

2015
01:53:13,000 --> 01:53:17,000
You know, like I said, after Medgar Evers was killed, there was a mass meeting.

2016
01:53:18,000 --> 01:53:22,000
And the church was packed and people were out on the streets.

2017
01:53:22,000 --> 01:53:24,000
You know, the people who couldn't get in.

2018
01:53:24,000 --> 01:53:26,000
I had never seen that before.

2019
01:53:26,000 --> 01:53:31,000
So it was a movement city, a town.

2020
01:53:31,000 --> 01:53:33,000
Mm-hmm.

2021
01:53:33,000 --> 01:53:36,000
Other people that you met that stand out was like,

2022
01:53:36,000 --> 01:53:39,000
some of the two who's being there, like Joyce Ladner?

2023
01:53:39,000 --> 01:53:40,000
No.

2024
01:53:40,000 --> 01:53:42,000
Freddie Green was there.

2025
01:53:42,000 --> 01:53:43,000
Yeah.

2026
01:53:43,000 --> 01:53:44,000
Freddie was there.

2027
01:53:44,000 --> 01:53:46,000
Freddie's family is from Greenwood.

2028
01:53:47,000 --> 01:53:49,000
And she was a student at Dillard.

2029
01:53:49,000 --> 01:53:51,000
I think she was a freshman.

2030
01:53:51,000 --> 01:53:55,000
And my cousin was a freshman at Mississippi Valley State.

2031
01:53:55,000 --> 01:53:57,000
So they got to know each other.

2032
01:53:57,000 --> 01:54:01,000
And then I ran into Freddie, you know, over and over again after that.

2033
01:54:01,000 --> 01:54:02,000
Yeah.

2034
01:54:02,000 --> 01:54:03,000
Mm-hmm.

2035
01:54:05,000 --> 01:54:09,000
I know Mr. Vile was one of the really important leaders.

2036
01:54:09,000 --> 01:54:10,000
Absolutely.

2037
01:54:10,000 --> 01:54:12,000
Can you tell us what he was like?

2038
01:54:12,000 --> 01:54:18,000
He lived right down the road from us before my mom got remarried.

2039
01:54:18,000 --> 01:54:20,000
Very strong man.

2040
01:54:20,000 --> 01:54:22,000
He had a farm.

2041
01:54:22,000 --> 01:54:30,000
I knew his sons, the two older sons, Vincent and Robert Jr. miles.

2042
01:54:30,000 --> 01:54:33,000
Everybody knew that he was a movement man.

2043
01:54:33,000 --> 01:54:40,000
He was a member of West Camp Missionary Baptist Church.

2044
01:54:40,000 --> 01:54:46,000
And he looked after us, like when my mom was at work and we were tear down the two rooms.

2045
01:54:46,000 --> 01:54:48,000
One night we were playing church.

2046
01:54:48,000 --> 01:54:51,000
And Robert Miles knocked on the door because he heard all the noise.

2047
01:54:51,000 --> 01:54:55,000
To check on us, mother was at work until 8 o'clock, you know.

2048
01:54:55,000 --> 01:54:59,000
And we fell all in the floor and tried to crawl under the beds because it scared us.

2049
01:54:59,000 --> 01:55:01,000
But he just wanted to know what we were doing.

2050
01:55:01,000 --> 01:55:02,000
Yeah.

2051
01:55:02,000 --> 01:55:03,000
Yeah.

2052
01:55:03,000 --> 01:55:06,000
He was like that even before we knew that he was a big movement man.

2053
01:55:06,000 --> 01:55:07,000
Yeah.

2054
01:55:07,000 --> 01:55:08,000
He was really a community person.

2055
01:55:08,000 --> 01:55:09,000
Yeah, he was.

2056
01:55:09,000 --> 01:55:10,000
Yeah.

2057
01:55:10,000 --> 01:55:12,000
Our little road was pretty close knit.

2058
01:55:12,000 --> 01:55:13,000
Mm-hmm.

2059
01:55:13,000 --> 01:55:18,000
Who was the one in the community that were involved in the movement?

2060
01:55:18,000 --> 01:55:21,000
What were they like?

2061
01:55:21,000 --> 01:55:25,000
They didn't take Mrs. Glover.

2062
01:55:25,000 --> 01:55:30,000
The one with Glover is the person who sticks out immediately.

2063
01:55:30,000 --> 01:55:33,000
She was a local teacher.

2064
01:55:33,000 --> 01:55:36,000
And she went to the meetings.

2065
01:55:36,000 --> 01:55:37,000
She made speeches.

2066
01:55:37,000 --> 01:55:43,000
And I told you, she was the one who stood in the little thing between the cops and us praying.

2067
01:55:43,000 --> 01:55:48,000
Her children, two of her children at least were involved in the movement, Faye and LaWita.

2068
01:55:48,000 --> 01:55:54,000
LaWita ended up going to the University of Illinois and becoming a lawyer in Chicago.

2069
01:55:54,000 --> 01:55:59,000
Faye became a teacher in Chicago.

2070
01:55:59,000 --> 01:56:02,000
This Glover was one of the outspoken women.

2071
01:56:02,000 --> 01:56:05,000
Mrs. Pearl Robinson was one of the active women.

2072
01:56:05,000 --> 01:56:08,000
I don't remember her making speeches.

2073
01:56:08,000 --> 01:56:12,000
Mrs. Virgil Robinson, again, was one of the active women.

2074
01:56:12,000 --> 01:56:15,000
Don't remember her speaking publicly anyplace.

2075
01:56:15,000 --> 01:56:20,000
So when you said they were active but they didn't speak publicly, what were some of the things that they would do?

2076
01:56:20,000 --> 01:56:23,000
Make sure people got to the polls to vote.

2077
01:56:23,000 --> 01:56:27,000
Make sure they tried to register to vote.

2078
01:56:27,000 --> 01:56:30,000
I think they took in civil rights workers.

2079
01:56:30,000 --> 01:56:33,000
A Claire, Claire, Claire, what's her name?

2080
01:56:33,000 --> 01:56:35,000
Lawson was Mrs. Pearl's daughter.

2081
01:56:35,000 --> 01:56:40,000
She was also one of the active women.

2082
01:56:40,000 --> 01:56:50,000
The Thomas says the owner of the sundry where everybody hung out in 64 had not been active before.

2083
01:56:50,000 --> 01:56:54,000
But the sundry was a place where people hung out.

2084
01:56:54,000 --> 01:57:00,000
There were people who were moved with people.

2085
01:57:00,000 --> 01:57:05,000
And I don't remember them ever being really active.

2086
01:57:05,000 --> 01:57:08,000
But they were okay with people using their hands.

2087
01:57:08,000 --> 01:57:10,000
In 64.

2088
01:57:10,000 --> 01:57:12,000
Not before 1964.

2089
01:57:12,000 --> 01:57:17,000
So some people are definitely responding to these outside people.

2090
01:57:17,000 --> 01:57:19,000
Is it because they're outside?

2091
01:57:19,000 --> 01:57:20,000
And they're white.

2092
01:57:20,000 --> 01:57:25,000
And I think people from a distance, we didn't really know them up close and personal.

2093
01:57:25,000 --> 01:57:32,000
And I think it was really something to see them walking in our neighborhood and talking to us and embracing us.

2094
01:57:32,000 --> 01:57:35,000
And people were sort of shocked by it.

2095
01:57:35,000 --> 01:57:39,000
I think so.

2096
01:57:39,000 --> 01:57:46,000
And did you become friends with any of the white volunteers?

2097
01:57:46,000 --> 01:57:48,000
Penny Patch?

2098
01:57:48,000 --> 01:57:49,000
Yeah, I remember Penny.

2099
01:57:49,000 --> 01:57:51,000
I wasn't really friends with her.

2100
01:57:51,000 --> 01:58:00,000
But Claire, O'Connor, from Minnesota.

2101
01:58:00,000 --> 01:58:03,000
We watched them.

2102
01:58:03,000 --> 01:58:04,000
Yeah, we watched them.

2103
01:58:04,000 --> 01:58:05,000
What are they going to do now?

2104
01:58:05,000 --> 01:58:09,000
Let's watch them.

2105
01:58:09,000 --> 01:58:12,000
Did you do gal with them or anything like that?

2106
01:58:12,000 --> 01:58:17,000
I was sort of off the table as far as my mom was concerned.

2107
01:58:17,000 --> 01:58:21,000
Because they were going to leave and you would be here.

2108
01:58:21,000 --> 01:58:26,000
And so I sort of worked with my friends.

2109
01:58:26,000 --> 01:58:31,000
When we did sit-in stuff, then we did it all together.

2110
01:58:31,000 --> 01:58:34,000
Did other people work with them?

2111
01:58:34,000 --> 01:58:35,000
Yeah.

2112
01:58:35,000 --> 01:58:39,000
I'm listening to some of them trying to keep you a little separate.

2113
01:58:39,000 --> 01:58:41,000
Trying to keep you safe.

2114
01:58:41,000 --> 01:58:46,000
Yeah, we had that trouble in the family before the 60s.

2115
01:58:46,000 --> 01:58:47,000
Yeah.

2116
01:58:47,000 --> 01:58:48,000
Like what kind of trouble?

2117
01:58:48,000 --> 01:58:51,000
Oh, it was serious trouble.

2118
01:58:51,000 --> 01:58:53,000
Gosh.

2119
01:58:53,000 --> 01:59:00,000
One of my uncles had been in town, not Batesville, Pope,

2120
01:59:00,000 --> 01:59:05,000
another little town, and he was jumped by a group of flight men

2121
01:59:05,000 --> 01:59:08,000
who went out with white men.

2122
01:59:08,000 --> 01:59:11,000
And that was not, you couldn't do that.

2123
01:59:11,000 --> 01:59:14,000
So they were going to teach the younger brother,

2124
01:59:14,000 --> 01:59:17,000
and I don't know which of the brothers they were after.

2125
01:59:17,000 --> 01:59:19,000
They were going to teach him a lesson.

2126
01:59:19,000 --> 01:59:22,000
But he was armed and dangerous.

2127
01:59:22,000 --> 01:59:26,000
So I don't know if more than one person was killed,

2128
01:59:26,000 --> 01:59:28,000
but I know one person was paralyzed.

2129
01:59:28,000 --> 01:59:30,000
One person was killed.

2130
01:59:30,000 --> 01:59:34,000
One of my uncles who had been in town,

2131
01:59:34,000 --> 01:59:38,000
one of my uncles who had been in World War II,

2132
01:59:38,000 --> 01:59:43,000
and my dad went to the aid of the younger brother.

2133
01:59:43,000 --> 01:59:47,000
And the one uncle took responsibility,

2134
01:59:47,000 --> 01:59:51,000
actually, it was just recently we found out that he didn't do it.

2135
01:59:51,000 --> 01:59:56,000
He left his car in town so they would think it was him,

2136
01:59:56,000 --> 02:00:00,000
took the weapon, and left over bullets, and got out of town.

2137
02:00:00,000 --> 02:00:07,000
And he was a grandmother and a younger cousin to the woods

2138
02:00:07,000 --> 02:00:10,000
and said, we'll kill her if you don't turn yourself in.

2139
02:00:10,000 --> 02:00:14,000
So he turned himself in, which was the plan in the first place.

2140
02:00:14,000 --> 02:00:17,000
And they brought him back to Batesville.

2141
02:00:17,000 --> 02:00:20,000
They first, you know, in Oxford, he was in Oxford for a while.

2142
02:00:20,000 --> 02:00:24,000
Brought him back to Batesville and tried him and found him guilty of murder

2143
02:00:24,000 --> 02:00:29,000
and electrocuted him, like in 1952.

2144
02:00:29,000 --> 02:00:32,000
I guess.

2145
02:00:32,000 --> 02:00:37,000
And then 11 months later, my dad died mysteriously.

2146
02:00:37,000 --> 02:00:41,000
The secret word in the family was, he was poisoned.

2147
02:00:41,000 --> 02:00:46,000
He died exactly 11 months later.

2148
02:00:46,000 --> 02:00:51,000
The family moved away to, after the trouble,

2149
02:00:51,000 --> 02:00:56,000
they sold the farm and moved to King's Court, Tennessee.

2150
02:00:56,000 --> 02:00:58,000
That's dad family?

2151
02:00:58,000 --> 02:01:01,000
Yeah.

2152
02:01:01,000 --> 02:01:05,000
Do you know how the family story, how they put it, is poison?

2153
02:01:05,000 --> 02:01:07,000
Yeah.

2154
02:01:07,000 --> 02:01:08,000
Yeah, they think.

2155
02:01:08,000 --> 02:01:13,000
There was a doctor who took care of the black families, Dr. Martin.

2156
02:01:13,000 --> 02:01:15,000
And he would make house calls.

2157
02:01:15,000 --> 02:01:17,000
He took care of everybody.

2158
02:01:17,000 --> 02:01:20,000
He would go to black gatherings.

2159
02:01:20,000 --> 02:01:29,000
And my dad was given medicine for blood pressure or something.

2160
02:01:29,000 --> 02:01:35,000
And that was, we think, what might have taken him out?

2161
02:01:35,000 --> 02:01:37,000
So were you aware of this at the time?

2162
02:01:37,000 --> 02:01:39,000
Oh no, I had no idea what death was.

2163
02:01:39,000 --> 02:01:43,000
I was aware that there was trouble, because I listened,

2164
02:01:43,000 --> 02:01:46,000
and Eve's dropped on adults all the time.

2165
02:01:46,000 --> 02:01:52,000
And when my dad died, my mom, my uncle told her,

2166
02:01:52,000 --> 02:01:57,000
not my, her brother, but her dad's brother came in to tell her he was gone.

2167
02:01:57,000 --> 02:02:03,000
He also came to tell her when Uncle Lionel was electrocuted.

2168
02:02:03,000 --> 02:02:05,000
And I heard it.

2169
02:02:05,000 --> 02:02:11,000
And so she called me in, because they were trying to figure out how to tell me.

2170
02:02:11,000 --> 02:02:15,000
And I thought, okay, so I already know, but I won't let them know I know.

2171
02:02:15,000 --> 02:02:21,000
And so I went inside and mother said, your dad's dead.

2172
02:02:21,000 --> 02:02:26,000
I said, okay, I guess I'll figure out how to cry at the funeral somehow.

2173
02:02:26,000 --> 02:02:29,000
It was like acting to me.

2174
02:02:29,000 --> 02:02:32,000
It was death that meant nothing to me.

2175
02:02:32,000 --> 02:02:34,000
It was just not real.

2176
02:02:34,000 --> 02:02:38,000
You know, you go and you do performance at the church.

2177
02:02:38,000 --> 02:02:41,000
And then you're going about your business.

2178
02:02:41,000 --> 02:02:47,000
So, not initially, I told you it was performance art.

2179
02:02:47,000 --> 02:02:50,000
When they brought the cat, I remember it very well.

2180
02:02:50,000 --> 02:02:53,000
And I don't know whether I was four or five years old.

2181
02:02:53,000 --> 02:02:58,000
They brought the casket into the church covered in the flag.

2182
02:02:58,000 --> 02:03:00,000
Yeah, he was in World War II.

2183
02:03:00,000 --> 02:03:02,000
He went overseas.

2184
02:03:02,000 --> 02:03:04,000
And my auntie started to cry.

2185
02:03:04,000 --> 02:03:10,000
And I had to nut her and say, it's not time yet.

2186
02:03:10,000 --> 02:03:13,000
We are doing performance here.

2187
02:03:13,000 --> 02:03:14,000
It's not time yet.

2188
02:03:14,000 --> 02:03:20,000
And then I watched my older cousin to see when I was supposed to start crying because I wasn't sure.

2189
02:03:20,000 --> 02:03:22,000
You know, and I would look back.

2190
02:03:22,000 --> 02:03:25,000
She was sitting on the front row and she was sitting in a row behind me.

2191
02:03:25,000 --> 02:03:27,000
And I'd look back.

2192
02:03:27,000 --> 02:03:32,000
And then when the preacher finished preaching and everybody finished singing and they opened the casket,

2193
02:03:32,000 --> 02:03:36,000
I looked back and she was squeezing her eyes together to make tears.

2194
02:03:36,000 --> 02:03:40,000
And I thought, oh, it's time.

2195
02:03:40,000 --> 02:03:42,000
And so I did my crying.

2196
02:03:42,000 --> 02:03:44,000
Yeah.

2197
02:03:44,000 --> 02:03:49,000
So because of that, you're extending family with more cautious around my folks?

2198
02:03:49,000 --> 02:03:51,000
No.

2199
02:03:51,000 --> 02:03:54,000
I don't think so.

2200
02:03:54,000 --> 02:03:57,000
They decided that that was why I was in the movement.

2201
02:03:57,000 --> 02:04:00,000
But they didn't say it to me directly.

2202
02:04:00,000 --> 02:04:01,000
I heard it.

2203
02:04:01,000 --> 02:04:02,000
Oh, you heard them talking about that.

2204
02:04:02,000 --> 02:04:03,000
Yeah.

2205
02:04:03,000 --> 02:04:04,000
Yeah.

2206
02:04:04,000 --> 02:04:09,000
And then when I went in to get my photo with the number,

2207
02:04:09,000 --> 02:04:14,000
there were a group of men sitting around in there and they said, girl, where's your daddy?

2208
02:04:14,000 --> 02:04:17,000
And they didn't know that they had found the wrong one.

2209
02:04:17,000 --> 02:04:21,000
And I said, I think you know better than I do.

2210
02:04:21,000 --> 02:04:22,000
Yeah.

2211
02:04:22,000 --> 02:04:27,000
But I didn't know they didn't know which of the Henderson guys was my dad.

2212
02:04:27,000 --> 02:04:31,000
And so I was talking about, oh, I know.

2213
02:04:31,000 --> 02:04:37,000
And I had gone up to see him when he was in jail there to take him ice cream.

2214
02:04:37,000 --> 02:04:42,000
And didn't understand why he didn't want me there.

2215
02:04:42,000 --> 02:04:46,000
He said to my sister, don't bring her back here.

2216
02:04:46,000 --> 02:04:51,000
And I thought, hi, I brought your ice cream.

2217
02:04:51,000 --> 02:04:52,000
And, hmm.

2218
02:04:52,000 --> 02:04:54,000
Why didn't you want to show them?

2219
02:04:54,000 --> 02:04:56,000
It was a gel.

2220
02:04:56,000 --> 02:05:00,000
He didn't want me associated or to be remembered that way.

2221
02:05:00,000 --> 02:05:05,000
And then I went move to California late 79.

2222
02:05:05,000 --> 02:05:11,000
And that was the one person who survived the younger uncle living in California.

2223
02:05:11,000 --> 02:05:13,000
He never came back to Mississippi.

2224
02:05:13,000 --> 02:05:21,000
And one of the reasons I wanted to go to California was to find out from him what actually happened that night.

2225
02:05:21,000 --> 02:05:22,000
Yeah.

2226
02:05:22,000 --> 02:05:23,000
When did he tell you?

2227
02:05:23,000 --> 02:05:24,000
He said, only I know.

2228
02:05:24,000 --> 02:05:26,000
And I will never tell.

2229
02:05:26,000 --> 02:05:28,000
And he cried.

2230
02:05:28,000 --> 02:05:35,000
And my auntie said to me, look after your uncle, he feels responsible for his brother's debts.

2231
02:05:35,000 --> 02:05:36,000
Okay.

2232
02:05:36,000 --> 02:05:42,000
So after he was gone, his wife told me that he had actually done the thing.

2233
02:05:42,000 --> 02:05:47,000
Why did they decide that the other brother would take responsibility?

2234
02:05:47,000 --> 02:05:50,000
I think that was the brother's decision.

2235
02:05:50,000 --> 02:05:53,000
And my uncle at the time was a teenager.

2236
02:05:53,000 --> 02:05:56,000
He was a young guy and somebody, and I don't know who yet.

2237
02:05:56,000 --> 02:05:58,000
I will find out.

2238
02:05:58,000 --> 02:06:00,000
Sent him away to the army.

2239
02:06:00,000 --> 02:06:02,000
That's how he got away.

2240
02:06:02,000 --> 02:06:03,000
Okay.

2241
02:06:03,000 --> 02:06:05,000
Somebody slipped him out of town.

2242
02:06:05,000 --> 02:06:06,000
Yeah.

2243
02:06:06,000 --> 02:06:13,000
But one of the family stories about my uncle is they gave him, he was a trustee in the gel.

2244
02:06:13,000 --> 02:06:19,000
And they gave him $500 to take to the bank just about the time the train was coming through.

2245
02:06:19,000 --> 02:06:24,000
And he took the money to the bank and went back to the jail.

2246
02:06:24,000 --> 02:06:27,000
So he actually could have escaped if he had wanted to.

2247
02:06:27,000 --> 02:06:29,000
He didn't want to.

2248
02:06:29,000 --> 02:06:32,000
I don't know what that was about.

2249
02:06:32,000 --> 02:06:35,000
And it's interesting because he has a son.

2250
02:06:35,000 --> 02:06:38,000
And we have never talked about it.

2251
02:06:38,000 --> 02:06:43,000
His son is maybe a year younger than I am.

2252
02:06:43,000 --> 02:06:45,000
And so you both lost your father?

2253
02:06:45,000 --> 02:06:50,000
Yeah.

2254
02:06:50,000 --> 02:06:57,000
And how do you sneak in the fact that your great-great-grandfather was the slave owner.

2255
02:06:57,000 --> 02:07:05,000
And he found it, he lived with his family, my folks, and found it a school for them.

2256
02:07:05,000 --> 02:07:10,000
In Penoly County until the 50s, there was a Henderson school.

2257
02:07:10,000 --> 02:07:14,000
Where all those little offspring went to school.

2258
02:07:14,000 --> 02:07:17,000
So was this the...

2259
02:07:17,000 --> 02:07:22,000
So he lived with his family, was this the fortress of the war?

2260
02:07:22,000 --> 02:07:25,000
He lived with the Black family?

2261
02:07:25,000 --> 02:07:28,000
Yes.

2262
02:07:28,000 --> 02:07:30,000
And he had...

2263
02:07:30,000 --> 02:07:33,000
And so then did he leave people land?

2264
02:07:33,000 --> 02:07:34,000
I think so.

2265
02:07:34,000 --> 02:07:39,000
I think the farm that they sold when they moved off to Tennessee was his land.

2266
02:07:39,000 --> 02:07:42,000
I need to do more research on it.

2267
02:07:42,000 --> 02:07:45,000
How can you say, yeah, did your family talk about that history at all?

2268
02:07:45,000 --> 02:07:46,000
No.

2269
02:07:46,000 --> 02:07:48,000
So you're on research on it?

2270
02:07:48,000 --> 02:07:49,000
Yeah.

2271
02:07:49,000 --> 02:07:50,000
Yeah.

2272
02:07:50,000 --> 02:07:57,000
Because I didn't know about him until one of my cousins, I'm trying to do the family tree

2273
02:07:57,000 --> 02:08:01,000
and talking about the Black people and the Native people.

2274
02:08:01,000 --> 02:08:03,000
And they said, what about Duncan?

2275
02:08:03,000 --> 02:08:04,000
I said, who?

2276
02:08:04,000 --> 02:08:06,000
Who is Duncan?

2277
02:08:06,000 --> 02:08:09,000
He's your great-great-grandfather.

2278
02:08:09,000 --> 02:08:11,000
How do you know that?

2279
02:08:11,000 --> 02:08:17,000
So I looked up the slave schedule and there he is, Duncan C. Henderson.

2280
02:08:17,000 --> 02:08:19,000
And he owned 13 people.

2281
02:08:19,000 --> 02:08:20,000
It's a dying...

2282
02:08:20,000 --> 02:08:23,000
There are no names, just ages.

2283
02:08:23,000 --> 02:08:26,000
And one of them, presumably, a great-great-grandfather?

2284
02:08:26,000 --> 02:08:27,000
Yes.

2285
02:08:27,000 --> 02:08:28,000
Yes.

2286
02:08:28,000 --> 02:08:32,000
And it took some doing to find her name.

2287
02:08:32,000 --> 02:08:34,000
How did you find your name?

2288
02:08:34,000 --> 02:08:35,000
Yeah.

2289
02:08:35,000 --> 02:08:40,000
Not in the sense of anything, but one of my cousins who was doing a family tree,

2290
02:08:41,000 --> 02:08:46,000
I saw her online, so I sent her a note saying, are you my cousin that I met at my auntie's funeral?

2291
02:08:46,000 --> 02:08:52,000
And she said, yes, I'm the great-great-granddaughter of Classy, Idae Lena.

2292
02:08:52,000 --> 02:08:55,000
I said, that's my grandfather's name.

2293
02:08:55,000 --> 02:08:57,000
We found her name.

2294
02:08:57,000 --> 02:08:58,000
That's exciting.

2295
02:08:58,000 --> 02:08:59,000
It was.

2296
02:08:59,000 --> 02:09:00,000
It was very exciting.

2297
02:09:00,000 --> 02:09:03,000
I had to tell her that the next family reunion.

2298
02:09:03,000 --> 02:09:05,000
Have you looked at the land records going down?

2299
02:09:05,000 --> 02:09:06,000
No, I have not.

2300
02:09:06,000 --> 02:09:07,000
That might be interesting.

2301
02:09:07,000 --> 02:09:08,000
That's true.

2302
02:09:08,000 --> 02:09:10,000
You can look at the transfer.

2303
02:09:10,000 --> 02:09:12,000
My dad is a research looking at the transfer.

2304
02:09:12,000 --> 02:09:13,000
Yeah.

2305
02:09:13,000 --> 02:09:18,000
So you've started with your dad's grandfather?

2306
02:09:18,000 --> 02:09:19,000
Yeah.

2307
02:09:19,000 --> 02:09:20,000
That's grandfather.

2308
02:09:20,000 --> 02:09:22,000
I'll track it back or not, but that would be interesting.

2309
02:09:22,000 --> 02:09:23,000
I think so.

2310
02:09:23,000 --> 02:09:24,000
I think so.

2311
02:09:24,000 --> 02:09:25,000
Yeah.

2312
02:09:25,000 --> 02:09:29,000
Did you participate in Freedom School in summer of 1964?

2313
02:09:29,000 --> 02:09:31,000
Did they have Freedom School?

2314
02:09:31,000 --> 02:09:34,000
I think they did, but I don't know that I participated.

2315
02:09:34,000 --> 02:09:37,000
I don't remember being in Freedom School classes.

2316
02:09:37,000 --> 02:09:43,000
I don't remember our Freedom Schools being as organized

2317
02:09:43,000 --> 02:09:48,000
as they were in other parts of the state.

2318
02:09:48,000 --> 02:09:49,000
No.

2319
02:09:49,000 --> 02:09:52,000
Mm-hmm.

2320
02:09:52,000 --> 02:09:57,000
I'm trying to look at my message.

2321
02:09:57,000 --> 02:09:59,000
So what did I do after all of that?

2322
02:09:59,000 --> 02:10:00,000
Yeah.

2323
02:10:00,000 --> 02:10:01,000
What did you do after all of that?

2324
02:10:01,000 --> 02:10:06,000
After the West Indies, I came back and Florence Tate again

2325
02:10:06,000 --> 02:10:11,000
was trying to keep me working and doing stuff

2326
02:10:11,000 --> 02:10:13,000
that I was supposed to do.

2327
02:10:13,000 --> 02:10:15,000
And of course, I would stray off.

2328
02:10:15,000 --> 02:10:19,000
I took a couple of classes at George Washington University

2329
02:10:19,000 --> 02:10:24,000
because I decided I wanted to be a doctor.

2330
02:10:24,000 --> 02:10:28,000
And I got myself a tutor for chemistry.

2331
02:10:28,000 --> 02:10:30,000
And that didn't last very long.

2332
02:10:30,000 --> 02:10:32,000
And then I quit another job.

2333
02:10:32,000 --> 02:10:37,000
I got another job at Children's Defense Fund of all places.

2334
02:10:37,000 --> 02:10:38,000
Yeah.

2335
02:10:38,000 --> 02:10:41,000
And I think I worked there half day as something.

2336
02:10:41,000 --> 02:10:43,000
I thought, no, this is not me.

2337
02:10:43,000 --> 02:10:45,000
What kind of work was it?

2338
02:10:45,000 --> 02:10:49,000
Secretarial, answering phones.

2339
02:10:49,000 --> 02:10:54,000
Then I worked for if goal for a minute.

2340
02:10:54,000 --> 02:10:57,000
They had an office in Washington.

2341
02:10:58,000 --> 02:11:01,000
Interreligious foundation for community organization.

2342
02:11:01,000 --> 02:11:04,000
They had a people who had been taking packages,

2343
02:11:04,000 --> 02:11:08,000
were taking care packages to Cuba.

2344
02:11:08,000 --> 02:11:10,000
Don't remember the order of that.

2345
02:11:10,000 --> 02:11:13,000
But Florence again called me up at some point and said,

2346
02:11:13,000 --> 02:11:15,000
why Dean, what are you doing?

2347
02:11:15,000 --> 02:11:16,000
Nothing.

2348
02:11:16,000 --> 02:11:18,000
Come to work with me tomorrow.

2349
02:11:18,000 --> 02:11:21,000
I said, okay.

2350
02:11:21,000 --> 02:11:25,000
And I went to work for the National Urban Coalition.

2351
02:11:25,000 --> 02:11:31,000
And the job there was to be a public relations writer.

2352
02:11:31,000 --> 02:11:36,000
And I thought, okay, go and interview so and so, okay.

2353
02:11:36,000 --> 02:11:40,000
And they had a little magazine that I helped with.

2354
02:11:40,000 --> 02:11:43,000
And then I read in the Washington Afro

2355
02:11:43,000 --> 02:11:49,000
that Columbia University had a program for minority journalists.

2356
02:11:49,000 --> 02:11:53,000
And I applied and got accepted.

2357
02:11:54,000 --> 02:12:02,000
So I went off to New York in 1974 to the Michele Clark Fellowship Program at Columbia.

2358
02:12:02,000 --> 02:12:06,000
And became a reporter.

2359
02:12:06,000 --> 02:12:08,000
It was funny because I was too shy.

2360
02:12:08,000 --> 02:12:11,000
And I know you can't see that now.

2361
02:12:11,000 --> 02:12:13,000
I can't see that in the child.

2362
02:12:13,000 --> 02:12:17,000
You're talking about like acting up.

2363
02:12:17,000 --> 02:12:19,000
It was a sneaky shy.

2364
02:12:19,000 --> 02:12:22,000
I walked around with some woman running for governor of New York

2365
02:12:22,000 --> 02:12:25,000
and didn't ask her a single question.

2366
02:12:25,000 --> 02:12:28,000
Walked around with her for hours.

2367
02:12:28,000 --> 02:12:29,000
Yeah.

2368
02:12:29,000 --> 02:12:32,000
And they were like, what are we going to do with her?

2369
02:12:32,000 --> 02:12:34,000
She's not, you know, where were you working?

2370
02:12:34,000 --> 02:12:36,000
I didn't have a job yet.

2371
02:12:36,000 --> 02:12:43,000
I was at Columbia and we were putting out a little weekly paper called Deadline.

2372
02:12:43,000 --> 02:12:48,000
And so they sent for Earl Caldwell,

2373
02:12:48,000 --> 02:12:51,000
the guy that met on the poor people's campaign.

2374
02:12:51,000 --> 02:12:53,000
So you better come over here.

2375
02:12:53,000 --> 02:12:55,000
Rodin is not participating.

2376
02:12:55,000 --> 02:12:58,000
I was kind of participating, but not really.

2377
02:12:58,000 --> 02:13:01,000
And Earl had me calling people on the phone, taking notes.

2378
02:13:01,000 --> 02:13:07,000
And then he would put the note, I would have to call him back if I didn't write down everything he thought I should write.

2379
02:13:07,000 --> 02:13:10,000
And it was like, okay, drive me crazy.

2380
02:13:10,000 --> 02:13:14,000
And then I was assigned to go to the prison

2381
02:13:14,000 --> 02:13:22,000
and to interview a man who had been imprisoned in North Carolina.

2382
02:13:22,000 --> 02:13:25,000
I think he was sentenced to life or something.

2383
02:13:25,000 --> 02:13:27,000
And they let the prisoners out to fight a fire.

2384
02:13:27,000 --> 02:13:29,000
And he hit the tracks.

2385
02:13:29,000 --> 02:13:30,000
Ran away.

2386
02:13:30,000 --> 02:13:32,000
Yeah, he ran away.

2387
02:13:32,000 --> 02:13:34,000
Went to New York, was in a car accident.

2388
02:13:34,000 --> 02:13:36,000
That's how they got him again.

2389
02:13:36,000 --> 02:13:41,000
And I went to interview him and wrote a story about his life.

2390
02:13:41,000 --> 02:13:42,000
It was interesting to me.

2391
02:13:42,000 --> 02:13:45,000
And he was like, you know, I'm just like a club, you know.

2392
02:13:45,000 --> 02:13:52,000
I'm just like, I'm just like, you know, I'm just like, you know, I'm just like, you know, I'm just like, you know, I'm just like a club, you know.

2393
02:13:52,000 --> 02:13:56,000
And then I, that was the one story I really liked.

2394
02:13:56,000 --> 02:14:02,000
Then I went to the Newport Jazz Festival.

2395
02:14:02,000 --> 02:14:08,000
And went to talk to one of the old musicians because I knew nothing about it.

2396
02:14:08,000 --> 02:14:10,000
And he told me about the various people.

2397
02:14:10,000 --> 02:14:13,000
And I wrote about Cafe Society.

2398
02:14:13,000 --> 02:14:23,000
And then I went off to my first newspaper job at the end of the summer in Mount Vernon, New York, working for the Daily Argus.

2399
02:14:23,000 --> 02:14:25,000
Yeah.

2400
02:14:25,000 --> 02:14:27,000
And I was a little scared.

2401
02:14:27,000 --> 02:14:31,000
The first story was of a kid who had, the elevator was broken.

2402
02:14:31,000 --> 02:14:37,000
And she stuck her head through the glass to see what it was and was decapitated.

2403
02:14:37,000 --> 02:14:40,000
Yeah, that was my first story.

2404
02:14:40,000 --> 02:14:41,000
Oh, wow.

2405
02:14:41,000 --> 02:14:43,000
First story was front page, huh?

2406
02:14:43,000 --> 02:14:45,000
Yeah.

2407
02:14:45,000 --> 02:14:48,000
And I did the newspaper stuff for 28 years.

2408
02:14:48,000 --> 02:14:50,000
So I guess you found what you liked?

2409
02:14:50,000 --> 02:14:51,000
I loved it.

2410
02:14:51,000 --> 02:14:53,000
What can I tell you?

2411
02:14:53,000 --> 02:14:54,000
That's great.

2412
02:14:54,000 --> 02:15:02,000
How do you think your involvement in the movement, shape the person you did it?

2413
02:15:02,000 --> 02:15:07,000
I think it was the movement and the family.

2414
02:15:07,000 --> 02:15:09,000
Because my family was pretty strong.

2415
02:15:09,000 --> 02:15:10,000
Uh-huh.

2416
02:15:10,000 --> 02:15:13,000
My grandmother teaching in her little school.

2417
02:15:13,000 --> 02:15:16,000
My grandfather, we never mentioned him too much.

2418
02:15:16,000 --> 02:15:18,000
But I hung out with him.

2419
02:15:18,000 --> 02:15:24,000
He was the person who people came to see when they were ill and didn't go to the normal doctor.

2420
02:15:24,000 --> 02:15:27,000
He made medicine.

2421
02:15:27,000 --> 02:15:29,000
And a farmer.

2422
02:15:29,000 --> 02:15:31,000
He was a farmer and he made medicine.

2423
02:15:31,000 --> 02:15:34,000
Uh-huh.

2424
02:15:34,000 --> 02:15:36,000
He wanted me to be a lawyer.

2425
02:15:36,000 --> 02:15:39,000
And at some point I said I was going to do that.

2426
02:15:39,000 --> 02:15:40,000
But I didn't.

2427
02:15:40,000 --> 02:15:42,000
I didn't really want to do that.

2428
02:15:42,000 --> 02:15:43,000
You know?

2429
02:15:43,000 --> 02:15:44,000
Yeah.

2430
02:15:44,000 --> 02:15:47,000
I wish I had learned more about herbs from him.

2431
02:15:47,000 --> 02:15:48,000
Uh-huh.

2432
02:15:48,000 --> 02:15:49,000
I didn't.

2433
02:15:49,000 --> 02:15:52,000
So now I study on my own.

2434
02:15:52,000 --> 02:15:54,000
The movement.

2435
02:15:54,000 --> 02:15:57,000
I'm still in touch with some of the people like Charlie and Frank.

2436
02:15:57,000 --> 02:15:59,000
I don't see him every day.

2437
02:15:59,000 --> 02:16:00,000
And that often.

2438
02:16:00,000 --> 02:16:03,000
But I have to check in on him every now and then.

2439
02:16:03,000 --> 02:16:06,000
Gene Wheeler Smith is young.

2440
02:16:06,000 --> 02:16:08,000
He's in my neighborhood.

2441
02:16:08,000 --> 02:16:11,000
So occasionally we will connect again.

2442
02:16:11,000 --> 02:16:13,000
Yeah, the movement is us.

2443
02:16:13,000 --> 02:16:16,000
And it is a part of my life still.

2444
02:16:16,000 --> 02:16:20,000
What do you think it's important for people to know about the movement?

2445
02:16:20,000 --> 02:16:26,000
That at a time when it was really dangerous in the United States that young people stood

2446
02:16:26,000 --> 02:16:29,000
up to power in this country.

2447
02:16:29,000 --> 02:16:33,000
And like they are doing now pretty much.

2448
02:16:33,000 --> 02:16:35,000
And that you can do it.

2449
02:16:35,000 --> 02:16:37,000
And yes, you lose a few on the way.

2450
02:16:37,000 --> 02:16:39,000
But you can't let it stop you.

2451
02:16:39,000 --> 02:16:40,000
Yeah.

2452
02:16:40,000 --> 02:16:45,000
Can you think of other things that I haven't asked you about?

2453
02:16:46,000 --> 02:16:47,000
No.

2454
02:16:47,000 --> 02:16:51,000
What didn't you ask me about?

2455
02:16:51,000 --> 02:16:53,000
Spiritual stuff.

2456
02:16:53,000 --> 02:16:56,000
And how I left church as soon as I turned.

2457
02:16:56,000 --> 02:16:58,000
18.

2458
02:16:58,000 --> 02:17:00,000
Yes, I did.

2459
02:17:00,000 --> 02:17:02,000
I didn't play the piano anymore.

2460
02:17:02,000 --> 02:17:04,000
I have a piano now.

2461
02:17:04,000 --> 02:17:08,000
But I stopped playing at church.

2462
02:17:08,000 --> 02:17:11,000
I stopped going to church.

2463
02:17:12,000 --> 02:17:16,000
And I think one of my favorite things was I come not to bring peace but a sword.

2464
02:17:16,000 --> 02:17:18,000
It's time for us to fight.

2465
02:17:18,000 --> 02:17:21,000
You know?

2466
02:17:21,000 --> 02:17:23,000
That was before I went to prison.

2467
02:17:23,000 --> 02:17:27,000
State prison, Mississippi, parchment, overnight.

2468
02:17:27,000 --> 02:17:32,000
We were awful.

2469
02:17:32,000 --> 02:17:39,000
In Rosedale, the churches were afraid to open their doors for movement meetings.

2470
02:17:39,000 --> 02:17:42,000
So we decided we were going to meet on the steps of the church.

2471
02:17:42,000 --> 02:17:47,000
And we had a little rally on the steps of the church.

2472
02:17:47,000 --> 02:17:50,000
And I don't remember what the issue was at the time.

2473
02:17:50,000 --> 02:17:55,000
But when people left, as we were leaving, most people had gone already.

2474
02:17:55,000 --> 02:18:00,000
Maybe 10 or 11 of us were left behind talking about what our next move should be

2475
02:18:00,000 --> 02:18:03,000
and how we can get the churches to open their doors.

2476
02:18:03,000 --> 02:18:07,000
These people jumped out of the bushes with their high-powered rifles.

2477
02:18:08,000 --> 02:18:13,000
And marched us off to jail, which was right there, a block away, a half block.

2478
02:18:13,000 --> 02:18:17,000
Processed us because they wanted to know who was in their town.

2479
02:18:17,000 --> 02:18:22,000
And then after they got all our names and addresses and all of that,

2480
02:18:22,000 --> 02:18:25,000
they took us off to parchment.

2481
02:18:25,000 --> 02:18:28,000
Parchment, prison.

2482
02:18:28,000 --> 02:18:30,000
That scared me.

2483
02:18:30,000 --> 02:18:33,000
But we couldn't let scared show.

2484
02:18:33,000 --> 02:18:35,000
And I remember they took the men off the bus.

2485
02:18:35,000 --> 02:18:38,000
I don't remember how many men were on there.

2486
02:18:38,000 --> 02:18:40,000
And left just the women.

2487
02:18:40,000 --> 02:18:43,000
And we got our courage up by cursing.

2488
02:18:43,000 --> 02:18:47,000
You touched them?

2489
02:18:47,000 --> 02:18:48,000
Oh, yeah.

2490
02:18:48,000 --> 02:18:51,000
And then they brought in a trustee woman.

2491
02:18:51,000 --> 02:18:52,000
We had to strip.

2492
02:18:52,000 --> 02:18:58,000
They stripped, searched us, and gave us only back our top clothes.

2493
02:18:58,000 --> 02:19:06,000
And put us in cells for women to a cell with two still bunk beds still.

2494
02:19:06,000 --> 02:19:07,000
And I don't know.

2495
02:19:07,000 --> 02:19:14,000
Maybe we were there for two or three hours before they came around with the big jar of stuff for us to drink.

2496
02:19:14,000 --> 02:19:16,000
I don't know what it was.

2497
02:19:16,000 --> 02:19:21,000
But immediately after you drank it, you have to use the toilet.

2498
02:19:21,000 --> 02:19:23,000
There's one toilet for four women.

2499
02:19:23,000 --> 02:19:26,000
It was ridiculous.

2500
02:19:26,000 --> 02:19:31,000
After that, maybe an hour or so later, they put us back on the bus

2501
02:19:31,000 --> 02:19:36,000
and took us back to Bolivar County to Cleveland, not Rosedale.

2502
02:19:36,000 --> 02:19:40,000
And then from Cleveland, we went back to Rosedale.

2503
02:19:40,000 --> 02:19:43,000
And then I think the Delta Ministry had bailed us out or something.

2504
02:19:43,000 --> 02:19:46,000
And I ran across the road to the house where I was staying.

2505
02:19:46,000 --> 02:19:48,000
But sick.

2506
02:19:48,000 --> 02:19:49,000
They gave us something to drink.

2507
02:19:49,000 --> 02:19:51,000
I wish I knew what.

2508
02:19:51,000 --> 02:19:53,000
Did you do that with everybody?

2509
02:19:53,000 --> 02:19:54,000
Yeah.

2510
02:19:55,000 --> 02:20:00,000
Well, I don't, I mean, all of the people who were arrested in that group, yes.

2511
02:20:00,000 --> 02:20:01,000
Yeah.

2512
02:20:01,000 --> 02:20:08,000
Martin Thomas, who had been one of the white guys from Boston, didn't get out immediately.

2513
02:20:08,000 --> 02:20:11,000
He was in Cleveland.

2514
02:20:11,000 --> 02:20:13,000
And they beat him fiercely.

2515
02:20:13,000 --> 02:20:15,000
The other prisoners.

2516
02:20:15,000 --> 02:20:18,000
He came out looking really, really bad.

2517
02:20:18,000 --> 02:20:23,000
I mean, even his ears were bashed.

2518
02:20:23,000 --> 02:20:29,000
And I think his dad sent for him after that and he had to go home.

2519
02:20:29,000 --> 02:20:33,000
Did that intimidation all that experience that it's what you know?

2520
02:20:33,000 --> 02:20:34,000
No.

2521
02:20:34,000 --> 02:20:36,000
I decided I wouldn't go back to jail.

2522
02:20:36,000 --> 02:20:40,000
And I said, you shouldn't tell this, but I had put a little pistol in my purse.

2523
02:20:40,000 --> 02:20:42,000
Although I couldn't shoot it.

2524
02:20:42,000 --> 02:20:44,000
Didn't know how to shoot it.

2525
02:20:44,000 --> 02:20:46,000
But you're still packing.

2526
02:20:46,000 --> 02:20:49,000
I was packing here.

2527
02:20:49,000 --> 02:20:50,000
Yeah.

2528
02:20:50,000 --> 02:20:51,000
No.

2529
02:20:51,000 --> 02:20:56,000
And if I had, I probably would have thrown it at somebody.

2530
02:20:56,000 --> 02:20:58,000
For him, that's all.

2531
02:20:58,000 --> 02:21:00,000
That's right.

2532
02:21:00,000 --> 02:21:03,000
But you better be off carrying this off.

2533
02:21:03,000 --> 02:21:04,000
That's true.

2534
02:21:04,000 --> 02:21:05,000
That's true.

2535
02:21:05,000 --> 02:21:07,000
Other other thing?

2536
02:21:07,000 --> 02:21:11,000
No, I can't think of anything.

2537
02:21:11,000 --> 02:21:17,000
I used to give my little sister, my younger sister is 12 years younger than I am.

2538
02:21:17,000 --> 02:21:20,000
And I was sneak little buttons onto her clothes.

2539
02:21:20,000 --> 02:21:23,000
I said, put this on when we get to town.

2540
02:21:23,000 --> 02:21:26,000
Did your sister be a walking billboard?

2541
02:21:26,000 --> 02:21:27,000
Yeah.

2542
02:21:27,000 --> 02:21:29,000
Did she put she in?

2543
02:21:29,000 --> 02:21:31,000
She was too young to know.

2544
02:21:31,000 --> 02:21:34,000
She was too young to know anything.

2545
02:21:34,000 --> 02:21:39,000
If I was 16, she was four.

2546
02:21:39,000 --> 02:21:41,000
Had no clue.

2547
02:21:41,000 --> 02:21:43,000
Freedom now.

2548
02:21:43,000 --> 02:21:44,000
That's right.

2549
02:21:44,000 --> 02:21:47,000
I didn't have a little hand stuck up.

2550
02:21:47,000 --> 02:21:50,000
We started doing that.

2551
02:21:50,000 --> 02:21:53,000
What about the marriage march?

2552
02:21:53,000 --> 02:21:56,000
I didn't do a lot on the marriage march.

2553
02:21:56,000 --> 02:21:58,000
I did go.

2554
02:21:58,000 --> 02:22:01,000
Oh, that's a terrible story.

2555
02:22:01,000 --> 02:22:05,000
A doctor came from Detroit to help out the marches.

2556
02:22:05,000 --> 02:22:10,000
And he kept talking about the poor downed rotten people of Mississippi.

2557
02:22:10,000 --> 02:22:14,000
I went to the marches, but I had to go home first to see my mother.

2558
02:22:14,000 --> 02:22:17,000
Because the marches were nearby.

2559
02:22:17,000 --> 02:22:22,000
And he was saying that poor downed rotten new grows.

2560
02:22:22,000 --> 02:22:28,000
And people burned rags at home to keep the mosquitoes away.

2561
02:22:28,000 --> 02:22:34,000
We were driving down one of the little streets in baseball, and I would stop the car.

2562
02:22:34,000 --> 02:22:38,000
And I went and jumped up and down on somebody's burning a rag.

2563
02:22:38,000 --> 02:22:48,000
Molotov cocktail.

2564
02:22:48,000 --> 02:22:50,000
I said what that poor man.

2565
02:22:50,000 --> 02:22:51,000
Yes.

2566
02:22:51,000 --> 02:22:53,000
And then we dropped him off at the marches.

2567
02:22:53,000 --> 02:22:55,000
They were in, I don't know where they were.

2568
02:22:55,000 --> 02:22:57,000
Pope was someplace.

2569
02:22:57,000 --> 02:23:00,000
And noticed that somebody was following us.

2570
02:23:00,000 --> 02:23:03,000
So I stopped at my sister's restaurant.

2571
02:23:03,000 --> 02:23:06,000
A little sister said somebody's following us.

2572
02:23:06,000 --> 02:23:09,000
She gave me a 38 and put some bullets in it.

2573
02:23:09,000 --> 02:23:13,000
I said, right, facing the back window of the car.

2574
02:23:13,000 --> 02:23:16,000
They get too close to the car, shoot out the back window.

2575
02:23:16,000 --> 02:23:18,000
We can replace that.

2576
02:23:18,000 --> 02:23:19,000
I said okay.

2577
02:23:19,000 --> 02:23:23,000
And I put the gun in my purse and we went back to Jackson.

2578
02:23:23,000 --> 02:23:24,000
Nothing happened.

2579
02:23:24,000 --> 02:23:30,000
I guess they figured as much because the car stopped following us.

2580
02:23:30,000 --> 02:23:33,000
Were you in Greenwood when Stokely Carmichael made you?

2581
02:23:33,000 --> 02:23:35,000
Yes, I was actually.

2582
02:23:35,000 --> 02:23:37,000
Yes, I was there.

2583
02:23:37,000 --> 02:23:40,000
But I had just gone up for the day.

2584
02:23:40,000 --> 02:23:42,000
I didn't march.

2585
02:23:42,000 --> 02:23:43,000
We went up.

2586
02:23:43,000 --> 02:23:45,000
I told you I was sick of the marches.

2587
02:23:45,000 --> 02:23:47,000
And I heard the speech.

2588
02:23:47,000 --> 02:23:49,000
I heard Rick's first.

2589
02:23:49,000 --> 02:23:53,000
And I had been at the SNCC meeting when Stokely Carmichael was elected.

2590
02:23:53,000 --> 02:23:54,000
You know?

2591
02:23:54,000 --> 02:23:55,000
In Nashville?

2592
02:23:55,000 --> 02:23:56,000
You there, you.

2593
02:23:56,000 --> 02:23:59,000
Uh-huh.

2594
02:23:59,000 --> 02:24:02,000
And I didn't think a lot of it at the time.

2595
02:24:02,000 --> 02:24:05,000
I didn't know why it became such a big deal later.

2596
02:24:05,000 --> 02:24:07,000
Then I understood it a little later on.

2597
02:24:07,000 --> 02:24:08,000
It took me a minute.

2598
02:24:08,000 --> 02:24:09,000
But we left the march.

2599
02:24:09,000 --> 02:24:14,000
I left with Frank and Jean again and we went into Greenville for something.

2600
02:24:14,000 --> 02:24:17,000
And then we came back to Jackson.

2601
02:24:17,000 --> 02:24:20,000
And I went to the rally in Jackson.

2602
02:24:20,000 --> 02:24:23,000
What did you think when Stokely Carmichael made his speech at the time?

2603
02:24:23,000 --> 02:24:26,000
What did you think about the idea of black power?

2604
02:24:26,000 --> 02:24:28,000
I thought it was necessary.

2605
02:24:28,000 --> 02:24:30,000
I didn't think that was so far fetched.

2606
02:24:30,000 --> 02:24:31,000
You know?

2607
02:24:31,000 --> 02:24:32,000
That was how we started.

2608
02:24:32,000 --> 02:24:35,000
I think it, what we didn't call it, black power.

2609
02:24:35,000 --> 02:24:41,000
But that black people needed to mobilize and do things for themselves.

2610
02:24:41,000 --> 02:24:43,000
So I thought that was right on the money.

2611
02:24:43,000 --> 02:24:45,000
I was surprised that it turned off so many people.

2612
02:24:45,000 --> 02:24:46,000
You know?

2613
02:24:46,000 --> 02:24:47,000
What do you mean?

2614
02:24:47,000 --> 02:24:48,000
Mm-hmm.

2615
02:24:48,000 --> 02:24:50,000
Mm-hmm.

2616
02:24:50,000 --> 02:24:56,000
Um, by then the Deacons for Defense and Justice had unveiled themselves.

2617
02:24:56,000 --> 02:24:59,000
And I think on that Meredith March.

2618
02:24:59,000 --> 02:25:02,000
I don't know if anybody is going to be mad at me.

2619
02:25:02,000 --> 02:25:03,000
I don't care.

2620
02:25:03,000 --> 02:25:06,000
People were walking around armed.

2621
02:25:06,000 --> 02:25:07,000
Uh-huh.

2622
02:25:07,000 --> 02:25:09,000
Making sure that everything was okay.

2623
02:25:09,000 --> 02:25:12,000
Not flunting weapons but being armed anyway.

2624
02:25:12,000 --> 02:25:13,000
Mm-hmm.

2625
02:25:13,000 --> 02:25:16,000
Did that make you feel safer?

2626
02:25:16,000 --> 02:25:17,000
I didn't feel unsafe.

2627
02:25:17,000 --> 02:25:21,000
I guess I'm just, you know, I didn't feel unsafe.

2628
02:25:21,000 --> 02:25:23,000
Yeah.

2629
02:25:26,000 --> 02:25:28,000
Can you explain to me?

2630
02:25:28,000 --> 02:25:29,000
No.

2631
02:25:29,000 --> 02:25:31,000
I went, while I was in school, Ben.

2632
02:25:31,000 --> 02:25:35,000
The one who wanted me to act more like a girl, uh, was killed.

2633
02:25:35,000 --> 02:25:37,000
And I saw that on TV.

2634
02:25:37,000 --> 02:25:41,000
And kind of lost it briefly.

2635
02:25:41,000 --> 02:25:47,000
Um, somebody sent me a ticket to come home and I went down for the funeral.

2636
02:25:47,000 --> 02:25:49,000
And thought, what a waste.

2637
02:25:49,000 --> 02:25:51,000
You know, how did that happen?

2638
02:25:51,000 --> 02:25:53,000
And then I went back to college.

2639
02:25:53,000 --> 02:25:56,000
Who didn't get in touch with this family or anything.

2640
02:25:56,000 --> 02:25:59,000
And how was he killed?

2641
02:25:59,000 --> 02:26:01,000
The police officers saw him.

2642
02:26:01,000 --> 02:26:05,000
He had gone to a restaurant to get a sandwich for his wife or something.

2643
02:26:05,000 --> 02:26:10,000
And they recognized him from the old days and killed him.

2644
02:26:10,000 --> 02:26:13,000
That was what we were told.

2645
02:26:13,000 --> 02:26:14,000
Yeah.

2646
02:26:14,000 --> 02:26:16,000
There was a demonstration over in Jackson State, right?

2647
02:26:16,000 --> 02:26:17,000
Yeah.

2648
02:26:17,000 --> 02:26:19,000
The police were going to campus.

2649
02:26:19,000 --> 02:26:20,000
Mm-hmm.

2650
02:26:20,000 --> 02:26:21,000
And Ben wasn't on campus.

2651
02:26:21,000 --> 02:26:24,000
He wasn't a college student.

2652
02:26:24,000 --> 02:26:31,000
He had been married probably less than a year.

2653
02:26:31,000 --> 02:26:34,000
I think he was staying with his mom and trying to get a job

2654
02:26:34,000 --> 02:26:41,000
of working some non-movement job.

2655
02:26:41,000 --> 02:26:43,000
Yeah, that was kind of a...

2656
02:26:43,000 --> 02:26:44,000
He's been lost.

2657
02:26:44,000 --> 02:26:47,000
Yeah, I mean, I just emotionally.

2658
02:26:47,000 --> 02:26:49,000
I don't know how.

2659
02:26:49,000 --> 02:26:51,000
How can you do that?

2660
02:26:51,000 --> 02:26:54,000
I'm trying to get a job on the plantations,

2661
02:26:54,000 --> 02:26:57,000
trying to organize farm workers and nothing happens.

2662
02:26:57,000 --> 02:26:58,000
You know?

2663
02:26:58,000 --> 02:27:00,000
We knew how to run.

2664
02:27:00,000 --> 02:27:02,000
If you don't know somebody who's saving it,

2665
02:27:02,000 --> 02:27:04,000
you don't know how to run.

2666
02:27:04,000 --> 02:27:05,000
You know?

2667
02:27:05,000 --> 02:27:08,000
He didn't have a chance.

2668
02:27:08,000 --> 02:27:09,000
Yeah.

2669
02:27:09,000 --> 02:27:11,000
Yeah, and final thoughts?

2670
02:27:11,000 --> 02:27:12,000
No.

2671
02:27:12,000 --> 02:27:15,000
Except it's kind of scary now.

2672
02:27:15,000 --> 02:27:19,000
And we had better figure out how to mobilize ourselves again.

2673
02:27:20,000 --> 02:27:25,000
What do you think of the current work?

2674
02:27:25,000 --> 02:27:28,000
Actually, and this is terrible,

2675
02:27:28,000 --> 02:27:31,000
but I try not to pay attention.

2676
02:27:31,000 --> 02:27:33,000
I try not to pay attention.

2677
02:27:33,000 --> 02:27:34,000
It's too painful.

2678
02:27:34,000 --> 02:27:37,000
Like, why are we going through this again?

2679
02:27:37,000 --> 02:27:38,000
Yeah.

2680
02:27:38,000 --> 02:27:39,000
Mm-hmm.

2681
02:27:39,000 --> 02:27:43,000
At home, and I'm hopefully we'll go later this month

2682
02:27:43,000 --> 02:27:46,000
to see my family.

2683
02:27:47,000 --> 02:27:51,000
One of my nephews is a deputy sheriff in Batesville.

2684
02:27:51,000 --> 02:27:53,000
And I thought, oh my goodness.

2685
02:27:53,000 --> 02:27:54,000
Okay.

2686
02:27:54,000 --> 02:27:56,000
But he also is a preacher.

2687
02:27:56,000 --> 02:28:00,000
So do you feel like you had something to do

2688
02:28:00,000 --> 02:28:04,000
with the impossible for him to be a deputy?

2689
02:28:04,000 --> 02:28:05,000
Probably.

2690
02:28:05,000 --> 02:28:07,000
And one of the things I used to do,

2691
02:28:07,000 --> 02:28:09,000
and he talked to me about it,

2692
02:28:09,000 --> 02:28:11,000
as I used to take books home for them,

2693
02:28:11,000 --> 02:28:13,000
my nieces and nephews.

2694
02:28:13,000 --> 02:28:15,000
That's what they got for Christmas.

2695
02:28:15,000 --> 02:28:17,000
And that was their Christmas present.

2696
02:28:17,000 --> 02:28:19,000
You got to know where you came from.

2697
02:28:19,000 --> 02:28:22,000
And he said he would try so hard to read those books.

2698
02:28:22,000 --> 02:28:25,000
Yeah.

2699
02:28:25,000 --> 02:28:28,000
Would you have any advice for the young people

2700
02:28:28,000 --> 02:28:30,000
who are living in today's movement?

2701
02:28:30,000 --> 02:28:31,000
I wish I did.

2702
02:28:31,000 --> 02:28:32,000
I do not.

2703
02:28:32,000 --> 02:28:35,000
Because I don't know.

2704
02:28:35,000 --> 02:28:36,000
It's so weird now.

2705
02:28:36,000 --> 02:28:40,000
You know, if you listen to Mr. Trump,

2706
02:28:40,000 --> 02:28:43,000
and all of the stuff that comes out of his mouth

2707
02:28:43,000 --> 02:28:45,000
is, oh, what if you come to Trump?

2708
02:28:45,000 --> 02:28:47,000
What is this?

2709
02:28:47,000 --> 02:28:50,000
And it's scary to me.

2710
02:28:50,000 --> 02:28:54,000
Because at least then we had a close knit community.

2711
02:28:54,000 --> 02:28:56,000
Now we're scattered.

2712
02:28:56,000 --> 02:28:58,000
You know what I mean?

2713
02:28:58,000 --> 02:29:00,000
Yeah.

2714
02:29:00,000 --> 02:29:01,000
So how do you...

2715
02:29:01,000 --> 02:29:04,000
I guess you cannot do it across racial lines.

2716
02:29:04,000 --> 02:29:08,000
You have to be with people who like-minded people.

2717
02:29:08,000 --> 02:29:10,000
Mm-hmm.

2718
02:29:10,000 --> 02:29:13,000
I hope I didn't talk to you at Europe.

2719
02:29:13,000 --> 02:29:15,000
And if you come up with questions later,

2720
02:29:15,000 --> 02:29:17,000
you can always call me.

2721
02:29:17,000 --> 02:29:18,000
I will.

2722
02:29:18,000 --> 02:29:19,000
Okay.

2723
02:29:19,000 --> 02:29:22,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress

2724
02:29:22,000 --> 02:29:25,000
and the Smithsonian National Museum

2725
02:29:25,000 --> 02:29:28,000
of African American History and Culture.

